<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Rejects World Series Statue Bet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The World Series statue bet envisioned by  
Georgia's governor and Atlanta's mayor fell apart Friday when New 
York's governor refused to go along. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Roy Barnes and Mayor Bill Campbell offered to put a New  
York Yankees cap and jersey on the statue of former President Jimmy 
Carter at the Georgia Capitol the day after any World Series game 
won by the Yankees. In return, they wanted New York to put an 
Atlanta Braves cap and jersey on Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman's 
statue outside New York City's Plaza Hotel for every game won by 
the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael McKeon, a spokesman for New York Gov. George Pataki,  
called the idea ridiculous. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were a little surprised that Georgia didn't care about  
disrespecting a former president,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McKeon left open the way for a more lighthearted bet along the  
lines of the ribs and Italian ices Pataki wagered against Barnes' 
peanuts and grits during the National League Championship Series, 
when the Braves defeated the New York Mets 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd love to work out a bet because we clearly believe the  
Yankees are going to crush the Braves,'' McKeon said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
