<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Lawyers Appeal Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet launched an  
appeal today of a magistrate's ruling that the former Chilean 
dictator should be extradited to Spain to face charges of torture. 
</P>
<P>
	The formal notice that Pinochet would challenge the decision was  
submitted to the High Court on the final day of the 15-day window 
for filing. The court now must set a date to hear the appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Caplan, Pinochet's lead lawyer, would not say on what  
grounds the 83-year-old general was seeking to overturn the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pinochet's attorneys are expected to argue that it would be  
``unjust or oppressive'' to send Pinochet to Spain. They also might 
claim that the Spanish case was brought in bad faith and is 
politically motivated, or that too much time elapsed between the 
acts alleged and Pinochet's arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon has accused Pinochet of  
masterminding a campaign of terror against political opponents 
during his 17-year regime in Chile. He has been detained in Britain 
since Oct. 16, 1998, when he was arrested while recovering from 
spinal surgery at a London hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	An official Chilean government report has acknowledged that  
3,197 people died or disappeared after Pinochet toppled Chile's 
elected Marxist president Salvador Allende in a bloody 1973 coup. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet relinquished power in 1990 and became a senator for  
life. He is protected from prosecution at home by an amnesty law he 
helped pass. 
</P>
<P>
	After a long round of legal battles, the case finally proceeded  
to a formal extradition hearing last month in which Deputy Chief 
Magistrate Ronald Bartle ruled that Spain's 34 charges of torture 
and a single allegation of conspiracy to torture constituted 
extraditable crimes and that, even though none of the alleged 
victims were Spanish, Spain had authority to try the general. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to appeal Bartle's ruling could mean Pinochet will  
spend many more months, if not years, fighting extradition in the 
British courts. 
</P>
<P>
	If he loses this appeal, he could be allowed to lodge a  
challenge in Britain's highest court of appeals, the House of 
Lords. If that fails and all his legal options are exhausted, the 
case would return for a final ruling to Home Secretary Jack Straw, 
who in addition to legal issues could consider political and 
humanitarian concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet's doctor has disclosed that the general suffered two  
small strokes this fall and continues to be plagued by dizziness 
and short-term memory loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain said this week that if Straw ruled that Pinochet could  
return to Chile, the Spanish courts would not appeal because they 
would recognize it as a political, not a judicial, ruling. If Straw 
rules against Pinochet, he again could appeal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
