<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Bonds Edge Higher / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term Treasury bonds edged higher but  
shorter-term government securities ended largely unchanged Friday 
after the Federal Reserve announced a measure to soothe concerns 
over the Year 2000 computer glitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1/8 point,  
or $1.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, slipped to 6.34 percent from 6.35 percent late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve said it would expand the types of collateral  
it exchanges for loans to commercial banks, in an effort to 
mitigate any possible disruptions in supply from Y2K computer 
failures. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was mostly symbolic, since healthy banks usually don't  
resort to directly borrowing money from the 12 regional Fed 
branches. The Fed has already taken more important steps to head 
off cash shortages that some fear might be seen nearer the 
millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	But the market optimism created by the move helped insulate  
fixed-income securities against a flight of capital into a rallying 
stock market Friday. Stocks rose sharply, led by financial shares, 
capping a comeback this week that wiped out much of last week's 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to down 1/32 point, and intermediate maturities were 
unchanged, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.05 percent as the  
discount fell 0.05 percentage point to 4.92 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.26 percent, as the discount rose 0.01 percentage 
point to 5.05 percent. One-year yields were 5.47 percent as the 
discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 5.18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.06 from 5.25 percent on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 point to 108 17/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 6.14 percent from 6.13 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
