<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush-Bashing Biographer Had Secret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The biographer who accused GOP presidential  
front-runner George W. Bush of burying a cocaine arrest apparently 
had a secret of his own: a 1988 conviction for plotting to murder a 
co-worker. 
</P>
<P>
	The disclosure about James Howard Hatfield prompted his  
publisher on Thursday to suspend sales, shipment and promotion of 
the new book, ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the Making of an 
American President.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield was still on parole from a 15-year prison term while  
writing his book on the Texas governor, and also did time for 
embezzlement, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to reach Hatfield through his publisher, St. Martin's  
Press, were unsuccessful. The publisher did not return calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign has its legal staff reviewing the matter for  
possible libel implications, spokeswoman Karen Hughes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield alleged that Bush was arrested in 1972 for cocaine  
possession but did only community service after his father, former 
President Bush, intervened. The arrest record was later expunged at 
the request of the elder Bush, the book alleged. Hatfield cited 
three anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious (the book) was not checked,'' Ms. Hughes said  
Friday. The Texas governor previously ripped the book as ``science 
fiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book was due out in January 2000 but was released early  
after the manuscript arrived with the cocaine story. The publisher 
said 70,000 copies are already in stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Barnes &AMP; Noble and Amazon.com said they will keep selling  
the book. It was already in Amazon's top 50 best sellers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Morning News first reported Hatfield's criminal  
background on Thursday. Hatfield, 41, told the newspaper it was a 
case of mistaken identity. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Friday, a Dallas lawyer, Norman L. ``Happy'' Nelson Jr.,  
said that the author and the convict are one and the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson, who knew Hatfield for about nine years before the 1988  
conviction, said he was stunned to see Hatfield's picture in the 
newspaper as the Bush biographer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The picture in the paper was the picture of the bomber,''  
Nelson said. ``That was him. I quite frankly didn't like him 
denying that he had a record, when I knew he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glen Castlebury, spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal  
Justice, confirmed that a James Howard Hatfield was arrested in 
1987 for solicitation of murder -- hiring a hit man to plant a bomb 
under a co-worker's car. 
</P>
<P>
	After he was found guilty, Hatfield went to prison in 1988 and  
spent the next five years there. Upon his release, Hatfield was 
turned over to federal authorities; he wound up doing a short 
stretch in El Reno, Okla., for embezzling nearly $35,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While prison authorities would not provide details, Nelson said  
that Hatfield had tried to kill a co-worker when she suspected him 
of embezzling federal Housing and Urban Development funds. The 
woman later testified against Hatfield in the embezzlement case, 
Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb planted beneath the co-worker's car only partially  
detonated, and she escaped serious injury, Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield, who moved to Arkansas with the approval of Texas  
authorities, remains on parole through April 15, 2003, Castlebury 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to his official biography, Hatfield was ``a syndicated  
columnist, free-lance Texas journalist and frequent contributor to 
several Lone Star State newspapers and magazines.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
