<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 00:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Glavine Pitching Game 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Tom Glavine was hardly overwhelmed by the honor  
of pitching Game 1 in the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time Cy Young winner struggled much of the season for  
the Atlanta Braves and finished with his highest ERA (4.12) since 
1990. But he will be on the mound Saturday night against the New 
York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like I'm the ace or anything,'' Glavine said. ``It  
just happens to be my turn to pitch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Cox did not want Glavine to have an 11-day layoff  
between starts, so he picked the left-hander to go against New 
York's Orlando Hernandez in the opener at Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine (14-11) is followed in the Braves' rotation by Greg  
Maddux (19-9), who worked Game 1 for the Braves in the division 
series and the NL Championship Series. Kevin Millwood (18-7) and 
John Smoltz (11-8) will take the mound after the series shifts to 
Yankee Stadium next week. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first two rounds of the playoffs, Atlanta used a rotation  
that began with Maddux, followed by Millwood, Glavine and Smoltz. 
</P>
<P>
	If Cox stuck with that alignment for the World Series, Glavine  
would have gone 11 days between starts. He last worked a week ago, 
pitching seven scoreless innings to beat the New York Mets in Game 
3 of the NLCS. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine might have pitched Game 2 Sunday night, but the  
left-hander wouldn't have been available for Game 5 in New York -- 
assuming, of course, the best-of-7 series lasts that long. 
</P>
<P>
	Lefties tend to have an advantage at Yankee Stadium because the  
power of right-handed hitters is negated by cavernous left field, 
where it takes a 399-foot shot to clear the wall in the power 
alley. Left-handed hitters, on the other hand, can take advantage 
of the short, 314-foot porch in right. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's his turn to pitch, No. 1,'' Cox said, explaining his  
decision to use Glavine. ``And this ensures he will pitch in New 
York, where left-handers are supposed to have a slight edge. I 
didn't do it for any other reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other ramifications of Atlanta's rotation: Smoltz will be  
available for relief duty in the opener, while Millwood, the team's 
most consistent starter, pitches Game 7 if the series goes the 
distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me feel good that our management and our team has  
that amount of confidence in me,'' Millwood said. ``Even if it does 
go that far, we'll have a lot of people ready for that game. I'll 
just go first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine takes the same sort of mentality into the opener,  
knowing his previous postseason starts were just as crucial even 
though he didn't pitch until Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In the division series, Glavine allowed only two runs in six  
innings against Houston, and the Braves went on to a decisive 5-3 
victory in 12 innings. He followed with a strong performance 
against the Mets, a 1-0 victory that gave the Braves a commanding 
3-0 advantage in the NLCS. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine has pitched 12 straight scoreless innings this  
postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, I fully expected to pitch Game 3,'' Glavine  
said. ``I thought Bobby would just roll it over and I would pitch 
the first game on the road like I did against the Mets and 
Astros.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees don't have a 30-homer man in their lineup, but they  
do have two players -- Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams -- who hit 
above .340, as well as four 100-RBI producers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their lineup is full of patient hitters with some power,''  
Glavine said. ``If you have a bunch of 50-homer guys, that means 
they're free swingers and probably easier to strike out. These guys 
don't strike out. They put the ball in play and make you work 
harder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Atlanta's four previous Series appearances this decade,  
Glavine pitched the opener once. He threw a complete-game 
four-hitter in 1992 for a 3-1 victory over Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	The most memorable Series performance came three years later,  
when he allowed only one hit in eight shutout innings against 
Cleveland in Game 6. The 1-0 victory gave the Braves their only 
championship of the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine is 4-3 with a 1.75 ERA in seven Series starts.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to be pitching Game 1,'' he said. ``Other than  
that, it's just one game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
