<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Keeps 'NYPD Blue' on Tuesdays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``NYPD Blue'' producer Steven Bochco won his war  
of wills with ABC on Friday. The network announced it was keeping 
the Emmy-winning police drama in the Tuesday time slot it has 
occupied since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's going to have to wait: ``NYPD Blue'' doesn't return for  
its new season until Jan. 11, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The network said it would move ``Once and Again,'' the new drama  
that has been airing Tuesdays at 10 p.m. ET, to Mondays at 10 p.m. 
in January, once the pro football season is over. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ... believe this scheduling decision allows us the  
opportunity to maximize the potential of both series,'' said Stu 
Bloomberg, co-chairman of the ABC Entertainment Television Group. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's deliberations over its schedule had turned into a public  
relations disaster when a furious Bochco denounced the network for 
thinking of moving his show. He had suggested that ABC wanted to 
give ``Once and Again'' the Tuesday time slot for financial reasons 
because it was produced by a company within the Walt Disney Co., 
which owns ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can certainly live with this compromise,'' Bochco said on  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC had set up the conflict by premiering ``Once and Again,'' a  
drama about two divorced parents, in the ``NYPD Blue'' time slot in 
September and not saying where it would go when ``NYPD Blue'' was 
ready to return in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once and Again,'' starring Sela Ward, started strong in the  
ratings but has faded in its time slot behind ``Judging Amy,'' 
CBS's new hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bochco said he's concerned about ABC losing more viewers to CBS  
Tuesday nights before ``NYPD Blue'' can return in January. But he 
said it will be an advantage for his show to air 22 new episodes in 
a row early next year without having to pause for reruns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once and Again'' will premiere in its new time slot on Jan.  
24. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise isn't a long-term solution. ABC will have to  
decide again next fall what to do with ``Once and Again,'' if it is 
renewed for a second season, when ``Monday Night Football'' 
returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only a problem if we get picked up for an eighth  
season,'' Bochco said. ``If we do well from January through May in 
our time slot, there's no downside for us. If they don't pick us 
up, someone else will.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
