<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Rejects Primary Date Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iowa and New Hampshire will lead off the  
Democratic presidential selection process with little competition 
after a panel refused to allow four other states to move their 
contests into February behind the leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	But the special status of Iowa and New Hampshire is likely to  
come under increasing fire when the Democratic Party starts 
wrestling with rules for the 2004 elections because of building 
resentment from other states. 
</P>
<P>
	A rules panel of the Democratic National Committee on Friday  
denied requests from Arizona, Michigan, South Carolina and 
Washington state to move their presidential primaries or caucuses 
into February. They sought the change to save money and stay 
competitive with state Republican parties that have moved events 
into February. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Democratic Party allows only Iowa and New Hampshire to  
hold caucuses or primaries before March 7 without penalty. The 
Republican National Committee does not set such limits, and state 
Republicans have taken advantage of the freedom by moving several 
other state events into February. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the panel decided to allow Iowa to move its leadoff  
caucuses to Jan. 24 and New Hampshire to move its 
first-in-the-nation primary to Feb. 1. But it decided Friday to 
hold the line there. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're continuing the fight that the Democratic Party has been  
carrying out for the last decade to keep this primary process from 
expanding into a permanent election,'' said Jim Roosevelt, 
co-chairman of the rules panel. 
</P>
<P>
	States have been jockeying for earlier positions on the calendar  
-- and increased influence -- ever since California decided earlier 
this year to move up to March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, South Carolina's Democratic primary will be March  
9, and Arizona and Michigan will hold their primaries March 11. 
Washington state had requested a Feb. 29 primary and a March 7 
caucus, but state party officials say their plans are ``up in the 
air.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC plans to begin examining the 2004 primary process at a  
Nov. 20 hearing. The RNC also is looking into the process, and the 
nation's secretaries of state are lobbying for a system of rotating 
regional primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., complained at the meeting that Iowa  
and New Hampshire are ``in a monopoly position.'' He said many 
states' Democrats are at a disadvantage ``all because of this 
cockamamie privilege for two states.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
