<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sentenced Woman Never Served Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- A 74-year-old woman sentenced to prison in  
1991 hasn't served her sentence because no one told her what to do 
or where to report after her appeal was denied seven years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A bureaucratic oversight came to light last month. Doris Preston  
was scheduled to begin serving her sentence today, though her 
attorneys have appealed and may ask the governor to commute her 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got word from anybody at all about where to go, but I  
was waiting and willing to serve my time,'' Mrs. Preston said. ``It 
never occurred to me that I was supposed to go turn myself in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her attorney, Carol Wright, said: ``She is looking at basically  
a death sentence if she is sent to prison at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Preston was convicted of aggravated arson in 1991 and  
sentenced to a five- to 25-year prison term. She was found guilty 
of starting a fire in her home that killed her 70-year-old husband, 
Andrew Preston. 
</P>
<P>
	She was released on bail while her appeal was pending. An  
appeals court upheld her conviction and sentence in December 1991, 
and the Ohio Supreme Court refused to hear the case in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Corrections Department last month discovered that  
there was no record of Mrs. Preston since her appeal and notified 
the Franklin County Common Pleas Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors then discovered Mrs. Preston had not served her  
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The statutes, the case law, nobody really says whose job it is  
to follow up on this once the appeals are denied,'' said Joyce 
Anderson, assistant county prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher court generally notifies the prosecutor's office,  
which files a motion to enforce the prison sentence, Anderson said. 
She couldn't say if they received notification that Mrs. Preston's 
appeals had been denied. 
</P>
<P>
	In the future, when decisions are handed back from the Supreme  
Court, the prosecutor's office will check to make sure that those 
who should be locked up are in custody, Anderson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
