<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nikkei Falls Slightly / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar slipped against the yen today after the  
release of a Japanese report showing the economy is improving. The 
key Tokyo stock index edged downward. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 105.44 yen late today in Tokyo, down  
0.68 yen from 106.12 yen Thursday in Tokyo and also below its level 
of 105.86 yen in New York late Thursday. During the day, it ranged 
from 105.25 yen to 106.28 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 9.47 points,  
or 0.05 percent, to finish at 17438.80. On Thursday, the average 
closed down 86.44 points, or 0.49 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher early in the  
session but later moved lower after the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry released its latest report on business activity 
in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that Japan's all industry activity index rose a  
healthy 1.2 percent in August from July. 
</P>
<P>
	Also weighing on the dollar were continuing worries over the  
direction of the U.S. economy, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell  
94.67 points to 10,297.69, hurt by a pessimistic profit outlook 
from International Business Machines Corp. late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 114.00 yen, down  
from 114.36 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors that France's Renault SA was selling euros for yen in a  
bid to increase its stake in Japan's Nissan Motor Co., in which it 
already owns a controlling 37 percent stake, helped pushed down 
both the euro as well as the dollar against the yen, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices in Tokyo initially rebounded  
moderately in light trading but later lost those gains. Some 
analysts were pessimistic about the market putting on any more 
gains this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has done its work for the year, it's marking  
time,'' said Chuck Lambert, market analyst at Jardine Fleming 
Securities. He said there could be profit-taking over the next few 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent falls in U.S. share prices have had a negative  
psychological impact in Japan, although Tokyo officials deny any 
impact on the country's economic fundamentals. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 9.99 points, or 0.66 percent, to 1,513.93. The 
TOPIX closed down 3.37 points, or 0.22 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section totaled about 564 million shares,  
down from 596 million shares Thursday. Retreating issues 
outnumbered advancers 717 to 488, while 138 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8950 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8700 percent. Its 
price fell 0.21 point to 99.19. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
