<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Push Ahead; Dow Up 187.43 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today, extending Thursday's  
late rebound from a steep selloff sparked by a profit warning from 
IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	With an hour remaining in Wall Street trading, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was up 187.43 at 10,485.13, erasing Thursday's 
94-point decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also had sizable gains. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 23.44 at 1,307.05, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 39.83 at 2,841.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks led the advance amid news that Republicans and  
Democrats had settled a dispute on bank lending rules that 
threatened to derail major legislation overhauling the financial 
services laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, the legislation would make it easier for banks,  
brokerage firms and insurance companies to merge and sell each 
other's products. Among the Dow 30, American Express rose 4 1/8 to 
149, J.P. Morgan rose 7 3/8 to 124 9/16 and Citigroup rose 1 7/8 to 48 
13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	With no major economic reports to steer the market, investors  
were focusing on the continuing flood of company reports on the 
just-ended third-quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market has had two major worries: short-term interest  
rates and earnings,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at 
Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``This week, we put interest rates behind us a bit 
so that would could focus on earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Gillette slid 2 1/4 to 35 5/8 following a report late  
Thursday that met most profit forecasts but warned of weak 
fourth-quarter sales and earnings due to inventory problems. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Dow closed with a loss of 94.67 after  
recovering from a 213-point slide. The broad market also rallied 
late in the day, with the technology-dominated Nasdaq composite 
turning higher despite the discouraging news from IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Wednesday, IBM warned that customers are postponing  
purchases of network and database machines, fearful that complex 
system upgrades will make them more vulnerable to the Year 2000 
computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, IBM rose 2 5/8 to 93 5/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 ratio on the  
New York Stock Exchange and by a 9-to-7 margin on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 766.85 million shares, slightly behind  
Thursday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 4.74 at  
419.01. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
