<DOCNO> APW19991022.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 08:07:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Longhorns Like Nebraska's Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Enough of this gushing over which team has  
the nicest fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The third-ranked Nebraska Cornhuskers just want to beat No. 18  
Texas on Saturday, not play nice. 
</P>
<P>
	With victories in 1996 and 1998, Texas joins Florida State as  
the only two teams to beat Nebraska twice this decade. It's a badge 
of honor earned against one of the dominant teams of the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	While Texas has fond memories of its 20-16 victory last year --  
which snapped Nebraska's 47-game home winning streak -- Cornhuskers 
center Dominic Raiola said the loss turned his stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate Texas,'' Raiola said. ``They're this high-and-mighty  
deal. I don't like that song either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas players and coaches sing ``The Eyes of Texas'' after every  
game. After the victory, Texas players hoisted coach Mack Brown on 
their shoulders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had my helmet on, my head down,'' Raiola said. ``It was  
cloudy and kind of dark. It made me disgusted to hear that song. It 
made me sick to see them celebrating on our field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas coaches and players have more pleasant memories.  
</P>
<P>
	First came the stunned silence when the clock ran out. Then came  
the standing ovation from several hundred Nebraska fans that Brown 
said he'll remember forever. 
</P>
<P>
	In an age when boos, taunts and even worse sometimes rain down  
on players from the stands, Nebraska fans are among the best in 
sports, Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were just unbelievable,'' he said. ``We can all learn  
from those people about sportsmanship and how to make an opposing 
team feel comfortable while still trying to win on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All week, calls to sports-radio talk shows have told stories of  
slaps on the back and free dinners from Nebraska fans after Texas' 
victory last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown has implored Texas fans to return the good will -- win or  
lose -- during Nebraska's first trip to Austin since 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's make the Nebraska people, when they leave Austin, say  
the same things that we've said for a year about Lincoln,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be easy to do if Texas (5-2, 2-1 Big 12) can beat  
Nebraska (6-0, 3-0) for the third straight time. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas beat the Cornhuskers 37-27 in the 1996 Big 12 title game --  
a loss that ended Nebraska's bid for a third consecutive national 
title -- before last year's upset in Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it helps us, knowing we're the only team that's been  
able to beat them two in a row in a long time,'' Texas wide 
receiver Ryan Nunez said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, Texas players say last year's game means  
little to them anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning the Big 12 and ascending the AP Top 25 to join the elite  
teams like Nebraska means everything. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have done some things against them the past two years, but  
it doesn't mean anything this season,'' cornerback Ahmad Brooks 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we want to be Big 12 contenders, we have to beat  
Nebraska.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
