<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telekom Expands in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom AG is buying a  
majority stake in U.S.-based MediaOne Group Inc.'s cellular-phone 
assets in central Europe and Russia for $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchases announced Friday from MediaOne, a Colo.-based  
cable television concern being acquired by AT&AMP;T Corp., 
significantly expand Telekom's portfolio in the emerging markets of 
central and eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The move caps a week of merger and acquisition news in Europe's  
rapidly consolidating telecommunications market. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Telekom's main rival in the German market,  
Mannesmann AG, announced its intention to buy British mobile 
operator Orange PLC, just two months after Telekom established its 
own foothold in Britain's mobile phone market by buying One2One. 
</P>
<P>
	German firms are also targets: France Telecom said Monday it was  
buying a majority stake in E-Plus, Germany's third-largest mobile 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the latest deal, Telekom will double its stake in Polska  
Telefonia Cyfrowa SP ZOO to 45 percent. The Polish firm, under its 
brand name Era GSM, is the largest and fastest-growing GSM digital 
wireless operator in Central Europe, according to Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	Telekom also will acquire a 49 percent holding in Westel  
Radiotelefon (Westel 450), the Hungarian analog wireless operator; 
a 49 percent share in Westel 900, the Hungarian GSM digital 
wireless operator; and a controlling stake in Russian 
Telecommunications Development Corp., or RTDC, which has 
investments in nine regional Russian telecommunications companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer termed the move ``a logical  
expansion of Deutsche Telekom's presence in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition ``complements our European internationalization  
strategy with our joint ventures in Austria, Hungary, the Czech 
Republic, Poland, Russia and Croatia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is subject to approval by Deutsche Telekom's  
supervisory board and regulators. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
