<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Matching Up Spartans and Badgers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin cornerback Jamar Fletcher thrives  
on big challenges, and 6-foot-6 Michigan State receiver Plaxico 
Burress is the biggest challenge in the Big Ten. 
</P>
<P>
	When the No. 11 Spartans visit the No. 17 Badgers at Camp  
Randall Stadium, the 5-10 Fletcher's matchup with Burress could be 
one of the most exciting duels of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's only one part of an important game with serious Rose  
Bowl implications for two teams near the top of the Big Ten. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game also features the nation's fifth-best rushing  
offense against the best run defense. Watching Ron Dayne and his 
powerful offensive line pound away at the Spartans' massive front 
seven will be intriguing, but it just isn't as exciting as the duel 
between Burress and Fletcher, two probable future pros who play 
with flair and skill -- and truckloads of trash talk. 
</P>
<P>
	If Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez makes the coverage decision  
everyone expects him to, Burress and Fletcher will face each other 
head-on. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is go out and play my game,'' Fletcher said. ``I  
know he likes to talk. He's a pretty good receiver, but I don't 
know if he's faced anybody of my caliber. He's going to be in for a 
challenge also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burress has become known almost as much for his yapping and  
chest-pounding as his considerable skill at catching quarterback 
Bill Burke's passes. 
</P>
<P>
	He tries to intimidate defensive backs from the opening play  
with a constant stream of chatter. He's so relentlessly exuberant 
that coach Nick Saban barred him from talking to the media this 
week after the Spartans' 52-28 loss to Purdue, which knocked 
Michigan State from the ranks of the unbeaten. 
</P>
<P>
	Burress had just three catches for 50 yards in the game, and  
Purdue cornerback Michael Hawthorne issued a stinging verbal 
rebuke. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just big and is a lot of talk,'' Hawthorne said. ``I  
don't think he's the best receiver in the Big Ten. I hate how he 
pounds his chest after making a play, like saying, `I have heart 
and you don't.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Burress will be itching to redeem himself against Fletcher,  
who's eight inches shorter than Burress but every bit an equal 
competitor and talker. He's also short-listed for the Jim Thorpe 
Award, given to the nation's top defensive back. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is big time,'' Fletcher said. ``Any time you go up  
against a prime-time receiver like Plaxico, you want to show your 
game and let everybody else around the country know that you're 
pretty good, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher, a sophomore who led the nation with seven  
interceptions last season, has become the kind of defensive back so 
feared that he essentially removes one receiver from the Badgers' 
opponents playbook. He has just two interceptions this season, 
mostly because quarterbacks refuse to throw toward him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a tremendous amount of respect for Fletcher,'' Saban  
said. ``You have to know where he is on every play, or he'll get 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher loves to hit receivers at the line of scrimmage and  
knock them out of their routes, something the Boilermakers did to 
great effect last week. Burress has 35 catches for 629 yards and 
five touchdowns this season, but it's thought that he can be 
defended if an opponents doesn't allow him a physical advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez had no qualms about comparing the towering wideout to  
the prototypical big, athletic receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a Randy Moss-type receiver,'' Alvarez said. ``I'm talking  
about athleticism. I'm talking about height. I'm talking about 
big-play capabilities. Everybody that plays him pays special 
attention to him, yet he still gets the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burress set a school record with 10 catches for 255 yards  
against Michigan two weeks ago, and he could be even more important 
to the Spartans if Gari Scott, the team's No. 2 receiver, can't 
play because of a strained knee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
