<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reputed Hit Man Comes Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- For 12 years, Carolyn Wood was married to the mob,  
though she claims she never knew it. 
</P>
<P>
	But with her ex-husband's emergence from the underworld after 16  
years as a fugitive and his confession to killing 20 people for New 
England's top organized crime bosses, Wood sees this as his chance 
to do right by his real family, not his crime family. 
</P>
<P>
	While John Martorano, 59, wears $800 suits in court and employs  
several high-powered attorneys to defend him, Wood, 60, is living 
off disability checks and fighting for more than $200,000 she's 
owed from their 1975 divorce settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	When Martorano was arrested in 1995, defense attorney Martin  
Weinberg told a federal judge that his client was not a flight risk 
because he didn't want to abandon his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, who supported her family by working as a caterer and  
hairdresser, scoffs at the notion of Martorano as a family man, 
saying he was neither father nor husband. She said he was 
controlling and abusive, occasionally knocking her unconscious if 
she questioned his authority or insulted his friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I understand (Martorano) was (a partier),'' Wood  
said in recent telephone interviews from her home north of Boston. 
``But I stayed home and that was that. I was told who I could talk 
to. I wasn't allowed to do anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano has ``categorically denied the allegations of abuse,''  
Weinberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the couple divorced in Las Vegas, Martorano insisted it was  
for tax purposes, Wood said. Then in 1979, he disappeared to 
Florida to avoid prosecution for fixing horse races. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood said she neither saw nor heard from him during the next 16  
years, but remembers her young son ``cried many days.'' Wood, who 
has an older daughter from a previous marriage, told the boy his 
dad was away on business. 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano was captured and indicted in 1995 for racketeering and  
extortion along with his brother James and friends Francis 
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme; Steven ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, who is 
godfather to the couple's only son; and South Boston neighborhood 
crime boss James ``Whitey'' Bulger. James Martorano has since 
pleaded guilty, Flemmi and Salemme are in custody and Bulger has 
been a fugitive since his indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	When Martorano found out his friends had betrayed the mob by  
serving as longtime FBI informants, he agreed last month to testify 
against them and plead guilty to 12 murders in exchange for a 
sentence of as few as 12 1/2 years. The former hit man confessed to 20 
killings, but prosecutors decided to focus on the 12 that most 
directly relate to their federal racketeering case. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea bargain must be approved by U.S. District Judge Mark  
Wolf, who has said he is uncertain about accepting the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Wood's 29-year-old son refuses to read accounts  
of his father's transgressions and Wood is fighting for the value 
of the house she won in the divorce. While Martorano was 
underground, Wood learned that the house was not his to give her -- 
it belonged to his friend, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a probate judge awarded Wood more than $200,000 -- the  
value of the house plus interest -- but she still hasn't seen the 
money. She said Martorano is skillful at hiding his assets, and 
though Wood is not part of the criminal case against her 
ex-husband, her lawyer, Donna Turley, recently sent a letter to 
Wolf notifying him of Martorano's financial obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping to create enough pressure on Mr. Martorano to  
make him want to have this (debt) disappear,'' Turley said. The 
attorney representing Martorano in the divorce-related proceedings, 
Paul Haley, did not return calls seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, who never remarried, said she suffers from post-traumatic  
stress syndrome resulting from her marriage and learning about her 
ex-husband's exploits, like the fatal 1968 shootings of a Boston 
nightclub manager and two teen-agers who happened to be sitting in 
the car with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me feel guilty,'' she said between sobs.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
