<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Maker Has Dealers Sign Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) --The nation's largest handgun  
manufacturer is requiring dealers in its collective advertising 
program to sign a code of ethics designed to prevent the illegal 
sale of guns. 
</P>
<P>
	More than three-quarters of Smith &AMP; Wesson's 3,500 registered  
dealers in the program have signed the agreement since the company 
began mailing them in mid-July, said Paul Pluff, manager of retail 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the code requires dealers to obey all  
firearms laws, sell only Smith &AMP; Wesson guns with safety locks and 
to closely monitor buyers to avoid illegal purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Springfield-based company warned that dealers will be  
dropped from collective advertisements and won't receive other 
marketing help if they run afoul of the law or fail to sign the 
agreement by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, because the company doesn't sell directly to retailers,  
stores need not belong to the advertising program to sell Smith &AMP; 
Wessons, spokesman Ken Jorgensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of negligent sales has been raised in several lawsuits  
that have been filed by various cities against the gun industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Smith &AMP; Wesson has not been found negligent. We want to make  
sure that the people we are doing business with are in step with us 
and the law in that way,'' Jorgensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Sugarmann, director of the nonprofit Violence Policy  
Center, said the ethics code is only meant to let the company 
``point their fingers at the dealers'' in lawsuits claiming 
negligent sales practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Carr, co-owner of Carr's Sporting Goods, in Taunton, said  
he expected to sign the letter as one of the Smith &AMP; Wesson's 
stocking dealers. ``I can understand them doing that. One of the 
reasons is legal liability.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
