<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Australian Open Winner Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- John Bromwich, a two-time Australian  
Open champion, died after suffering a heart attack this week, his 
family said today. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his tennis career was interrupted by World War II,  
Bromwich won the Australian Open in 1939 and 1946. He played 51 
Davis Cup matches from 1937 to 1950, winning 19 of his 30 singles 
matches and 20 of 21 doubles matches. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich was ambidextrous, using both hands on his forehand.  
</P>
<P>
	The major disappointment of his career came at Wimbledon in 1948  
when he reached the final against Bob Falkenburg and wasted three 
match points, losing the championship after leading 5-2 in the 
final set. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich's greatest successes came in doubles. In 1948, he won  
the Wimbledon doubles title with Frank Sedgman. He won at Wimbledon 
again in 1950 with Adrian Quist. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich was a three-time U.S. Open doubles champion and also  
was a Wimbledon mixed doubles winner with Louise Brough in 1947-48. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife Zenda. His funeral will be held  
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
