<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Travel Agents Boycott United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Through postings on Internet travel sites, faxes  
and customer bookings, travel agents across the country are venting 
their wrath at United Airlines for slashing the fee it pays them 
for selling tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``United Airlines has been expelled from this travel agency,''  
declares a sign posted on the marquee outside John Shands' agency 
in Brownsville, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure my $50,000 in business isn't going to make a whit of  
difference to United Airlines. But I'm just not going to support 
them any more on this,'' Shands, who owns three travel agencies in 
south Texas, said in a telephone interview. ``I will not suffer my 
financial death at the hands of corporate executioners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United announced plans Oct. 7 to cut agents' commissions from 8  
percent to 5 percent, a move that would save the airline $150 
million a year. Since then, 16 other carriers have followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agents say the airlines are trying to encroach on their  
business and force consumers to deal directly with the carriers, 
which could result in higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Antitrust law bars agents from acting together in an organized  
effort targeting United or any other carrier. But numerous agents 
boycotted after the previous three rounds of cuts -- two initiated 
by United -- and conversations in Internet chat rooms make it clear 
such informal actions are under way again. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agents face stiff competition from Internet sites that  
allow consumers to shop for deals and buy directly from the 
airlines. They were first jolted by industrywide commission cuts in 
1995, after Delta Air Lines reduced fees for domestic tickets to 10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, United chopped that to 8 percent and then  
followed in 1998 by capping commissions on international tickets at 
8 percent. In the latest move, it lopped off another 3 percent 
while retaining the $50 cap as the maximum it would pay agents per 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 80 percent of airline tickets are still sold  
through retail travel agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kathleen Tagariello, whose Buckhead Travel Partners in  
Atlanta has stopped doing United bookings, claimed the latest 
decrease could put as many as half of travel agents nationwide out 
of business within months. Such dire predictions haven't come true 
in previous cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately at this point every carrier has followed suit  
and we cannot boycott everybody or we can't have anybody traveling 
anywhere,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stirred to act by the latest cuts, Linda Rawlings, head of  
Travel Advocate in Denver, is organizing a rally of travel agents 
on the steps of the Colorado state capital next Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is now absolutely unprofitable to issue an airline  
ticket,'' she said. ``We had exactly nine hours' notice of a 37 1/2 
percent cut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United chairman James Goodwin, explaining the reasoning behind  
the cuts, said in Tokyo this week that ``electronic capabilities'' 
are forcing the airline to find smarter ways to do business. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the airline indicated it isn't feeling any pinch. A  
spokeswoman for the Elk Grove Village, Ill.-based carrier who 
declined to be named said United was aware only of ``discussion 
about planned boycotts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American Society of Travel Agents, which represents 11,000  
U.S. travel agencies and 12,000 suppliers, downplayed the boycott 
and said it had nothing to do with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever's going on is probably a lot of talk,'' said Paul  
Ruden, senior vice president. ``The agent really isn't in a 
position to direct business this way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the travel agents' group, while tiptoeing around legally  
dangerous boycott talk, revoked United's membership in the 
association -- a mostly symbolic move -- and has been proposing 
federal legislation to reverse the cuts. It also has asked the 
Transportation Department to rescind the cuts as unfair under the 
Federal Aviation Act. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, large airlines who were sued by the trade group for  
allegedly conspiring to cut commissions and cap payouts settled out 
of court for more than $90 million. The lawsuit obviously did not 
deter them from further cuts, and some agents predict their cut 
will eventually drop to zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Airlines is one of the few major U.S. carriers to keep  
its travel agents' fees intact despite this round of cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a commitment to travel agents back in 1995 that we  
would uphold the 10 percent commission through the year 2000,'' 
explained Beth Harbin, a spokeswoman for the Dallas-based airline. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
