<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Sues Barnes &AMP; Noble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Amazon.com, the world's leading online  
bookseller, is suing Barnes &AMP; Noble over alleged copycat use of its 
popular ``1-Click'' feature, which greatly simplifies the process 
of making online purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon filed a patent-infringement lawsuit against New  
York-based Barnes &AMP; Noble in U.S. District Court in Seattle 
Thursday. The complaint seeks to halt use of the technology by 
Barnes &AMP; Noble's online subsidiary, barnesandnoble.com, and seeks 
unspecified damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Gus Carlson, a spokesman for barnesandnoble.com, said: ``We have  
not yet examined the suit in detail, but from what we do know, we 
believe the suit is completely without merit and we will vigorously 
defend our position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com's 1-Click feature securely stores billing and  
shipping information so return customers don't have to re-enter the 
data each time they buy -- a turn-off for shoppers. 
</P>
<P>
	Most online retailers have similar technology.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody' got one,'' said analyst Tom Huskerson with Zona  
Research in Redwood City, Calif. Clearly Amazon.com ``feels Barnes 
&AMP; Noble has done something that copies what they're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is the second such lawsuit in a matter of days. Last week,  
priceline.com sued Microsoft, contending that Expedia.com's new 
online hotel-pricing service violates Priceline's patent. Both 
services invite customers to state the price they're willing to pay 
for a room. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the equivalent of a global war in the sphere of  
e-commerce and this is only the beginning,'' said patent attorney 
Rob Gorman with the New York firm of Fulnright and Jaworski. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet and recent case law development ``have opened up a  
whole new area of unclaimed land which can be carved out through 
the proper filing of patents,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have functionality that is going to provide faster,  
more efficient, convenient access to some aspect of e-commerce, why 
wouldn't you protect that functionality?'' Gorman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit contends that in May 1998, barnesandnoble.com  
``meticulously copied Amazon.com's 1-Click process, dubbed it 
'Express Lane,' and introduced it on their barnesandnoble.com 
website.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com, the Internet's No. 1 music, video and book retailer,  
opened its virtual doors on the World Wide Web in July 1995. Barnes 
&AMP; Noble ventured online in May 1997. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
