<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Bill Would Extend Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott introduced a  
tax bill Friday that would make the business research and 
development credit permanent and extend several other expiring tax 
breaks through 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, with an estimated cost of $33 billion over 10  
years, blends parts of similar bills approved by the Senate Finance 
Committee and the House Ways and Means Committee. It also drops 
several provisions in those bills. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Lott would not extend any energy tax credits,  
including those for wind-produced electricity or those for power 
produced with chicken manure. The first is a priority for 
Midwestern lawmakers, while the second is sought by Finance 
Committee Chairman William Roth, whose home state of Delaware is 
prime poultry country. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Lott, R-Miss., said the bill is more  
straightforward than the other versions and achieves the majority 
leader's goal of removing expiring tax credits from the 
congressional agenda during the 2000 election year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like to not have to come back and do all of this again  
next year,'' said spokesman John Czwartacki. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the bill would spend some of the projected non-Social  
Security budget surplus in all but its first year. President 
Clinton has threatened to veto the five-year, $23.2 billion House 
version for the same reason; the $8.5 billion Senate Finance 
Committee measure is fully paid for. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth said an earlier version of his bill would have made the R&AMP;D  
credit permanent and would have spent non-Social Security surplus 
money, but he discovered ``there was significant opposition'' among 
Republicans and Democrats alike to that approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the final days of the session, when time is short, we will  
need a consensus package,'' Roth said. ``I believe the Finance 
Committee bill has the best chance of obtaining that consensus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the R&AMP;D credit would be made permanent in Lott's bill,  
companies could not claim it until Sept. 30, 2000, to remove it 
from the tight fiscal 2000 budget. The credit, which expired on 
June 30, is prized by the high-tech industry and manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would ensure that millions of individual taxpayers  
do not run afoul of the complex alternative minimum tax by claiming 
numerous personal credits. Those credits would be exempted from AMT 
consideration through Dec. 31, 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill would make the AMT fix permanent, while the  
Finance Committee version applies to the 1999 and 2000 tax years. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the differences between the bills, congressional leaders  
of both parties and Clinton say a compromise on extension of the 
expiring credits will be reached by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to have an agreement ... so we don't have to go to  
conference forever to get it done,'' said House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
