<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 02:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Targeted for Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon wants Alaska to be the location  
for missile interceptors if President Clinton chooses to deploy a 
national defense against ballistic missile attack, a defense 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Bacon, speaking for Defense Secretary William Cohen,  
said Thursday the question of location is one of several elements 
of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty that would have to be 
revised if the United States went ahead with construction. Clinton 
may make such a decision as early as June. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is strongly opposed to the United States building a  
national missile defense -- even the limited version the Clinton 
administration envisions -- and has so far refused to renegotiate 
the ABM treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Russian officials opened a new round of discussions on  
the ABM treaty Thursday in Moscow, but there was little sign that 
the Russians would change their minds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said the United States could build an anti-missile base at  
Grand Forks, N.D., where it briefly operated one in the 1970s. That 
would be permissible under the ABM treaty, but the pact does not 
allow for more than one site or a change from one site to another. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a variety of reasons -- mainly to achieve complete  
(defensive) coverage of the United States -- we've decided that we 
have to move that site to Alaska,'' Bacon said. ``So the first 
thing we're proposing is to be able to move that site.'' He said 
there were other elements of the treaty that need to be 
renegotiated, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force Lt. Col. Rick Lehner, spokesman for the Pentagon  
office in charge of developing missile defenses, said anti-missile 
interceptors based in North Dakota could not protect the entire 
United States. He said his office had not been informed that the 
Pentagon had decided on Alaska. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
