<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:51:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jose Floods Caribbean Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILIPSBURG, St. Maarten (AP) -- Tropical Storm Jose inundated  
St. Maarten and other Caribbean islands with heavy rain Friday, 
causing mudslides, flooding city streets and isolating thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	The tropical storm was stalled about 120 miles north of Puerto  
Rico Friday, and its 65-mph winds were expected to strengthen. 
Tropical storm-force winds extended 145 miles from the center of 
the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose was moving at 8 mph, and its speed was expected to increase  
during a projected turn north into the open Atlantic. On that 
course, forecasters say the storm should be far east of Bermuda by 
Saturday, but the National Hurricane Center in Miami warned changes 
were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	While Jose's weak western side spared Puerto Rico, its stronger  
northeastern face dumped rain for 1 1/2 days on French St. Martin, 
Dutch St. Maarten, St. Eustatius and Saba as well as the nearby 
British island of Anguilla, some 200 miles east of San Juan, Puerto 
Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dutch St. Maarten, the plant of the newspaper The Daily  
Herald was flooded. 
</P>
<P>
	``The roof blew off. It's all one big mess because of the water.  
It's still pouring down and it gets worse and worse as long as the 
rain continues!'' said editor Roger Snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Islanders on St. Maarten, Saba and St. Eustatius were ordered to  
stay home. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Maarten Lt. Gov. Dennis Richardson went on the radio to warn  
islanders to stay off roads made impassable by fallen rocks, 
uprooted trees and swiftly flowing floodwaters. Richardson also 
ordered police to close a flooded main road that kept 5,000 people 
isolated in the village of St. Peter's, cut off from Philipsburg, 
the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights that had been rescheduled to arrive Friday were  
canceled, stranding dozens of tourists on the waterlogged island 
that is divided between Dutch St. Maarten and French St. Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Meteorologists said the islands in the area had received some 18  
inches of rain and warned that more was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Maarten appeared worst hit. Streams in the hills that  
surround Philipsburg burst their banks Friday, flooding some main 
roads with up to two feet of water. Yards flooded and people called 
radio stations to say floodwaters were seeping into their homes. 
Local radio reported rock slides and landslides, but said that 
there were no reports of injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby Anguilla fared little better, though it had power after  
work crews braved heavy overnight rain to restore electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both of my bedrooms had about half an inch of water in them,''  
said Dave Bicker, staff secretary to the island's British governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Local government official Orris Proctor said Anguilla's famed  
beaches suffered severe erosion in the south and east. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
