<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Eyes Ky. Gov.'s Derby Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- A state ethics panel reviewing the  
governor's control of hundreds of reserved seats for the Kentucky 
Derby voted Friday to do nothing -- at least not in public. 
</P>
<P>
	The Executive Branch Ethics Commission said it would send a  
private letter to Gov. Paul Patton. But the commission's five 
members, all appointed by the governor, wouldn't elaborate on what 
that letter might say. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky's governors have been given first crack at hundreds of  
reserved seats for the perennially sold-out Triple Crown jewel for 
the past four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice was largely ignored by the public until May when a  
Laurel, Md., horse trainer was arrested outside Churchill Downs and 
charged with scalping a $42 Derby ticket for $100. His attorneys 
traced the ticket, one of three James Casey had bought from a 
scalper, back to the office of the Kentucky governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey, whose trial is scheduled to begin Monday in Louisville,  
has conceded that he violated Kentucky law by selling the ticket at 
an inflated price, but he said he didn't deserve being locked in a 
holding cell for 12 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey said he paid a scalper $100 each for three Derby tickets  
because it was the only way to get a reserved seat, which ``are 
sold out forever,'' he said. Since he only needed two, he sold the 
third -- to an undercover police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out the ticket had been among 550 reserved for the  
governor. The state bought about 60 for use by the Tourism 
Development and Economic Development cabinets, and the rest were 
offered to friends and political supporters at face value -- 
$42-$500. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly can't imagine how there could be anything improper  
or how the public could possibly be hurt,'' Patton said Friday. ``I 
don't reckon the policy of this state is that governors can't have 
any friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both he and Churchill Downs spokesman Karl Schmitt said the  
track uses the governor's office as a way to draw more celebrities 
to the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Patton was not implicated in the alleged ticket scalping  
involving Casey, and he said he felt no personal responsibility for 
it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
