<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Campaigns to Undecided Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore was chirping along,  
deftly fielding questions from undecided voters he hoped to woo 
when Laurrie Malizia stood up and stopped him dead in his tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving a human face to the purported ``Clinton fatigue'' that  
some say has hurt Gore's quest for the 2000 Democratic presidential 
nomination, the 42-year-old administrative assistant told the vice 
president Thursday that she was disappointed in President Clinton 
for his affair with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Malizia declared she was looking for a leader who was ``an  
honest man but a moral man,'' and with her 14-year-old daughter, 
Kendra, seated by her side, she stated: ``I want your viewpoint on 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, his voice dropping noticeably, replied: ``I want to take  
my own values of faith and family to the presidency. I understand 
the disappointment that you feel, and I felt it myself. I think 
most people want to look to the future, turn that page and move on. 
So, all I can do is tell you about myself and about my commitment 
to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that, Gore recounted his personal history, his 29-year  
marriage and spoke proudly of his four children and first grandson, 
born on the Fourth of July. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, Malizia said that she liked Gore's answer but would  
still think about Gary Bauer, the Republican conservative activist, 
before making a primary choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what impressed her, Malizia replied: ``The fact that he  
looked at me straight in eyes. The fact that he seemed disappointed 
in the actions of the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a new poll showing Gore and Bill Bradley in a statistical  
dead heat for the Democratic nomination, the vice president's 
campaign pulled together a group of roughly 200 undecided voters so 
Gore could make his pitch for their vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The setting was pure Americana -- a dusty middle school gymnasium  
with 200 people sitting on bleachers and folding chairs. Gore's 
appeal was an equal serving of apple pie: ``I'm in this because I 
want to make a positive difference and I'm in this because I think 
I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For nearly two hours, the audience quizzed him on a wide range  
of subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	-- What can you do to make prescription drugs more affordable for  
me and other senior citizens? Include them in Medicare, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	-- How can we reduce smog and help my asthma? Get serious with  
the global environment, he replied. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Do you support work on 18 extra submarines at the Portsmouth  
Naval Shipyard, where I work? I'll have to study that, was the 
answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The forum at the older of Dover's two middle schools came as the  
latest New Hampshire poll showed that Bradley, the former New 
Jersey senator and Gore's only challenger, was in a statistical tie 
with the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-five percent of 600 likely Democratic voters supported  
Bradley, compared with 41 percent for Gore. Other recent polls have 
shown similar dead heats. An August poll showed Gore leading 
Bradley 46 percent to 29 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dover is a homey Seacoast City basking in the glory of New  
England's foliage season, its voters have been far from 
enthusiastic about Gore in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	As a presidential candidate in 1988, he finished fourth in Dover  
with 7.7 percent of the vote in the state's primary. Neighboring 
son Michael Dukakis was first with 37 percent, followed by Rep. 
Dick Gephardt of Missouri and former Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign said it picked the group of uncommitted voters  
after door-to-door canvassing and telephone banks. About 200 were 
invited -- some brought children -- and the campaign placed no 
restrictions on the content of their questions. 
</P>
<P>
	John Byrne, 45, of Dover, said afterwards he had been leaning  
towards Bradley but would have to re-evaluate Gore. ``The whole 
woodenness issue has been laid to rest for me. He's very 
personable,'' Byrne said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
