<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Down on Lower Output Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures jumped by 4 percent Friday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange on expectations that OPEC's continued 
solidarity on production cutbacks will push prices higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Other energy prices also gained.  
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, soybeans slid as rain in Brazil continued to  
ease concerns about dry planting conditions there, and sagging 
coffee prices rebounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil prices, which had lagged since topping $25 a barrel earlier  
this fall, climbed well above $23 a barrel as the market continued 
to respond to signs within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries that production won't be raised any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rally is basically an extension of the buying pressure in  
the wake of recent comments by the Saudis underscoring their 
hesitancy about raising production,'' said Michael Rothman, senior 
energy analyst for Merrill Lynch in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Key producers Saudi Arabia and Venezuela both indicated this  
week that OPEC may keep its oil output cuts in place after they 
expire next March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Fueling the rally, a senior Kuwaiti oil official said his nation  
would back an extension if necessary to stabilize the markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting prices was the news that Phillips Petroleum  
Co.'s 300,000-barrel-a-day Ekofisk field in the North Sea was shut 
down temporarily due to a small gas leak. 
</P>
<P>
	Rothman said oil prices are trading within a broader range now,  
with the next key benchmark a Nov. 17 meeting of the tripartite 
group -- the Saudis, Mexico and Venezuela, in the Saudi capital 
Riyadh. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower production level could stick, according to analyst  
Chris Stavros of Paine Webber, if the Northern Hemisphere winter is 
mild, leaving world oil stocks high. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (OPEC members) are saying 'Don't necessarily assume that  
we're goiung to automatically raise prices in March,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Light sweet crude for December delivery rose 84 cents to $23.45  
a barrel; November heating oil rose 1.90 cent to 60.89 cents a 
gallon; November unleaded gasoline rose 1.60 cent to 65.58 cents a 
gallon; November natural gas rose .8 cent to $3.072 per million 
British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude rose 82 cents to $22.93 a  
barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts of more rain in northern areas of Brazil and a  
technical followthrough to Thursday's slump sent soybeans to their 
lowest level in seven weeks on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The wave of selling occurred as the November contract was  
expiring. 
</P>
<P>
	November soybeans fell 7 cents to $4.72 3/4 a bushel.  
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures, which have been taking a beating in recent days  
on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange, bounced back from 
early weakness Friday amid concern that dry weather in Brazil could 
still harm the 2000-2001 crop. 
</P>
<P>
	While there are forecasts for weekend showers, much of the  
coffee-growing regions will be dry Monday and Tuesday, according to 
meteorologists. 
</P>
<P>
	December coffee rose 2.20 cents to 92.80 cents a pound.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
