<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Broadly With Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose broadly Friday against most  
major currencies, following the lead of a resurgent U.S. stock 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 105.97 yen,  
up from 105.86 yen late Thursday. It had been trading lower against 
the yen in Europe but regained lost ground after stocks opened 
higher on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar scored bigger gains against the euro and the British  
pound. The euro sank to $1.0675 from $1.0820 on Thursday, while the 
British pound dropped to $1.6573 from $1.6767. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillermo Estebanez, a senior currency strategist at Bank of  
America in San Francisco, said the dollar ``tends to be very much 
at the mercy of the equity markets'' in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. stock prices rallied Friday, with the New York market's  
best-known indicator, the Dow Jones industrial average, rising more 
than 172 points after dropping nearly 95 points in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	Other stock market indicators also posted gains.  
</P>
<P>
	Estebanez said the dollar's rally against the European  
currencies was assisted by a new report that wholesale prices in 
Germany rose a slight 0.1 percent in September from August. 
Economists expected a 0.2 percent rise. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that quieted some fears in Europe that inflation in its  
biggest market was accelerating and that the European Central Bank 
would boost interest rates to contain it. Estebanez said the new 
data suggests a rate hike isn't imminent in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4987 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4720, and 1.4767 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4822. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8321 German 
marks, up from 1.8078; 6.1445 French francs, up from 6.0727; and 
1,813.75 Italian lire, up from 1,789.69. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
