<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Detective Punished Over Louima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An Internal Affairs detective accused of  
mishandling the first tip about the torture of a Haitian immigrant 
by police officers has been suspended for 30 days without pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Commissioner Howard Safir handed down the punishment for  
detective Gary Alfred, which took effect Wednesday, The Daily News 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred had been staffing the Internal Affairs Bureau hotline on  
Aug. 9, 1997, when a nurse at Coney Island Hospital called to 
report an attack on Abner Louima, who had been arrested outside a 
nightclub and brought to the hospital with injuries suffered at the 
police station. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred failed to log the call. The investigation didn't begin  
until 36 hours later, after a second tip. Police officials said the 
delay may have allowed evidence to be lost or destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Two officers are awaiting sentencing, one who sodomized Louima  
with a broken broom handle and another who restrained him during 
the assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred's lawyers asked a court to stay his suspension, saying  
the caller ``had a very heavy accent, was speaking laboriously and 
reluctantly'' and didn't give enough information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
