<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed As Church Van Overturns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATASCADERO, Calif. (AP) -- A rental van packed with church  
members heading to a religious conference overturned on a coastal 
highway, killing seven women and scattering Bibles and hymnals 
across the pavement. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen members of the Kingdom of Jesus Christ Church in Los  
Angeles were in the van when it apparently skidded and tumbled 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the accident was under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know if she swerved or overcorrected or what,''  
Sheriff's Detective Sean Donahue said. He said deer and other 
wildlife frequently cross that stretch of highway and the driver 
may have tried avoid hitting an animal. 
</P>
<P>
	Five women thrown from the van were killed. The driver, Julieta  
Razon, 49, and another woman inside also died. Two adults were 
listed in critical condition. A 4-year-old girl was in serious 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The crumpled van landed on its side in a 10-foot-deep ditch.  
Rescue workers had to prop it up with boards to reach the people 
trapped in the wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the Bibles and religious books, purses, backpacks and  
scores of plastic utensils littered the ground around the van. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said only a few of the passengers were wearing  
seatbelts. 
</P>
<P>
	The group was heading to San Francisco, where the founder of  
their church, Apollo C. Quiboloy, was scheduled to speak Friday 
evening. The church, based in the Philippines, was started 1985 and 
has about 3 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	Quiboloy drove to Atascadero, about halfway between San  
Francisco and Los Angeles, after he learned of the crash. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
