<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Serbia To Let Montenegro Go Free  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a major policy shift, President  
Slobodan Milosevic will allow pro-Western Montenegro to leave the 
Yugoslav federation without bloodshed if the republic decides to do 
so, Serbian officials said today. The government of Montenegrin 
President Milo Djukanovic has demanded radical restructuring of the 
Yugoslav federation, a process which would virtually abolish 
Milosevic's control over the small republic. Montenegro plans to 
hold an independence referendum in case Milosevic rejects its 
proposal. Talks between the two republics' delegations are 
scheduled for next week. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. OKs Peackeepers for Sierra Leone  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council today approved a  
6,000-strong U.N. peacekeeping force for Sierra Leone. A U.N. 
Mission in Sierra Leone will be established for six months at first 
to help safeguard the peace deal signed July 7 by the government 
and rebel leaders after an eight-year civil war. The resolution 
authorizes the U.N. force to take ``necessary action'' to ensure 
the security and movement of U.N. personnel, and to protect 
civilians. During the war, tens of thousands of people were killed 
by members of the Revolutionary United Front and their allies. 

</P>
<P>
	Papon Headed to Prison in France  
</P>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Maurice Papon, the former Vichy  
official who fled France rather than face jail for his role in 
sending Jews to Nazi death camps, was handed over to French 
authorities today. His final destination is a prison in a southern 
Paris suburb, where he was to be incarcerated. The Swiss government 
expelled Papon earlier today. He was convicted in April 1998 and 
sentenced to 10 years in jail for complicity in crimes against 
humanity for his role in deporting 1,590 Jews from Bordeaux. Most 
deportees later died at the Auschwitz death camp. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Can Force Klansmen To Remove Masks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An appeals panel ruled today that the city does  
not have to allow Ku Klux Klan members to wear their masks at a 
planned rally tomorrow. The decision was a victory for the city. A 
lower court yesterday had ordered the city to allow KKK members to 
hold the rally while wearing their hooded white masks. City 
attorney Michael Hess said the KKK leaders had not applied for a 
permit yet, but he said if they did they would get one, as long as 
they agreed to abide by the ruling and stick to hoods and robes but 
no masks. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Skipping GOP Candidates' Debate  
</P>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Five Republican presidential candidates  
gathered today for their first debate, but the focus is on the 
rival who is not there -- front-runner George W. Bush. The Texas 
governor opted to skip the New Hampshire forum, as his $57 million 
campaign kitty and sizable lead in polls provided no real incentive 
for an encounter with his challengers. Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, 
Orrin Hatch, Alan Keyes and John McCain will participate in 
tonight's forum. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Gang Clearing Out ATMs  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A sophisticated Russian criminal ring has been  
clearing out bank accounts in several countries by tampering with 
ATM machines in Moscow. The full extent of the fraud is not yet 
known, but authorities believe hundreds of thousands of dollars 
have been stolen by a well-organized criminal group that may have 
insider connections at Russian banks. Some foreigners who had money 
stolen from their bank accounts are having problems getting 
reimbursements from their banks, The Moscow Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Meat Diet Fattens Prices at Market  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The high-protein diet craze that has people  
pigging out on steak and chops may be plumping up meat prices on 
the wholesale market. ``Confirmed pasta eaters are now red meat 
eaters,'' says Chicago analyst Bill Plummer, who contends that the 
phenomenon is boosting prices. The high-protein weight-loss diet 
has been promoted in such best sellers as ``Protein Power'' and 
``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution.'' Demand for beef is expected to 
increase 1.6 percent over last year, the National Cattlemen's Beef 
Association said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 213.39  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today, with the Dow Jones  
industrial average up 213.39 points at 10,511.09 justt before the 
close. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 1,967-1,047. The Nasdaq composite index was up 29.84 at 
2,831.79. 

</P>
<P>
	FSU's Warrick To Play vs. Clemson  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Heisman Trophy contender Peter Warrick  
will rejoin Florida State in time for tomorrow's game at Clemson 
after agreeing to deal in which he will serve no jail time on a 
theft charge. The star receiver pleaded guilty today to misdemeanor 
petty theft in connection with a department store scam. The 
settlement met the university's standard for allowing him to play. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
