<DOCNO> APW19991022.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 03:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress May Revive Cleanup Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation overhauling the Superfund  
environmental cleanup program could resurrect taxes on oil and 
chemicals that ended in 1995 -- but not if a key House committee 
chairman can stop it. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is attempting to blend  
together two bills that would cut down on lawsuit costs, remove 
barriers to redevelopment of old industrial sites and protect 
innocent businesses from getting tangled in litigation or 
unwarranted cleanup costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Many business organizations support the reforms, which have  
backing from both Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill. But 
other influential corporate groups and the House Ways and Means 
Committee chairman, Rep. Bill Archer, oppose resurrecting the 
excise taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics say the opposition by Archer, a Republican from  
Houston, is aimed at protecting Texas oil and gas interests. But 
Archer said in an interview Thursday that he does not believe any 
industry should be singled out with a tax to resolve a waste 
problem unless it was directly to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a question of what's right and what's wrong,'' Archer  
said. ``I would oppose this if it were levied against the steel 
industry or the electronics industry, if they were not involved in 
the creation of the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many corporate groups side with Archer on the taxes but favor  
the proposed Superfund reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax was levied against the oil and chemical industry when  
Superfund was created in 1980 because those industries were a 
primary source of toxic pollution covered by the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would like to see a bill get through, but that does not  
include the tax,'' said Mark Whitenton, a vice president at the 
National Association of Manufacturers. ``It has never made much 
sense, except that it was a convenient source of revenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others say the costs should not be borne by all taxpayers.  
President Clinton proposed reviving the $1.5 billion excise tax in 
his fiscal 2000 budget and repeatedly has called on Congress to do 
so. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't reinstate the taxes, what you're doing is  
shifting billions of dollars from polluters to the public,'' said 
Karen Florini, senior attorney at the Environmental Defense Fund. 
``These industries have a closer connection to the dump sites than 
the general public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The excise taxes were allowed to expire in 1995, saving the  
affected industries some $6 billion over the last four years. 
Enough money has accumulated in the fund that along with general 
revenue money the cleanup program can continue to operate through 
2002, including $700 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	A leading Republican congressman on environmental issues, Rep.  
Sherwood Boehlert of New York, said the tax should be reinstated to 
ensure Superfund can finish the hazardous site cleanup job -- and 
then slowly phased out over eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to complete the program,'' said Boehlert, sponsor of  
one reform bill. ``I'm not excited about any taxes. But it's the 
responsible thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A main sponsor of the other Superfund bill, GOP Rep. Michael  
Oxley of Ohio, said many business groups are willing to accept the 
tax to get the reforms, particularly small businesses that are 
often roped into huge Superfund cleanups simply because they shared 
a landfill where hazardous wastes were dumped. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like a reasonable tradeoff,'' Oxley said.  
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting this week, Hastert urged Oxley, Boehlert and others  
involved in the issue to put the two bills together and then 
present them to Archer's committee for a decision on reinstating 
the tax. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to reconcile some of the differences ... so that is  
the first step,'' Hastert said Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 00:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ski Safety Programs Broadened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Skiers and snowboarders have been told to rein in  
the recklessness this winter as the nation's ski resorts step up 
safety programs following a particularly deadly season. 
</P>
<P>
	With just days before the opening of some ski areas, resort  
managers say they're ready to strip season passes and daily lift 
tickets from hotdogging skiers who jet through congested areas, 
risking serious injury to themselves and others. 
</P>
<P>
	``More people will be more closely watching the slopes this  
year,'' said Paul Witt of Colorado's Vail Resorts. ``If people 
don't feel the resort is doing something about safety, they are not 
going to come to the slopes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The increased monitoring comes as part of the ``Heads Up''  
safety awareness campaign by the National Ski Areas Association 
launched Thursday at Colorado's Loveland ski area west of Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, 39 people died on U.S. ski slopes, compared with 26  
the year before and an average of 34. The worst season for ski 
deaths came in 1994-95, when 49 people died on the slopes. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of overall injuries fell 50 percent last season,  
though serious injuries such as paralysis or other spinal cord 
injuries increased slightly. That was despite a 2.5 percent decline 
in national skier and snowboarder visits, the equivalent of one 
person skiing or snowboarding one day. 
</P>
<P>
	While insisting the slopes remain safe overall, industry  
officials point out that many deaths and serious injuries involve 
young men who ski too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve of last year's victims died on Colorado slopes -- nearly  
twice the yearly average. In one, a teen-age skier slammed into a 
60-year-old snowboarder, killing both. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an anomaly,'' said John Frew of Colorado Ski Country USA.  
``No one in the industry can remember the last time two people died 
in a collision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa O'Brien of the Park City resort in Utah said officials  
there decided to implement a patrol program after skiers suggested 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were complaining about people speeding through slow  
skiing zones,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops: Mom Admits Starving Two Sons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Eight-year-old brothers -- two of a set  
of triplets -- died after their mother starved them for days and 
scalded their feet in hot water, authorities say. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bass, who had been hospitalized with severe burns, died  
early Friday, police spokesman Sgt. Floyd Mitchell said. His 
brother Larry, who weighed less than 30 pounds, died Wednesday at 
their home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the worst case of child neglect I've seen,'' homicide  
Capt. Darryl Forte said of Larry. ``He was just a skeleton covered 
with skin. He looked mummified. It was like famine you would see in 
a Third World country. He basically died a slow death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The third triplet was not abused and was placed in foster care,  
along with two other children who were not abused -- a 12-year-girl 
and a 10-year-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Their mother, Mary Bass, called authorities after finding Larry  
unconscious Wednesday evening. She pleaded innocent Wednesday to 
assault, abuse and neglect. Other charges could be filed when a 
coroner's report is received, Jackson County Prosecutor Robert 
Beaird said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old mother admitted punishing Larry and Gary by  
putting their feet in scalding water, locking them in a room and 
depriving them of food except bread and water for up to two weeks, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor had no theory as to why only two of the children  
were apparently abused. 
</P>
<P>
	Bass told police it was hard to work full-time and go back to  
school while trying to raise the five children, and began 
withholding food from the two boys this summer when she had trouble 
controlling them. 
</P>
<P>
	The other children were checked at a hospital, found to be in  
good shape and immediately placed in foster care, Forte said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They weren't shocked. They weren't screaming or anything when  
we told them we were going to take them,'' he said. ``In the girl's 
room, she had some books spread out with a notebook and a pencil 
like she had been studying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors said Bass, her children and her boyfriend moved into  
their neighborhood about a year ago, but were rarely seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never laid eyes on her,'' said Maxine Thomas, who lived two  
houses away. ``The man, he was introduced to me when they first 
moved in. He looked like a real nice man. But I never saw him 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baird said there were no plans to charge the boyfriend.  
</P>
<P>
	School teachers began seeing signs of neglect as long as two  
years ago, and alerted state social workers. It wasn't immediately 
clear whether all the children had been enrolled in school this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Missouri Division of Family Services declined to discuss the  
family's case or say if it had investigated. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0064 </DOCNO>
