<HEADLINE> Soybean slide continues / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures prices fell sharply today in  
early trading on the Chicago Board of Trade, extending a steep 
decline into a third day. Grains were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts of more rain in dry growing areas of Brazil and a  
technical followthrough to Thursday's slump sent soybeans to their 
lowest level in seven weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The wave of selling occurred just before the expiration of the  
November contract later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn dipped, pressured by the slide in soybeans.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also retreated amid weak U.S. export potential and a  
generally bearish outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1 1/4 cent to $2.55 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $1.99 1/2 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.09 a bushel; November soybeans fell 4 1/2 centS to 
$4.75 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were lower in early trading today on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .27 cent to 70.90 cents a pound;  
November feeder cattle fell .25 cent to 80.95 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs rose .45 cent to 49.20 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies fell .65 cent to 65.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
