<HEADLINE> Miss America Helps Homeless Vets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Miss America Heather French drew a  
congressional crowd to a Capitol Hill news conference Thursday 
where she opened her campaign to help homeless veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	With her crown perched on a nearby stool, Miss French said her  
father, a disabled Vietnam veteran, was the reason why ``a 
24-year-old fashion designer cares about veterans' issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss French, who was crowned on Sept. 18, said there were  
250,000 homeless veterans sleeping on the nation's streets and she 
had come to Washington because it was ``the one place that I 
thought I could make the biggest impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first Miss America from Kentucky was flanked by her state's  
Republican senators, Mitch McConnell and Jim Bunning, and several 
Kentucky representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he came from a  
state of many Miss Americas. But, pointing to recent decisions to 
boost spending for veterans' programs, Lott said, ``I've never seen 
a Miss America have an impact so quickly.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
