<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Fall on Brazil Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures took another tumble Friday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as rain in Brazil continued to ease concerns 
about dry planting conditions there. Grain prices were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
        Forecasts of more rain in northern areas of Brazil and a technical  
followthrough to Thursday's slump sent soybeans to their lowest level 
in seven weeks. 
</P>
<P>
        The wave of selling occurred as the November contract was expiring.  
</P>
<P>
        Corn edged lower, pushed downward by soybean selling, but losses  
were limited on a quiet trading day. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat prices were supported by continuing dry conditions in  
both northern Argentina and the southwestern U.S. winter wheat belt. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery rose 1 cent to $2.58 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $1.99 1/2 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.09 a bushel; November soybeans fell 7 cents to $4.72 
3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
        December cattle rose .43 cent to 69.20 cents a pound; November  
feeder cattle fell .10 cent to 81.10 cents a pound; December lean hogs 
rose .50 cent to 49.25 cents a pound; February frozen pork bellies 
fell 1.28 cent to 64.82 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
