<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Clarifies Rate Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's financial secretary is committed to  
the existing fixed exchange rate to the U.S. dollar, despite his 
comments in a newspaper suggesting the peg could be dropped, a 
government statement said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's Straits Times reported Friday that Financial  
Secretary Donald Tsang suggested Singapore and Hong Kong consider 
moving toward a common currency that could include other Asian 
currencies as part of a new global financial architecture. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel brave and courageous in even uttering these words. It's  
the unthinkable. But we must think the unthinkable now,'' the 
newspaper quoted Tsang as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	But a Hong Kong government statement late Friday said Tsang's  
comments on giving up Hong Kong's peg to the U.S. dollar were taken 
out of context. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government has no intention whatsoever to change the  
system. The Hong Kong dollar parity with the U.S. dollar has 
remained rock solid and unchanged since it was put it place,'' the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fixed rate gave ``the essential anchor and stability for  
trade to flourish,'' it added. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's currency is fixed at 7.80 Hong Kong dollars to the  
U.S. dollar, and Tsang was reported by the newspaper as suggesting 
a common regional currency patterned after the European monetary 
union could fend off financial instability. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
