<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Sign Hansen As Punter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the mystery surrounding Matt Turk's broken  
finger deepened Friday, the Washington Redskins signed 39-year-old 
Brian Hansen to punt in Sunday's game against the Dallas Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
	Hansen has played with New Orleans, New England, Cleveland and  
the New York Jets over a 14-year NFL career. He averaged 39.8 yards 
over seven games last season before the Jets released him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best guy we worked out,'' said coach Norv Turner, who  
auditioned six punters and wanted someone with good directional 
ability to minimize the threat from Cowboys return man Deion 
Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, no one wanted to say much about a report in The  
Washington Post that cast suspicion on Turk's injury. The report, 
which appeared beside a lengthy interview with owner Dan Snyder, 
cited unidentified sources who claimed the Redskins suspect that 
Turk broke his finger playing basketball Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That would appear to contradict the account of Turk's brother,  
long snapper Dan Turk, who said he saw Matt's injured left middle 
finger on the plane as the team returned from Sunday's game at 
Arizona. Both brothers thought it was only sprained, and Matt Turk 
did not report the injury until Tuesday. He had surgery Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post report said that Turk could be fined for not  
playing against the Cowboys if it is confirmed that the injury 
resulted from basketball and not football. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Turk has not commented on his injury. Dan Turk stood by his  
story Friday when asked by a reporter. Neither Turner nor general 
manager Vinny Cerrato would discuss the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no comment on all that,'' Cerrato said.  
</P>
<P>
	Turner left open the possibility that Hansen could remain with  
the team for more than one game. Meanwhile, quarterback Brad 
Johnson will assume Matt Turk's holding duties on field goals and 
extra points. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Hansen on the roster, the Redskins released  
guard Rod Milstead. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
