<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Prada Beats AmericaOne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Italy's Prada defeated San  
Francisco's AmericaOne in the challenger series for the America's 
Cup in a race marked by spinnaker problems for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	After racing was postponed Thursday because of gale-force wind,  
conditions were nearly perfect today for fast match racing among 
the syndicates fighting for the chance to take on New Zealand for 
sailing's most prized trophy next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the most anticipated and exciting race of the regatta so far,  
with a breeze blowing a steady 15 knots, skipper Francesco de 
Angelis' beat the Americans at the start and built a lead of 24 
seconds by the first turn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italians hit trouble after rounding the mark, twice losing  
their spinnaker -- and their lead -- in the first downwind leg of the 
12.5 nautical mile course on Hauraki Gulf when a shackle snapped 
open. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italians made up two boat lengths on the next leg and were  
within striking distance of Paul Cayard's AmericaOne as they headed 
downwind towards the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Cayard looked to have held off Prada when, with just a few  
hundred yards to go, the giant green spinnaker burst and collapsed 
into the water. 
</P>
<P>
	Prada powered past and won the race by 17 seconds. AmericaOne  
raised another spinnaker but crossed the line with shreds of the 
torn old sail flapping from the top of the mast. 
</P>
<P>
	Cayard said tactical mistakes had been made on board AmericaOne  
and that Prada would have led all the way if it wasn't for their 
equipment problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``They deserved to win,'' Cayard said. ``They had some bad luck  
on the first run and I think it was appropriate that we had some 
bad luck on the last run. I'm happy for the accounting to be that 
way. For the time being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was still confident AmericaOne would be one the boats  
in the challenger final series. 
</P>
<P>
	It was AmericaOne's first loss of the regatta, and ended what  
had been a three-way leadership deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	Prada went ahead on points but has yet to have their bye. New  
York challenger Young America is also undefeated, but must beat 
Prada in their next race, expected Saturday, to draw even, and go 
ahead of AmericaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	In other races, the Spanish Challenge defeated Young Australia  
by 37 seconds; America True defeated Stars and Stripes by 41 
seconds; Nippon defeated Le Defi Francais by 1 minute, 53 seconds; 
and Young America defeated Abradabra by 1 minute, 24 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of races on today was half that of previous days  
because of a local racing regatta on waters near the two challenger 
courses. 
</P>
<P>
	In more than 700 races over four months, the 11 challenger teams  
from seven countries score one point for each victory in the first 
of three round-robins, four points in the second and nine in the 
third. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of a finals series will meet Team New Zealand in a  
best-of-9 regatta starting in February 2000 for the America's Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
