<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warrick Cleared To Play vs. Clemson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Peter Warrick will rejoin Florida State  
in time for Saturday's game at Clemson after agreeing to deal in 
which he will serve no jail time on a theft charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The star receiver pleaded guilty today to misdemeanor petty  
theft in connection with a department store scam. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement met the university's standard for allowing him to  
play. The school had insisted that the Heisman Trophy contender 
would not play until he had served any jail time. 
</P>
<P>
	School spokesman Mark Riordan said Warrick will play against  
Clemson when coach Bobby Bowden goes for his 300th career victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to (President) Sandy D'Alemberte there are not  
further barriers, legal or institutional, that would keep Peter 
Warrick from representing this institution on the football field,'' 
Riordan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick has missed Florida State's last two games after being  
charged with felony grand theft Oct. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a fair resolution for the state, a fair resolution for  
Peter Warrick a fair resolution for the university,'' Warrick's 
lawyer, John Kenny, said. ``And we know it's a fair resolution for 
our fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick, a former teammate and a store clerk were charged with  
felony grand theft when the two players bought more than $400 worth 
of designer clothes Sept. 29 at a Dillard's department store for 
$21.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge John Crusoe agreed to terms in which Warrick will serve  
one year probation, donate the clothes to the Children's Home 
Society, pay $579 restitution, $295 in court costs, have no contact 
with Dillard's and spend 30 days on a work program where he will 
probably clean trash from city streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not wearing stripes, he's not in jail, and that's a  
significant determining factor for the university,'' Kenny said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't mean to diminish what he did, but folks it was a  
discount,'' Kenny said Friday. ``I know the state attorney looked 
at it that they could find a way to make it a felony.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old receiver was in South Carolina with his  
teammates for the Clemson game when the deal was struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden goes for the milestone victory against son Tommy Bowden,  
the Clemson coach, in the first father-son matchup in Division I-A 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenny and Warrick met Thursday night with Florida State  
president Sandy D'Alemberte, who had a problem with a player 
competing if he faced jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the jail or prison time behind someone before they  
play,'' D'Alemberte said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Kenny reached an agreement to reduce the  
charge to a misdemeanor with the state attorney, but that would 
have required the player to spend 30 days in jail at the end of the 
semester. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Dillard's clerk, Rachel Myrtil, pleaded no contest  
Thursday to grand theft and was sentenced to two years' probation, 
10 days on a county work program, ordered to pay $308 in court 
costs and stay out of Dillard's department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Laveranues Coles, who paid for the clothes, was kicked off the  
Florida State team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
