<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FIA Holds Hearing on Ferrari Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Ferrari made its case today before the FIA's  
International Court of Appeal in a bid to overturn its 
disqualification from last Sunday's Malaysian Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, to be announced Saturday by the FIA, was in the  
hands of a five-member panel of international lawyers, who heard 
testimony from Ferrari and two other F1 teams: McLaren Mercedes and 
Stewart Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing at the Hotel Crillon -- Paris' most exclusive hotel --  
took about four hours with Ferrari driver Eddie Irvine, sporting 
director Jean Todt and technical director Ross Brawn leading the 
Italian delegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine was pushed and shoved entering the hotel and struck on  
the head by a camera as a photographer lunged to get a better view 
in a scrum of hundreds of reporters and photographers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari team officials declined to talk with the media and left  
without comment, carrying a black bag containing the parts in 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart Ford's Paul Stewart departed and called it ``a fair and  
thorough hearing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferraris driven by Irvine and Michael Schumacher finished first  
and second in Malaysia but were disqualified because their 
aerodynamic deflectors didn't comply with FIA regulations. The 
deflectors missed the FIA specifications by three-eighths of an 
inch. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision gave victory -- and the 1999 Formula One  
championship -- to Mika Hakkinen, the McLaren driver who finished 
third in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	A win for Irvine would have given him a four-point lead going  
into the final race of the season, the Japanese Grand Prix on Oct. 
31. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari reportedly mounted a three-point defense: the deflectors  
didn't offer an advantage; the measurement might have been 
incorrect or should have allowed for a minimum tolerance; the error 
was unintentional. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari, which has not won a drivers' title since Jody Schecter  
in 1979, also was expected to say the punishment was too severe. 
</P>
<P>
	It needed to convince the panel to invoke FIA's clause on  
``exceptional circumstances'' to overturn a stewards' decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel has a range of options. It could uphold the decision,  
change it to a fine against Ferrari and reinstate the points, 
reinstate the drivers' points but remove the points from the 
Constructors' championship, overturn the entire decision, or 
stiffen the penalty and disqualify Ferrari from the Japanese Grand 
Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	McLaren's No. 2 driver David Coulthard attended the hearing.  
Hakkinen was on vacation in Asia, a McLaren official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, trying to protect the upgraded second and third places  
for Johnny Herbert and Rubens Barrichello, supported McLaren's 
argument that rules are rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams have to know where they stand on the regulations,'' he  
said. ``It's up to the court of appeal to decide if Ferrari is in 
the right or the wrong.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
