<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FIA Hears Ferrari F1 Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Any chance Ferrari has of winning its first Formula  
One drivers' title in 20 years rests with five international 
lawyers and their interpretation of ``exceptional circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari, with drivers Eddie Irvine and Michael Schumacher  
finishing 1-2, was disqualified at last Sunday's Malaysian Grand 
Prix because the cars' aerodynamic deflectors didn't comply with 
FIA regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-member FIA International Court of Appeal listened to  
more than four hours of closed-door testimony Friday. A decision 
was expected Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari, the biggest spending and longest suffering team in  
Formula One, is believed to have offered a three-point defense: 
</P>
<P>
	--The deflectors, missing FIA requirements by three-eighths of an  
inch, did not offer an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	--The measurement might have been incorrect or should have  
allowed for a minimum tolerance. 
</P>
<P>
	--Any error was unintentional.  
</P>
<P>
	If the panel rules for Ferrari, Irvine will get his victory back  
and hold a four-point lead over Mika Hakkinen of McLaren Mercedes 
entering the season-ending Japanese Grand Prix Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari pushed to invoke a FIA clause on ``exceptional  
circumstances'' to overturn the decision. The odds are against 
Ferrari -- 12 of 15 appeals to FIA's appeals court over the past 25 
years have been rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	If the panel rejects Ferrari's appeal, Hakkinen will keep the  
victory despite finishing third -- and keep his second straight 
season championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Any decision is bound to be controversial and open the world  
governing body of motor sports to criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals panel has several options.  
</P>
<P>
	It could uphold the decision; change it to a fine against  
Ferrari and reinstate the points; reinstate the drivers' points but 
remove the points from the constructors' championship; overturn the 
entire decision; or stiffen the penalty and disqualify Ferrari from 
the Japanese Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine was pushed and shoved entering the hotel Friday and  
struck on the head by a camera as a photographer lunged to get a 
better view in a scrum of hundreds of reporters and photographers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrari team officials left the hotel without comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The Stewart Ford team, trying to protect the upgraded second and  
third place for Johnny Herbert and Rubens Barrichello, supported 
McLaren's argument that rules must be enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Stewart, representing Stewart Ford, attended Friday's  
hearing and called it ``fair and thorough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams have to know where they stand on the regulations,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
