<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gillette Earnings Likely To Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Gillette Co.'s stock tumbled almost 10 percent  
this morning after the consumer products manufacturer warned that 
fourth-quarter sales and earnings are likely to decline because of 
inventory problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast cast a pall on a third-quarter earnings report late  
Thursday that met analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette shares fell $3.68 3/4 to $34.18 3/4 a share in early trading  
today on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and chief executive officer Michael C. Hawley said  
Thursday that industry consolidations were a primary reason why 
Gillette needed to reduced inventories -- especially blade 
inventories in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect that this corrective action will result in a  
fourth-quarter sales decline in the mid-single digits and a 
quarterly earnings decrease in the middle to high teens,'' said 
Hawley. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had been expecting earnings of 42 cents a share in the  
three months ending Dec. 31. In the year-ago fourth-quarter, 
Gillette earned $435 million, or 39 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawley said that despite the lowered fourth-quarter  
expectations, the strength of the Gillette's core businesses, 
coupled with the changes ``bode well for a return to (Gillette's) 
historic high growth rates in the near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Gillette reported third-quarter earnings of $352  
million, or 32 cents a share. Earnings, which were helped by 
increased blade and razor sales, were held back in part due to 
higher interest costs associated with a share repurchase program. 
</P>
<P>
	That result, which met the expectations of analysts surveyed by  
First Call/Thomson Financial is slightly below last year's 
operating income of $353 million, or 30 cents per share. Last 
year's results do not include a one-time reorganization charge of 
$347 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette's sales for the three-month period ending Sept. 30 were  
$2.51 billion, down from $2.53 billion in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston company's blade and razor sales increased by 9  
percent, and sales of Duracell batteries rose 6 percent, with 
Duracell profits up 25 percent compared with the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	But sales of Braun appliance products dropped 15 percent, and  
profits in that division fell by 39 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said unfavorable exchange rates and poor economic  
conditions in some markets were to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	For the nine-month period ending Sept. 30, sales dropped from  
$6.88 billion to $6.86 billion. Net income rose from $646 million 
to $921 million. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
