<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Committees OK Medicare Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that would restore more than $15  
billion previously cut from Medicare fees paid to health care 
providers is a step closer to congressional approval. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration and Democratic lawmakers have  
raised objections that much of the money would come out of 
Medicare's trust fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``We oppose it in its current form because it's not paid for,''  
said Richard Tarplin, the Health and Human Services Department's 
assistant secretary for legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Ways and Means and Senate Finance committees approved  
separate versions of the relief package Thursday, but without 
earmarking any offsetting savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means panel also rejected, in a party-line vote, a  
Democratic amendment that would have required drug companies to 
offer the same discounts on prescriptions to individual Medicare 
beneficiaries as they do to bulk purchasers such as private health 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the $15  
billion in additional Medicare fee payments need not be offset by 
new savings because the legislation would only give back money that 
has been saved in excess of what lawmakers intended when they 
approved Medicare cuts in their 1997 deal to balance the federal 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill has already been paid for ... by the overzealous  
cuts of the balanced budget act,'' said Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would give cash to hospitals, nursing homes, and  
others who complain they now get too little to care for the elderly 
and disabled. Health care providers have spent millions of dollars 
this year on advertising and lobbying campaigns aimed at winning 
back some Medicare money. 
</P>
<P>
	The desire to provide the relief is widely shared by Democrats  
and Republicans. It is expected to be the only action Congress 
takes on Medicare this year, after political divisions scuttled 
plans for a major overhaul of the program. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton administration officials said that the proposals  
approved Thursday could push forward by as much as a year -- from 
2015 to 2014 -- the date when Medicare's trust fund is expected to 
be depleted. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has suggested that some of the money needed  
could come from innovations in the way Medicare does business. 
Examples include competitive bidding by medical suppliers and 
giving retirees the chance to save money if they see doctors and 
other health care providers who agree to special discount contracts 
with Medicare -- much like the many private health plans' 
``preferred provider'' networks. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Ways and Means and Finance committees on Thursday  
rejected amendments offered by Democratic lawmakers that would have 
offset the caregiver relief package with ideas like Clinton's. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., pledged to  
consider such changes next year when Congress has more time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my intent to move right ahead with major hearings on  
Medicare reform. I intend to do everything I can to build 
consensus,'' said Roth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
