<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                    *Elizabeth Stauffer Collinson    	
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Elizabeth ``Betty'' Stauffer Collinson,  
a past director of the media group Stauffer Communications Inc., 
and wife of former Independence Examiner publisher T. Hall 
Collinson, died Tuesday in Venice, Fla. She was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Collinson's father, Oscar S. Stauffer, was a founder of  
Stauffer Communications. The Topeka, Kan.-based company was 
purchased by Morris Communications Corp. in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Christopher Drogoul    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Christopher Drogoul, an Atlanta banker who was  
caught up in a scandal involving $5.5 billion in loans to Iraq, 
died of cancer Monday. He was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Drogoul, the former manager of the Atlanta branch of Italy's  
government-owned Banca Nazional del Lavoro, was sentenced in 1993 
to three years in prison as a result of the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Drogoul was branch manager of the Italian bank from 1984 to  
1989. Federal authorities said the branch borrowed money from other 
banks then committed the funds to exporters to Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal came to light after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in  
August 1990, and Iraq defaulted on the loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democratic lawmakers alleged that Iraqi leader Saddam  
Hussein used at least some of the money to develop Iraq's military. 
Some also say Drogoul was a scapegoat in a larger conspiracy to aid 
Saddam before the invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	Drogoul ultimately pleaded guilty to wire fraud and submitting  
false reports to bank regulators and was sentenced in November 1993 
to prison. Several co-defendants also received prison terms. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal investigation later determined that BNL's top  
officials in Rome were not responsible for the fraud in Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Zeng Liansong    	
</P>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Zeng Liansong, who designed the national  
flag of the People's Republic of China, died Tuesday. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeng submitted his design of five gold stars on a red background  
in 1949 in response to a newspaper ad calling for recommendations 
for a flag for the newly communist nation. The stars represent the 
Communist Party, industry and commerce, farmers, students and the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	The flag first was raised on Oct. 1, 1949, over Beijing's  
Tiananmen Square by revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung when he 
declared the founding of the People's Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeng later became a company manager and a member of the Shanghai  
Municipal Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Jeanelle C. Moore    	
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Jeanelle C. Moore, the widow of former  
North Carolina Gov. Dan Moore, died Wednesday. She was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Moore worked for beautification of the state while her  
husband was in office from 1965 to 1969. She helped form the 
Governor's Beautification Committee, which was succeeded by Keep 
North Carolina Beautiful Inc. She became executive director of the 
nonprofit organization in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Moore also wrote ``The First Ladies of North Carolina,''  
and she was honorary chairwoman of a drive to raise $75,000 to 
build the Chapel of the Nameless Woman at Women's Prison in 
Raleigh. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Ross Parmenter    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ross Parmenter, author and a former music news  
editor at The New York Times, died Monday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Parmenter was on the music staff from 1940 until his retirement  
in 1964. He wrote news, features, criticism, and a column called 
``The World of Music.'' He joined the newspaper in 1934, covering 
shipping news. 
</P>
<P>
	Parmenter also wrote 12 books, several dealing with Mexico,  
where he frequently traveled. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Raymond L. Sullivan    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Raymond L. Sullivan, a former California  
Supreme Court justice and author of landmark rulings on school 
finance and injury lawsuits, died Wednesday. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan was appointed to the court in 1966 after 31 years of  
private law practice in San Francisco and five years as a state 
appellate judge. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from the court in 1977, then spent 16 years as a  
professor at Hastings College of the Law. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Sullivan's majority decisions found California's entire  
school finance system unconstitutional because each district's 
ability to raise money depended on local property values. The state 
was forced to equalize district funding and eventually moved away 
from local property taxes as a school revenue source. 
</P>
<P>
	Another of his majority decisions abolished a long-standing rule  
that denied all damages to injury victims if they were at fault to 
any degree in an accident. The ruling, which reduced a victim's 
damages only by the proportion of their own fault, became a 
standard nationwide. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U S West Earns $421 Million in 3Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- U S West Inc., the Baby Bell telephone company  
being acquired by Qwest Communications, posted an 11.1 percent gain 
in third-quarter income to beat Wall Street forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	The provider of local phone service through most of the Rocky  
Mountains and Pacific Northwest reported Friday an operating profit 
of $421 million or 83 cents a share for the period. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't reflect one-time factors such as $282 million in  
costs from breaking an agreement to merge with Global Crossing, a 
deal trumped by a higher bid from Qwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Including those expenses, Denver-based U S West had a net profit  
of $139 million, or 27 cents per share, for the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, when there were no one-time  
factors, U S West earned $379 million, or 75 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts had expected U S West to show an operating  
profit of just 80 cents a share, according to a survey by First 
Call/Thomson Financial. However, in Friday's trading on the New 
York Stock Exchange, U S West's shares slipped 43 3/4 cents to $59. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter revenues totaled $3.32 billion, up about 6.5  
percent from $3.11 billion in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement was driven by growth in Internet and other  
data-related services, custom calling features and private line 
services, the company said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
