<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glavine Ready to Duque it Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Orlando Hernandez's postseason stats make him  
look like Sandy Koufax. Against Atlanta, he's resembled Kenny 
Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Will it be Senor Smoke showing up for Game 1 of the World Series  
on Saturday night? Or will it be the ``El Duque'' who didn't make 
it past the fifth inning in his two regular-season starts against 
the Braves? 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy's really good,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said  
Friday. ``He's not starting tomorrow because he's average. He's a 
really tough guy out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, Bobby, not when he faces the Braves.  
</P>
<P>
	Tom Glavine, the Braves' starter for the opener, beat Hernandez  
7-2 when they met in New York on June 23, 1998, sending ``El 
Duque'' to his first major league loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez allowed six runs -- three earned -- and six hits in 3  
2-3 innings in that one, but that was a great outing compared with 
his 1999 start against Atlanta, when he gave up eight hits, four of 
them homers, and six runs in 4 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	So while he's 29-11 against the rest of the major leagues, he's  
0-2 against Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, keeping up his season-long habit of saying almost  
nothing about himself, wouldn't address the question of what 
adjustments he needed to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be able to say, as far as my technique and  
approach, what I'm going to do,'' he said through a translator. '' 
Obviously, it's something I should do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine, 4-3 in the World Series and 10-11 in postseason play,  
lost to David Cone in Game 3 of the 1996 Series, but is 2-0 with 
one no-decision against the Yankees in the regular season. He beat 
Roger Clemens on July 15, allowing two runs and six hits in 6 2-3 
innings, and has never allowed more than two runs in any of his 
starts against the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	He struggled this season, losing his first three decisions, and  
was just 3-7 before beating the Yankees. He finished 14-11, 
matching his fewest wins since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried so many adjustments, tried to figure out so many  
things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in late August, he finally got his mechanics straightened  
out, 
</P>
<P>
	``From that point on, the only thing I tried to do was get the  
ball and be as natural as I could,'' he said. ``A lot of it is 
mental.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez seems to make those type of adjustments pitch by  
pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can come at it at all angles,'' Cox said. ``He can get you  
off- balance, straighten you up and still make you lunge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees think it all goes back to last October and Game 4 of  
the AL Championship Series against Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a 114-48 regular season and 3-0 sweep of Texas in the  
first round, New York won its opener against the Indians, but lost 
Games 2 and 3. It was the first time all year the Yankees felt 
pressure, especially because they felt they had to win the World 
Series to validate their record-setting regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez pitched seven shutout innings, allowing three hits,  
starting the Yankees on a 12-game postseason winning streak that 
only ended with Roger Clemens' loss at Boston in Game 3 of the ALCS 
last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Hernandez is 4-0 with a 0.97 ERA in the postseason.  
Koufax's World Series ERA -- there were no playoffs then, was 0.95 
but his record was just 4-3, meaning ``El Duque'' can top him in 
wins Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you do it, now you realize it's in your memory bank,''  
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Then you do it again, and now, we 
expect it every time we send him out there. It's not saying he's 
going to win tomorrow night, but I know one thing: He's going to 
empty the tank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine says the key is not trying to change things just because  
it's the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many times,'' he said, ``people talk about somebody who  
steps it up, and it's like, OK, I'm going to step it up now, I'm 
going to throw harder, my slider's going to be better, my 
curveball's going to bite more and I'm going to throw everything in 
the black. I don't think you can do that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
