<HEADLINE> Stocks Close Higher; Dow Up 172.56 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply Friday, led by financial  
shares that soared on hopes that legislation will soon allow banks, 
stock brokerages and insurance companies to merge. The rally capped 
a volatile week in which the Dow industrials rose 450 points, 
wiping out much of last week's stunning loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last Friday, we ended the week in a state of despair. This  
Friday, the market is in a state of euphoria,'' said Scott Bleier, 
chief investment strategist at Prime Charter Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 172.56 to close at  
10,470.25, gaining 450.54 on the week after a 630.05-point loss 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 18.04 to 1,301.65, and the Nasdaq  
composite index rose 14.57 to 2,816.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks drove the market higher after Republicans and  
Democrats in Congress settled a dispute that had threatened to 
derail efforts to overhaul the nation's financial services laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations involved legislation that would dismantle  
Depression-era laws that restrict banks, brokerage firms and 
insurance companies from merging. The prospect of new business 
combinations and a fresh wave of mergers rejuvenated financial 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow components J.P. Morgan rose 8 7/16 to 125 5/8 and American  
Express rose 3 3/4 to 148 5/8. Investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; 
Jenrette gained 7 1/8 to 46 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts suggested financial services stocks were also ready  
for a rebound after being deflated in recent weeks by worries about 
higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of these stocks had been beaten down and left for dead,''  
said Bleier. ``The market has known about this legislation for a 
long time, so I don't think it's entirely responsible for the 
strength of the group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With no major economic reports to steer the market, investors  
were able to focus on the continuing flood of company reports on 
the just-ended third-quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market has had two major worries: short-term interest  
rates and earnings,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at 
Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``This week, we put interest rates behind us a bit 
so that we could focus on earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate earnings have, for the most part, met analysts' lofty  
estimates this quarter. But as expectations have soared, investors 
have proven willing to punish any companies that disappoint. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM set off a steep selloff by warning late Wednesday that  
customers are postponing purchases of network and database machines 
because of the Year 2000 computer bug. The Dow fell as much as 213 
points Thursday before most stocks began a gradual recovery that 
left the Dow with a loss of 94.67. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, IBM rose 2 15/16 to 93 15/16.  
</P>
<P>
	Gillette received a more gentle punishment Friday, sliding 1 7/8 to  
36 following a report late Thursday that met most profit forecasts 
but warned of weak fourth-quarter sales and earnings due to 
inventory problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The stream of corporate earnings reports peaked this week,  
leading many market watchers to believe investors will once again 
focus on interest rates next week. Government reports on the gross 
domestic product and employment costs are expected to provide the 
latest sense of whether inflation is escalating. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are concerned that the Federal Reserve will raise  
short-term interest rates at its next meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume totaled 1.14 
billion shares, compared with 1.22 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.42 to 418.69.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average slipped 0.05 percent.  
Germany's DAX index rose 2.1 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 2.0 
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.6 percent higher. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
