<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LSU Has Mississippi State's Number </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi State is motivated more by  
a losing streak than its nine straight regular-season victories. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because no matter how much success the 12th-ranked  
Bulldogs (6-0, 3-0 Southeastern Conference) have had in recent 
years, they haven't been able to beat LSU, regardless of how bad 
the Tigers have been. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have beat us seven straight times. That's our No. 1  
motivation. We owe them,'' senior linebacker Barrin Simpson said. 
``It doesn't matter what their record is, they have talent and play 
their best football against us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi State, one of just seven undefeated I-A teams, is  
home for the first time in a month when it plays host to LSU (2-4, 
0-4) on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	While the defending SEC West champion Bulldogs are off to their  
best start in 55 years, things have gotten so bad at LSU that 
athletics director Joe Dean was forced this week to publicly refute 
rumors that coach Gerry DiNardo was being fired midseason. 
</P>
<P>
	DiNardo knows the rumors and distractions have affected his  
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``How positively and how negatively, that's the uncertain thing.  
I just know it's human nature,'' said DiNardo, the fifth-year coach 
who has refused to discuss his future status. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers have lost seven straight SEC games and 10 of 11.  
Their lone league victory in that span was 41-6 last October 
against the Mississippi State team that went on to win the SEC 
West. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs haven't beaten LSU since 1991, coach Jackie  
Sherrill's first in Starkville. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the Bulldogs have won their first SEC football title  
of any kind since 1941, played in four postseason bowl games and 
won 50 games -- none of them against LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I've seen is that there are a lot of teams that have made  
some plays against them and that has hurt,'' Sherrill said of LSU. 
``But they've got an awful lot of talent. And LSU has always played 
us tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LSU is the next hurdle as the Bulldogs try to strengthen their  
position to defend the SEC West title. Three of their last five 
games are at home, but one of their road games is Nov. 13 at 
10th-ranked Alabama (5-1, 4-0). 
</P>
<P>
	With a victory over LSU, the Bulldogs would become the last of  
the current 12 SEC teams to start a season with seven straight 
victories. They would also have a 4-0 SEC record for the first time 
in school history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to think down the road, or we many never get  
there. There are so many potholes and so many curves,'' Sherrill 
said. ``Things could flip-flop in a hurry since we have five tough 
games in a row.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi State knows about those late season reversals of  
fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Mississippi State was 7-2 before losing its last  
two games. The Bulldogs missed a chance to win the SEC West title 
and were left out of the postseason altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Bulldogs won the West and made it to the SEC  
Championship Game last year, they lost in the title game to 
eventual national champ Tennessee and then were beaten by Texas in 
the Cotton Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our motto is to finish. We don't think last year that we  
finished,'' senior defensive back Ashley Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson said the last two years have taught the Bulldogs ``how  
to finish and to play the whole season strong. It helped us learn 
how to win and play in big games and finish out the season.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
