<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Water Fluoridation a Health Boon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Adding fluoride to the water supply led to a  
sharp decline in children's cavities during the second half of the 
20th century, federal researchers reported this week. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report issued Thursday, the Centers for Disease Control and  
Prevention called the drop one of the century's most significant 
advances in public health. 
</P>
<P>
	At the beginning of the century, nearly everyone in every age  
group in the United States had some sort of tooth decay. The most 
common treatment was to simply remove the teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, tooth decay was so rampant that the leading cause for  
rejection from the military during both world wars was a shortage 
of teeth, the CDC said in its latest report on the century's health 
advances. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1931, the National Institute of Health hired dental surgeon  
H. Trendley Dean to study discolored tooth enamel. In trying to 
find out whether fluoride -- a mineral found in food and water -- was 
the culprit, he learned it decreased the number of cavities. 
</P>
<P>
	Many cities quickly added fluoride to their public water  
supplies. The result was a 40 percent to 70 percent decline in 
cavities among children during the second half of the century. 
Fluoride also added to toothpaste, mouth rinses, tablets and drops. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the report said, ``tooth loss is no longer  
considered inevitable, and increasingly adults in the United States 
are retaining most of their teeth for a lifetime.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
