<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 12:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Father-Son Matchup On the Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEMSON, S.C. (AP) -- Saturday night will probably find Ann  
Bowden sitting way up in the stands of Memorial Stadium, where she 
can let her emotions out without anyone noticing. 
</P>
<P>
	On one side of the field will be her husband, Bobby, the coach  
of top-ranked Florida State. On the other will be her son Tommy, 
the coach of Clemson. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time in history a father has coached  
against his son in a major college football game. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Bowden, 69, will be trying to become the fifth big-time  
coach to win 300 games and join such legends as Bear Bryant and Joe 
Paterno. His 45-year-old son will be trying to stop him. The stakes 
are especially high for the elder Bowden, whose No. 1-ranked 
Florida State team, with a 7-0 record, is vying for the national 
championship. Clemson is 3-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm going to retreat up to the end zone in a high seat  
and sit there so I can kind of let my emotions hang out,'' said 
Mrs. Bowden, Bobby's wife of 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	For more than 20 years, the Bowdens have been college football's  
first family of coaching. Three of Bobby's four sons went into 
coaching, and two daughters are married to former football players, 
one of whom is now a coach. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, with most of the Bowden family on hand, father will  
try to outfox son, and son will counter with every trick he has 
picked up from his father, all on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told my players not to think about that Tommy boy stuff,''  
Bobby said Thursday, ``because it ain't going to be no friendly 
affair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was inevitable Bobby would end up coaching against one of his  
sons. It was supposed to be Terry, until he resigned last year as 
the coach of Auburn. But it may be fitting that Tommy is about to 
become the first to match wits against his father. They are similar 
in so many ways. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I've observed all my children coming up, Tommy's reactions  
and responses were more like I felt I used to be,'' Bobby said. 
``He's a scaredy cat. I was usually afraid to try things. Cautious, 
I guess you would say. It's like going into a cold swimming pool. 
Terry would just run and jump in, never even look to see if they 
had water in there. And Jeffrey and my older son Steve, they were 
both very much the same way, they'd jump right in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As early as sixth grade, Tommy wrote a class paper about  
becoming a football coach like Dad. Later, Tommy was a wide 
receiver at West Virginia for his father in the early 1970s. When 
fans hung his father in effigy from a tree after a tough loss, it 
was Tommy who took down the figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he took the job last year at Clemson, which is in the  
same conference as Florida State, Tommy talked to his father on the 
phone several times a week. In addition to religion and life in 
general, they talked football, exchanging game films, discussing 
strategy and trading stories. 
</P>
<P>
	This year is different. The calls are down to two a week, and  
there's no exchange of films. 
</P>
<P>
	``No way can we share the things we usually do,'' Bobby told  
Tommy. ``Now that we're playing, I have to be very careful. I don't 
reveal any secrets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked this week if he would feel any guilt if Clemson upset  
Florida State and spoiled his father's chance of winning a national 
title, Tommy said: ``No. None whatsoever. There would be none for 
him, either.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
