<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Upgrades D.C. Counterterrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mobilizing for possible chemical or biological  
terrorism, the FBI has formed a special squad to respond to any 
attack in the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50-member National Capital Domestic Response Unit would work  
with about a dozen other federal, state and local public safety 
agencies in the District of Columbia, northern Virginia and 
suburban Maryland in the event of an emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We take every threat that comes up every day seriously,'' said  
Gregg Horner, a spokesman for the FBI's Washington field office. 
The unit was spun off about a month ago from a larger FBI operation 
to deal exclusively with threats and suspicious packages in 
Washington and its suburbs, Horner said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are chemical and biological experts, bomb disposal  
squads, and evidence specialists involved in the effort,'' said 
Horner, who added that tactical weapons specialists are available 
when necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an FBI official, trained specialists are called to  
deal with three to six suspicious packages a day in downtown 
Washington. If necessary, specialists from the Secret Service, the 
Bureau of Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms, the district's fire and 
rescue and police departments can mobilize hundreds of additional 
personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the area law enforcement agencies are working together,''  
said Sgt. Joe Gentile, spokesman for the Metropolitan Police 
Department. An investigator-liaison from the district's police 
force is assigned full-time to the FBI field office for 
counterterrorism purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, various agencies helped cordon off a 20-block area of  
downtown Washington when a homeless man found a suspicious package 
in an alley behind a hotel. The leather valise contained welding 
tools that had been taken from a nearby construction site. The 
agencies also cooperated in the investigation of a pair of 
``anthrax,'' hoaxes at the Old Executive Office Building next to 
the White House and The Washington Post building in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO summit in April was the type of event that the  
counterterrorism task force addresses. Another will be the New 
Year's Eve American Millennium Celebration on the National Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll all be working 12-hour shifts, '' said Gentile. The  
district's 3,520 police officers have been told that all leaves 
have been canceled between Dec. 27 and Jan. 15 to ensure public 
safety during the first weeks of the new year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
