<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Russia Contradicts Itself on Chechnya  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian officials contradicted themselves  
Friday on whether their forces were responsible for the attack that 
killed at least 143 people in Chechnya's capital, with political 
leaders denying any Russian role even after a military spokesman 
said it was a special operation. At least 10 Russian missiles 
slammed into the central market in Grozny and other parts of the 
city center on Thursday. Chechnya's Health Ministry put the death 
toll at 143. Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin confirmed that 
there had been a blast at the market, but he stressed it was a 
weapons base. 

</P>
<P>
	Internment Memorial Breaks Ground  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt recalled ``a  
sad chapter'' in U.S. history today as he joined in breaking ground 
near the Capitol for a memorial to Japanese-Americans who were 
interned or fought during World War II. More than 115,000 
Japanese-Americans were interned during World War II. The Japanese 
American Memorial Commission surpassed its goal of $8.6 million to 
build the monument, due to be completed in a year. It collected 
$10.1 million and now hopes to reach $11 million by the end of the 
year. The surplus is to be used for an educational campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Unabomber Appeal To Be Heard  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court agreed today to  
hear Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski's request for a new trial, where 
he would face a possible death sentence. Kaczynski, a 
Harvard-trained mathematician who became a recluse, pleaded guilty 
in 1998 to mail bombings that killed three people and injured 23. 
The Justice Department had agreed to the guilty plea and life 
sentence after a psychiatric examination concluded Kaczynski was a 
paranoid schizophrenic but competent to stand trial. The exam had 
been arranged by Kaczynski's lawyers over his objections. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel Rejects Primary Date Change  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iowa and New Hampshire will have the kickoff  
of the Democratic presidential selection process all to themselves 
after a panel refused today to allow four other states to move 
their contests into February behind the leaders. A rules panel of 
the Democratic National Committee denied requests from Arizona, 
Michigan, South Carolina and Washington state to move their 
presidential primaries or caucuses into February. They sought the 
change to save money and stay competitive with state Republican 
parties that have moved events into February. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Says He Won't Go Negative  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House liberals said Democratic presidential  
candidate Bill Bradley told them today he won't engage in a 
``bloodletting'' negative campaign against Vice President Al Gore. 
Bradley also picked up an endorsement from Rep. Diana DeGette, 
D-Colo., only the third House member to publicly back the former 
New Jersey senator. Three Senate Democrats have also endorsed 
Bradley. Bradley told a closed-door meeting of about 20 members of 
the House Progressive Caucus that he thought personal attacks were 
ineffective and would hurt the Democratic Party, participants said 
afterwards. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons Host Philanthropy Conference  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton today hosted a conference highlighting the future of 
philanthropy in America. Participants in the first such conference 
spoke of a need to appeal more directly to baby boomers and 
Generation X. America Online Inc. founder Steve Case highlighted a 
new philanthropic Internet portal that offers an easy way to donate 
to over 620,000 charities. ``Silicon Valley and the whole venture 
capital, high-tech community needs to be at the forefront of what 
we're doing,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Decries Violence Against Serbs  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's new secretary-general turned  
his attention Friday to the rash of violence against Kosovo's 
minority Serbs, saying the alliance would not permit any ethnic 
group rule the province. In his first visit to Kosovo since being 
named secretary-general, George Robertson told ethnic Albanian 
rebels aiming to get even for the Serb crackdown that ``vigilante 
justice is no justice.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Week on a Positive Note  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial closed up 172.56 at  
10,470.25 today. The rally capped a volatile week in which the Dow 
industrials rose 450.54 after a 630.05-point loss last week. 
Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners 
1,960-1,062. The Nasdaq composite index was up 14.57 to 2,816.52. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Defeat Hurricanes 7-3  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Geoff Sanderson and Erik Rasmussen each  
scored twice as Buffalo routed the Carolina Hurricanes 7-3 tonight, 
the Sabres' first win of the season. Martin Biron made 17 saves in 
place of benched goaltender Dominik Hasek and Michael Peca scored 
his first goal of the season for the Sabres (1-5-2), who hadn't won 
since Game 5 of the Stanley Cup finals. Curtis Brown and Miroslav 
Satan added goals for Buffalo, while Sami Kapanen scored twice and 
Gary Roberts added a goal for Carolina (3-2-3). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
