<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer, Keyes Meet in GOP Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DERRY, N.H. (AP) -- Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes were the only  
participants in New Hampshire's first forum for Republican 
presidential candidates and both took advantage of the opportunity 
to blast their rivals for failing to show up. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah planned to attend, but was detained in  
Washington. He offered greetings and an apology by satellite before 
Thursday night's half-hour event. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer and Keyes criticized their opponents -- and Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush in particular -- for their unwillingness to attend 
the WNDS-TV forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's sad Gov. Bush has not shown up tonight,'' Bauer  
said. ``I think the front-runners in the party are relying on their 
bank accounts, not their ideas. I think that's going to backfire on 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes agreed, calling the absence of other candidates a  
``reflection of their contempt for the democratic process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a bunch of people who think this race is already  
determined by their name or their money,'' the former U.N. 
ambassador said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the event's host took a not-so-subtle jab at the absentees.  
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you wonder whether other candidates with more dollars  
and higher poll numbers really want to debate,'' said news director 
Jack Heath. 
</P>
<P>
	In the most recent poll by the American Research Group Inc. of  
Manchester, Keyes and Bauer were in low single digits while Hatch 
registered 0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer and Keyes are both courting Christian conservatives. When  
asked how they would persuade other voters to support them, Keyes 
said his goals stem from the fundamental principles the country was 
founded upon, ideals that transcend religion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter what someone's race or background is because  
we can stand as Americans together,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said he doesn't hide his faith, but is running as a  
``Reagan Republican'' whose views on the economy and other key 
issues will appeal to a wide segment of voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last time I checked, Buddhists were as concerned about lower  
taxes as anyone,'' said Bauer, who was vice president of a group 
called Focus on the Family from 1989 until 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair diverged most widely on the campaign finance issue,  
with Bauer supporting a ban on soft money contributions to 
political parties and an increase in the limit on donations that 
individuals can make to campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shouldn't have government financing of campaigns, but I do  
think we should have reform,'' he said. ``If someone can write a $5 
million check and give it to the Democratic National Committee or 
the Republican National Committee, that's going to buy some 
access.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes said campaign financing should be completely unregulated.  
</P>
<P>
	``We ought to abolish this whole phony system of regulation,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes said only individual voters should be able to contribute  
to campaigns, but should be allowed to do so without limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``There should be total publicity,'' he said. ``The minute they  
give that donation, everyone in American ought to know it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both candidates said the growing incidence of school violence  
stems from a breakdown in families and the nation's moral decline. 
They also agreed that the federal government has too much control 
over education. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
