<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 08:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tide To Host Vols in Tuscaloosa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- The last time Tennessee played Alabama  
at Tuscaloosa, Bear Bryant still was in high school, the stadium 
held only 12,000 fans and the Crimson Tide won its fourth straight 
Southern Conference championship. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third Saturday in October in 1930.  
</P>
<P>
	The two schools have played every year since, traditionally on  
the third Saturday of October. But Alabama hosted its games in 
Birmingham after that, keeping the Volunteers off its campus for 
nearly seven decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium is now called Bryant-Denny, and will hold a sellout  
crowd of 83,818 for the Vols' return Saturday, as No. 10 Alabama 
(5-1, 4-0 Southeastern Conference) faces No. 5 Tennessee (4-1, 
2-1). 
</P>
<P>
	``We've talked about the importance of playing in Bryant-Denny,  
and not just this game, but all the conference games,'' Alabama 
coach Mike DuBose said. ``There is no question there is a different 
atmosphere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer doesn't know what to expect  
Saturday. He last visited Tuscaloosa as an Alabama recruit in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	He can probably get some advice from quarterback Tee Martin, a  
Mobile native who was recruited by Alabama. Martin saw the Tide 
play Tennessee in Legion Field, and made a second visit to a game 
at Bryant-Denny. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different atmosphere,'' Martin said of the Bryant-Denny  
games. ``You're playing on campus. There will be more students 
there and more fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Martin dismisses the idea that it will affect the Vols.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a big deal,'' he said. ``We're trying to worry more  
about their defense and offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That should be the attitude for both teams because the loser  
will be out of the Bowl Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is so deeply rooted, the tradition of this game,'' Fulmer  
said. ``It's very important. It's a classic kind of game, always 
clean and hard fought. There is always a lot of emotion and 
excitement, especially now that we're both in the Top 10. The 
stakes are higher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vols have beaten the Tide four straight times, their longest  
winning streak in series history. The fact is not lost on DuBose, 
who gathered his team last week and asked any player to raise his 
hand if he had ever beaten Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody raised their hand,'' receiver Jason McAddley said. ``So  
he was like, `Stay focused.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	All eyes will be on Alabama tailback Shaun Alexander, who has  
shredded every defense he has faced this year. He has rushed for at 
least 100 yards in all six games, and has done it against some of 
the top run-stoppers in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week against Mississippi -- which was No. 2 in the nation at  
stopping the run -- Alexander had 214 yards and three touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, he gets the Vols, who are ranked third against the  
run. Tennessee has allowed only 64.4 yards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shaun Alexander is an exceptional player, which is an  
understatement,'' Fulmer said. ``He's done everything you could ask 
a running back to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stoudamire Has Reasons To Smile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- In Toronto, Damon Stoudamire was the  
scorer. In two partial seasons with the Portland Trail Blazers he 
was the distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with two new teammates who can assume some of the  
point-guard duties, he's hoping to be something in between. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire averaged nearly 20 points a game in 2 1/2 seasons with  
the Raptors before being traded to Portland, his hometown, in 
February 1998. His role immediately changed from that of scorer to 
strictly playmaker, and his point production dropped to 12.6 per 
game during the lockout-shortened season. 
</P>
<P>
	With the offseason acquisitions of Scottie Pippen and Steve  
Smith, both veterans who can handle the ball, Stoudamire is looking 
forward to showing that his offensive flash hasn't dimmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happier,'' he said. ``As long as I don't have to bring the  
ball up the court every time, I'm going to find a way to get to the 
basket or make something happen. When I'm in my attack mode, it's 
either going to be a bucket or a foul. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you can always make plays for somebody else, but nobody  
can make them for you in return, that gets very frustrating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trading for Pippen and Smith and signing free agent Detlef  
Schrempf also has shifted the spotlight from Stoudamire, who did 
not react well to pressure during the Blazers' four-game sweep by 
San Antonio in the Western Conference finals last season. 
</P>
<P>
	After missing a key free throw late in Game 2 that allowed the  
Spurs' Sean Elliott to win it with a 3-pointer, Stoudamire blasted 
Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy for playing Greg Anthony more than him 
in crunch time. Stoudamire even said signing a seven-year, $81 
million contract extension before the season might have been a 
mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire's comments perplexed his coach, raised the eyebrows  
of the seasoned Spurs and caused the player to be vilified on 
sports talk shows and in newspapers across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	His low point came in Game 3, when the Rose Garden crowd booed  
him. It only got worse when he shot just 1-for-12 and the Blazers 
lost by 22 points. Two nights later, Portland lost again and 
Stoudamire wept after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	As trade rumors sprang up, Stoudamire traveled to the Bahamas  
and all over the United States, returning to Portland only to 
conduct free basketball camps and other community service events. 
</P>
<P>
	``I traveled around the country and around the world for a  
couple months, just to get away from the game and do some other 
things,'' Stoudamire said. ``That was fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers are 4-0 this preseason and are looking more  
comfortable with each other every time out. In their first home 
exhibition against Golden State last week, Stoudamire was 
sensational, getting 10 points and six assists in a 37-point first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he'll get better shots on our team because we move the  
ball better, and we pass the ball better,'' Dunleavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three nights later against Phoenix, however, Anthony showed why  
Dunleavy went to him so often with the game on the line. 
Stoudamire, returning to the McKale Center in Tucson for the first 
time since leaving Arizona in 1995, watched from the bench as 
Anthony scored 10 points in the fourth quarter to lead the Blazers 
back from an 85-78 deficit to a 117-110 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire would like to boost his scoring average back up to  
the 15-point range, but said he won't mind if he isn't the center 
of attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that people don't understand is that I never really  
wanted to score 20 here,'' he said. ``That never really was my goal 
when I got traded here to Portland. I've always wanted to lead the 
league in assists, because I was always right up there with the 
high numbers in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not even too concerned about how my scoring opportunities  
are going to come. I know I'll have more, just because I've got 
guys that know how to create for other people, just the same way I 
can create for them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0117 </DOCNO>
