<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Approves Eye Laser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration has approved  
an eye laser for use in a procedure to correct nearsightedness. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said Thursday it had approved a laser made by Summit  
Technology of Waltham, Mass., for use in the surgery in which a 
doctor cuts a flap in the outer layer of the cornea and then uses 
the laser to remove a small amount of the tissue beneath. 
</P>
<P>
	The procedure is known as lasik, for laser in-situ  
keratomileusis. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies have shown that the surgery can improve nearsightedness  
in patients with or without astigmatism, although a small number of 
patients have side effects ranging from severe halo to loss of 
corrected vision. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 1,013 patients treated with the laser in tests at 13 medical  
centers, 92 percent were corrected to 20-40 or better and 47 
percent to 20-20 or better without glasses or contact lenses, the 
FDA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Summit Technology laser is the second approved for this  
procedure. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
