<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *John Bromwich    	
</P>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- John Bromwich, a two-time Australian  
Open champion whose ambidextrous play allowed him to hit forehands 
with both hands, died Friday of a heart attack. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his tennis career was interrupted by World War II,  
Bromwich won the Australian Open in 1939 and 1946. He played 51 
Davis Cup matches from 1937-50, winning 19 of 30 singles matches 
and 20 of 21 doubles matches. 
</P>
<P>
	His greatest successes came in doubles. In 1948, he won the  
Wimbledon doubles title with Frank Sedgman. He won at Wimbledon 
again in 1950 with Adrian Quist. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich was a three-time U.S. Open doubles champion and won  
Wimbledon mixed doubles titles with Louise Brough in 1947-48. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Christopher Drogoul    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Christopher Drogoul, an Atlanta banker who was  
caught up in a scandal involving $5.5 billion in loans to Iraq, 
died Monday of cancer. He was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Drogoul, the former manager of the Atlanta branch of Italy's  
government-owned Banca Nazional del Lavoro, was sentenced in 1993 
to three years in prison as a result of the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities said the branch borrowed money from other  
banks then committed the funds to exporters to Iraq. The scandal 
came to light after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990, and 
Iraq defaulted on the loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Drogoul pleaded guilty to wire fraud and submitting false  
reports to bank regulators. A federal investigation determined that 
BNL's top officials in Rome were not responsible for the fraud in 
Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Rosalie Hearst    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Rosalie Hearst, philanthropist and  
longtime supporter of the Hearst Foundation's United States Senate 
Youth Program, died Friday at home of circulatory failure. She was 
84. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the widow of George R. Hearst, the oldest of the five  
sons of newspaper magnate William Randolph Hearst. 
</P>
<P>
	Her stepson, George Randolph Hearst Jr., is chairman of the  
board of The Hearst Corp., owner of the San Francisco Examiner and 
other newspaper, magazine and broadcast holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	She is also survived by a stepdaughter, Phoebe Hearst Cooke of  
Woodside, Calif. 

</P>
<P>
                          *H. Stuart Hughes    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- H. Stuart Hughes, an author and scholar of  
European history best known for his trilogy of works on the 
intellectual scene in Europe in the 19th and 20th centuries, died 
Thursday of pneumonia. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	A longtime professor at the University of California, San Diego,  
Hughes wrote a dozen books, including the autobiography ``Gentleman 
Rebel'' in 1990 and the trilogy ``Consciousness and Society'' in 
1958, ``The Obstructed Path'' in 1968, and ``The Sea Change'' in 
1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in New York City, Hughes earned a doctorate in history from  
Harvard University, then taught at Brown University until 1941 when 
he enlisted in the Army. He later served as chief of the State 
Department's division of research for Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, a grandson of former U.S. Supreme Court Chief Justice  
Charles Evans Hughes, ran for a U.S. Senate seat in Massachusetts 
in 1962 and headed an organization in favor of a nuclear 
disarmament alliance from 1967 to 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	He received a Guggenheim Fellowship and a 1997 award for  
scholarly distinction from the American Historical Association. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Curtis E. Jones    	
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Curtis E. Jones, the former Mellon National  
Corporation president, died Thursday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was affiliated with Mellon and its predecessors for more  
than 43 years until his retirement in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones worked to attract new investors to the Pittsburgh area as  
the steel industry began to decline, Mellon chairman and chief 
executive officer Martin McGuinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones joined the Union Trust Company of Pittsburgh in 1936. He  
was named president of Mellon National Corporation and to the 
Mellon board of directors in May 1974. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Mae Street Kidd    	
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Mae Street Kidd, a campaigner for open  
housing and racial equality as one of the first black women in the 
General Assembly, died Wednesday. Kidd was believed to be in her 
mid-90s. 
</P>
<P>
	She was elected to the House in 1967, having come up through  
Jefferson County's Democratic ward clubs, the Urban League and the 
NAACP during the civil rights movement. She lost re-election and 
served her last session in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	She focused her legislative efforts on housing, women and race  
issues. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Penelope Mortimer    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Penelope Mortimer, whose semi-autobiographical  
stories explored the emotional impact of failing marriages among 
the British upper classes, died Tuesday. She was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Ms. Mortimer's dozen novels were well-received, and  
``The Pumpkin Eater,'' published in 1962, was made into a film 
starring James Mason and Anne Bancroft. She also wrote two 
acclaimed volumes of memoirs and several television screenplays. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mortimer published her first novel, ``Johanna,'' in 1947  
under the name Penelope Dimont. At the time she had been married 
for 10 years to the journalist Charles Dimont. Divorced by 1949, 
she married John Mortimer. 
</P>
<P>
	The first volume of her memoirs, ``About Time,'' won the  
Whitbread Prize in 1979. The second part, published in 1993, 
included a frank account of her troubled marriage to Mortimer, 
which ended in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1986, she published ``Queen Elizabeth: A Life of the Queen  
Mother,'' which provoked controversy because of its allegations 
about the beloved royal's romantic life before her marriage to the 
future King George VI. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Wayne Oates    	
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Wayne Oates, a pioneer in the field of  
pastoral care and counseling, died Thursday. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Oates was credited most often for the integration of theology  
with psychology and psychiatry. He wrote more than 50 books on the 
relationship between faith and healing and established the Wayne E. 
Oates Institute in Louisville in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute promotes dialogue among the medical, religious,  
social work and various therauptic communities. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Ross Parmenter    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ross Parmenter, author and a former music news  
editor at The New York Times, died Monday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Parmenter was on the music staff from 1940 until his retirement  
in 1964. He wrote news, features, criticism, and a column called 
``The World of Music.'' He joined the newspaper in 1934, covering 
shipping news. 
</P>
<P>
	Parmenter also wrote 12 books, several dealing with Mexico,  
where he frequently traveled. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Benno C. Schmidt    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Benno C. Schmidt, a pioneer in venture  
capitalism and informal health-policy advisor to several 
presidents, died Thursday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt, who spent 52 years working with financier John Hay  
Whitney, was appointed by President Nixon to serve as chairman of 
the President's Cancer Panel in the 1970s. He also was a chairman 
of the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	As one of the pioneers in venture capitalism, Schmidt's record  
at J. H. Whitney and Company included investments in the Spencer 
Chemical Company and in Minute Maid orange juice, despite an 
initial observation that the juice concentrate tasted ``tinny.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Ivo Hall Sparkman    	
</P>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Ivo Hall Sparkman, the widow of senator  
and Democratic vice-presidential nominee John Sparkman, died 
Wednesday. She was 100. 
</P>
<P>
	In her later years, Mrs. Sparkman took up painting and wrote a  
book, ``Over the Senator's Shoulder,'' about a trip the couple took 
to the Far East in the 1960s. In 1952, when Sparkman was the 
Democratic nominee for vice-president, she traveled with him to 38 
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
