<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Retirees Win Curbside Delivery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The U.S. Postal Service has agreed to  
start curbside delivery to 225 homes in a Florida retirement 
community, ending a two-year battle that stretched from Delray 
Beach to the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents in the first series of homes built in the Floral Lakes  
community have had to hike up to a half-mile to retrieve their mail 
from a central kiosk, while their neighbors in newer homes have had 
their mail delivered to their driveways. 
</P>
<P>
	But this week, Postmaster General William Henderson said the  
mail service would offer curbside delivery, said Josh Rogin, a 
spokesman for Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``They ultimately treated the residents very fairly,'' Rogin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the developer, Ben Martz, first started building homes  
three years ago in the community 50 miles north of Miami, he signed 
an agreement with the Postal Service for central delivery, a common 
method used to save government money and provide more secure mail 
delivery. 
</P>
<P>
	However, as the residents -- many of them veterans and retirees  
on Social Security -- began moving in, complaints mounted about the 
long, hot trek. One man, 64-year-old Donald Gross, claimed he 
needed four doses of heart medicine just to make the daily trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Martz first wrote to the postmaster requesting curbside delivery  
in June 1998. After months of discussion, the Postal Service said 
he could have curbside delivery to the more than 300 new homes in 
the development. But as for the original homes, the agency refused. 
Until the fight went to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	At the behest of Palm Beach County Commissioner Burt Aaronson,  
Wexler met with postal officials and urged them to reconsider. 
</P>
<P>
	Martz, chairman of Regency Homes, said Thursday it would cost  
him about $15,000 to install new mailboxes and reimburse the postal 
service for the kiosk. 
</P>
<P>
	He thanked those who challenged the Postal Service, an agency  
Martz says he now knows ``answers to no one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They're totally unyielding,'' Martz said. ``They're going to  
try to deliver the mail rain or shine, but the cheapest way they 
can.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
