<DOCNO> APW19991022.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 09:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida St. Rules on Warrick Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Peter Warrick can play for Florida  
State only after serving any jail time that is part of his plea 
agreement, the university president said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The star receiver and his lawyer met with Florida State  
president Sandy D'Alemberte on Thursday night. Warrick, a leading 
Heisman Trophy contender, is not expected to play Saturday against 
Clemson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the jail or prison time behind someone before they  
play,'' D'Alemberte said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating for everybody,'' said Warrick lawyer John  
Kenny, who must work out another deal with the state attorney's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick, a former teammate and a store clerk were charged with  
felony grand theft when the two players purchased more than $400 
worth of designer clothes Sept. 29 at a mall for $21.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick's lawyer this week reached an agreement to reduce the  
charge to a misdemeanor with the state attorney, but would have 
required the player to spend 30 days in jail at the end of the 
semester. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a fan, do I want him back? Absolutely yes,'' D'Alemberte  
said. ``But as a university president, I want him back after he's 
finished any problems with the criminal justice system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick has missed two games for the top-ranked Seminoles. On  
Saturday, Florida State coach Bobby Bowden goes for his 300th 
career victory. He will be facing son Tommy Bowden, the Clemson 
coach, in the first father-son matchup in Division I-A history. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick practiced Tuesday and Wednesday all week and can  
continue to do so. But when he rejoins the team for games is 
unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I enter a plea that is acceptable to the court and is  
acceptable to the state attorney's office, but won't help him get 
back on the field, it's not going to make Peter Warrick very 
happy,'' Kenny said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Dillard's clerk, Rachel Myrtil, pleaded no contest  
Thursday to grand theft and was sentenced to two years' probation, 
10 days on a county work program, ordered to pay $308 in court 
costs and stay out of Dillard's department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Laveranues Coles, who paid for the clothes, was kicked off the  
Florida State team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
