<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 03:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Developing Mad Cow Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists say they are close to developing a  
blood test for diagnosing mad cow disease and similar brain 
illnesses in animals and humans. 
</P>
<P>
	The test, developed by private and government researchers,  
detects the presence of abnormal proteins called prions that cause 
a group of diseases known as transmissible spongiform 
encephalopathies, or TSE. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, from what we've seen it looks very promising,'' said  
Mary Jo Schmerr, a scientist at the Agriculture Department's 
National Animal Disease Center in Ames, Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing for TSE diseases is now done by taking a sample of brain  
or glandular tissue, usually after death. 
</P>
<P>
	The blood test has been successfully used on TSE illnesses in  
sheep, elk, mule deer and hamsters. Additional research, which will 
probably take at least a year, must be done to ensure the test is 
reliable enough to be used for diagnostic purposes in humans and 
other animals, said Schmerr. 
</P>
<P>
	The test likely would be used first in Britain. The best known  
TSE is mad cow disease, which has been linked with a variant of the 
fatal brain condition known as Cruetzfeldt-Jakob. At least 43 
people have died of that strain of Creutzfeldt-Jakob in Britain 
since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans who traveled frequently to Britain during the mad cow  
crisis have been banned from donating blood in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no known mad cow disease in U.S. cattle, but sheep are  
susceptible to a related condition called scrapie and other forms 
of TSE infect elk, mule deer and mink. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA filed this week for a patent on the blood test.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
