<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP, Clinton Reach Lending Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Negotiating well past midnight, key Republican  
lawmakers reached agreement early Friday with administration 
officials on community lending rules for banks, participants in the 
five-hour, close-door talks said. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise was to be presented to a group of House and  
Senate negotiators considering legislation that would reshape the 
financial services industries. That group had halted its work while 
the closed-door talks continued to try to craft a bill that would 
avert a veto by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Final approval of the legislative package could come in the next  
few days. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial overhaul legislation would lift Depression-era  
legal barriers and allow banks, brokerage firms and insurance 
companies to merge and sell each other's products. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with Treasury Department officials, Republican and  
Democratic lawmakers emerged to say they had an agreement that the 
White House could accept. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am for the first time optimistic that we will pass, after a  
long time, financial services legislation,'' said Sen. Charles 
Schumer, D-N.Y. ``In 19 years, we are the closest we have ever been 
to actually achieving a bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all the negotiators were pleased with the compromise on  
community lending. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., denounced what she 
called ``the backroom negotiations'' and said she could not endorse 
the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, head of the Senate Banking Committee,  
earlier had vowed to continue pushing the financial overhaul 
legislation despite disagreements with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The new proposal includes Gramm's requirement that community  
groups receiving money from banks under federal law be compelled to 
disclose how they spent the money. In a compromise, that disclosure 
would be required only for loans of more than $50,000 and most 
grants of more than $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm's earlier proposal on community lending rules for banks  
had been rejected along a mostly party-line vote Thursday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports the legislative package in  
principle but has threatened a veto over provisions it says would 
weaken the 1977 Community Reinvestment Act, which requires banks to 
make loans in low-income and minority areas in which they operate. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm, who drafted the provisions, is an outspoken conservative  
and longtime critic of the 1977 law and has blocked efforts to 
expand its reach in the new legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm said Thursday he had shown willingness to compromise on  
the issue but would not abandon his core requirement that community 
groups receiving money from banks under the law be compelled to 
disclose how they spent the money. 
</P>
<P>
	For the administration and key Democratic constituencies, the  
community lending law is a cherished icon that they credit with 
having boosted the renewal of inner-city areas in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are communities that are moving forward now because (the  
Community Reinvestment Act) ... was the economic engine,'' Rep. 
Bobby Rush, D-Ill., said during debate on Gramm's proposal in the 
drafting session. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street and the banking and insurance industries have spent  
millions of dollars in recent years pushing for the financial 
overhaul legislation, insisting it would help consumers by 
providing one-stop financial shopping and saving them money. 
</P>
<P>
	This year Congress has come closer than ever to enacting  
legislation, but industry lobbyists have watched the prospects slip 
away in recent days as the administration officials, Gramm and 
other key Republican lawmakers struggled to reach an accord. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, consumer advocates and lawmakers pushing for  
stronger consumer privacy protections have criticized the financial 
overhaul legislation as inadequate in that area and put additional 
pressure on Clinton to veto the bill in its current form. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the issues of poor people and privacy left over  
because all the big boys have already gotten what they want,'' said 
Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
