<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Backs GOP's Abortion Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT, N.H. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush lined up with  
Senate Republicans on Friday in supporting a ban on certain 
late-term abortions, but he said there were other important issues 
for the country to address. 
</P>
<P>
	Holding a town meeting in a fire house near Lake Sunapee, the  
Republican presidential candidate told a female questioner he was 
opposed to a specific abortion procedure the Senate seeks to ban, 
but people should be allowed to disagree on abortion rights and the 
government should instead work to streamline adoptions. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Senate voted in favor of a resolution upholding  
Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion. 
Senators then passed a bill to ban an abortion procedure that 
involves partial delivery of the fetus, although the 63-34 vote was 
four short of the margin needed to override a promised veto by 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain, a rival of Bush for the GOP  
nomination, voted for the ban but did not vote on the question of 
Roe vs. Wade. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said earlier in the campaign he would not nominate Supreme  
Court justices based on their abortion views. At the same time he 
has said he would support a constitutional amendment limiting 
abortion rights but would not push for it. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit to Newport and later to Keene was the fifth that Bush  
has made to New Hampshire this year. The state holds the nation's 
first presidential primary on Feb. 1, eight days after the Iowa 
caucuses. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit also came the same day five Republican hopefuls were  
gathering for a debate at the University of New Hampshire. Bush 
declined an invitation and was appearing instead at a party 
fund-raiser in Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	Some pundits have questioned Bush's commitment to New Hampshire,  
and polls indicate that while the governor retains about 42 percent 
of the support of likely voters in the Republican primary, McCain 
has moved into a solid second place with about 26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing the criticism, Bush said he was invited to the  
Vermont event in June, and ``I'm a man who keeps my word.'' He said 
he was skipping another debate next week because his wife was 
receiving an award from her college. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family is my priority, and if it costs me votes for  
honoring my wife, so be it,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire house audience urged Bush to appoint quality people to  
government and asked him about making Elizabeth Dole his running 
mate. Dole ended her campaign Wednesday, citing Bush's overwhelming 
advantage in money. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said Dole brought grace and dignity to the campaign, but it  
was premature to talk about a running mate. ``I will speculate out 
loud after I win the party's nomination,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving his standard stump speech, Bush emphasized that America's  
prosperity must be used to improve the lot of all its citizens. He 
said that dream that can be realized through tax cuts, education 
improvements and by working with religious organizations to 
increase charity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stand before you as a uniter, not a divider,'' he declared,  
drawing hearty applause from a crowd of more than 200. 
</P>
<P>
	The appearance reaffirmed the beliefs of one couple in the  
audience, Luther and Margaret Williams of Hudson, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	``We voted for his father and we're going to vote for him,''  
said Williams, a 70-year-old retired security officer, referring to 
former President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he has a fresh outlook on everything that's going  
on,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
