<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Ahead in Argentine Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A dour opposition candidate who  
wants to ``end the party'' after the flashy decade of President 
Carlos Menem held onto a commanding lead Friday in the last opinion 
polls before this weekend's presidential elections in Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	Buenos Aires Mayor Fernando de la Rua has successfully harnessed  
Argentines' discontent with recession, crime and scandals. His main 
concern may now be avoiding a run-off with his nearest rival, 
Eduardo Duhalde of Argentina's ruling Peronist Party. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel the victory in the streets!'' de la Rua declared as he  
saluted tens of thousands of people during a campaign-closing 
motorcade across Buenos Aires on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's Gallup Argentina poll gave De la Rua 44.6 percent of  
the vote to 28.2 percent for Duhalde, governor of Buenos Aires 
province. Those results are similar to previous polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Running a distant third with 10.6 percent was Domingo Cavallo,  
the former finance minister who mended the tattered economy of this 
nation of 36 million in the early 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationwide poll, published by the newspaper La Nacion, had a  
margin of error of 3.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	To triumph in one round, the winner needs 45 percent outright  
Sunday -- or must garner between 40 percent and 45 percent of the 
ballot with a 10-percent lead over the runner-up. A run-off would 
be held Nov. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing his campaign in the northeastern city of Rosario,  
Duhalde cast doubt on the polls and warned against voting for De la 
Rua's opposition Alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	``A vote for the Alliance changes nothing. We are the true  
change,'' Duhalde said. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Rua, a 62-year-old lawyer who slowly rose up the political  
ladder, was first elected to the Senate in 1973. In 1996 he became 
mayor of the capital, where he erased a $600-million budget 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	He offers himself as a staid but steady alternative to Menem,  
the ``Hollywood president'' who transformed Argentina with 
free-market reforms -- all while driving race cars, mingling with 
soccer stars and celebrities and jetting around the globe to hobnob 
with world leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Menem reordered an economy that was inflationary and in disarray  
when he took officein 1989. Now 69, he ends his second term having 
completed one of the most intensive privatization programs in the 
world. He also made Argentina the strongest U.S. ally in South 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	But voters have grown weary, angered by a punishing recession,  
the second in four years, which has pushed unemployment to 14.5 
percent. Crime is also up, corruption scandals are swirling about 
some of Menem's most trusted aides and many on the streets say two 
presidential terms for the Peronists are enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Menem, who leaves office Dec. 10, threw late and tepid support  
behind Duhalde and did not even attend his last rally. Both 
candidates have campaigned as proponents of change and against 
Menem's record. 
</P>
<P>
	Where De La Rua offers clean government and continued  
free-market reforms, Duhalde has proposed cutting taxes and 
imposing a one-year moratorium on firings to surmount the 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	An opposition president could find governing complicated. The  
Peronists hold many of the 23 provincial governorships, with six 
gubernatorial races Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of seats are also up for grabs Sunday in the bicameral  
Congress, which is divided between the Peronists, Argentina's 
largest political force, and other parties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
