<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Behind the Scenes in Budget Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's chief negotiator in this  
week's budget tussle on Capitol Hill got his first lessons in 
politics from a master, former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Lew says he has never forgotten the Massachusetts  
Democrat's advice that ``while it's nice to be important, it's more 
important to be nice,'' even to adversaries in the annual minuet 
over how the government's money gets spent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew, who quoted his old boss' aphorism at a ceremony marking his  
nomination as budget director last spring, is leading 
budget-bargaining talks that began Wednesday at the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	He is a veteran Democratic aide who worked on Capitol Hill and  
in party politics before going to the White House at the start of 
the Clinton administration. In addition to partisan conviction, Lew 
has also demonstrated flexibility, said one of his Republican 
counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Clinton wants several billion dollars more than  
Congress has so far provided for hiring teachers and police 
officers, foreign aid and other programs. The president also wants 
to kill provisions the administration considers anti-environmental 
that would help the oil, mining and other industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from a brief tenure as a private lawyer, the 44-year-old  
New York City native has worked in politics, government or 
government-related think tanks for his entire career. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew is married, with two children, and known throughout the  
administration as an observant Jew who prefers not to work on 
Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath. Even Clinton, who routinely calls 
staffers at odd hours, tries not to bother Lew on Saturdays. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew took over as head of the White House Office of Management  
and Budget last year, after serving as the green-eyeshade group's 
No. 2. As the deputy to then-budget chief Franklin Raines, Lew was 
a front-line negotiator in talks that produced the 1997 budget 
accord. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day he would come in and say exactly what he had to say,  
and I would say exactly what I had to say,'' said Wayne Struble, 
staff director of the House Budget Committee, describing the 1997 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got to where we could say each other's lines. But after we  
dispensed with that back and forth, then it was serious,'' Struble 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew was an adviser on the failed 1994 Clinton health care  
overhaul and was key in launching the AmeriCorps national service 
program, which annually has been a target if GOP lawmakers but each 
year has survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew worked 14 years for congressional Democrats, including a  
stint as a senior policy adviser to O'Neill. In that job, Lew was 
on the opposite side of divided government in Washington, working 
for a top Democrat in a Democrat-led Congress while Republican 
Ronald Reagan was in the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew represented O'Neill in negotiations that overhauled Social  
Security in 1983 when the program was facing bankruptcy. Much of 
the rancor in this year's budget discussions has focused on whether 
either side will dip into the Social Security surplus to pay for 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jack has been at the heart of budget policy-making and the  
budget wars, really, for the last 15 years, or more than that,'' 
said Jake Siewert, a White House spokesman who knows Lew well. ``No 
one has been more involved at the detail level, and now sort of 
from the broader level than Jack. ... He's seen it from the 
congressional side, and he's seen it from the White House side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lew is the fourth budget director to serve in the Clinton  
administration, after Leon Panetta, Alice Rivlin and Raines, who 
left to head the home mortgage company Fannie Mae. 
</P>
<P>
	A Harvard graduate who also holds a law degree from Georgetown  
University, Lew is known as a serious student on sometimes arcane 
budget matters, said Robert Greenstein, head of the left-leaning 
Center on Budget and Policy Priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not someone who's on talk shows every Sunday,'' said  
Greenstein, referring to weekly public affairs television programs 
that frequently feature administration officials. ``He's someone 
who is invaluable to the administration in putting the budget 
together behind the scenes.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
