<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Examining Philanthropy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The young and the rich of the high-tech realm  
may be better known for punching code late into the night and 
indulging in extreme sports on the weekend. But if participants at 
a White House conference on philanthropy have their way, Silicon 
Valley will become the home of the social entrepreneurs of the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton were hosts  
for the conference highlighting the tradition and possible future 
of philanthropy in America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The face of this tradition is changing,'' President Clinton  
said. ``Philanthropy is like our country now -- more diverse as new 
groups seize and share opportunity in the new economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Participants in the first such conference spoke of a need to  
appeal more directly to baby boomers and Generation X. 
</P>
<P>
	Money isn't the only thing Internet mavens can provide.  
</P>
<P>
	America Online Inc. founder Steve Case highlighted a new  
philanthropic Internet portal, developed by the AOL Foundation, 
American Red Cross, the National Urban League and other groups, to 
offer an easy way to donate to over 620,000 charities. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can take all these tens of millions of people who are  
starting to change their lives because of the Internet and help 
them to change society because of the Internet as well,'' Case 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the talk turned again and again to the deep pockets of the  
cyberlords. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silicon Valley and the whole venture capital, high-tech  
community needs to be at the forefront of what we're doing because 
of the same reason Willie Sutton robbed banks,'' Clinton quipped. 
``That's where the money is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Fong, a general partner in a venture capital fund in  
Ventura, Calif., helped establish a group, the Entrepreneurs' 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fong said he and his associates aim to engage young people in  
Silicon Valley in their own communities. ``Many of these people 
aren't married yet, and all they know about is work,'' Fong said. 
</P>
<P>
	One example of a new approach to philanthropy, Fong said, is for  
a startup company to donate private stock to a local philanthropic 
fund. When a company goes public, the stock can generate millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's program was broadcast via satellite and on public  
television, reaching a potential audience of 10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Other participants included Patty Stonesifer, president of the  
$18 billion Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, actor Paul Newman, 
and 'NSync singer Justin Timberlake, who was announcing creation of 
a foundation to support musical education in public schools. 
Sponsors include the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation, the National 
Endowment for the Humanities, the J. Paul Getty Trust and the Iscol 
Family Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference also took stock of traditional philanthropic  
endeavors in the United States and assessed the importance of 
understanding how different ethnic communities approach the notion 
of supporting each other collectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Emmett Carson of the Minneapolis Fund urged mainstream  
philanthropic organizations to give up any ``noblesse oblige'' view 
of giving as ``narrow and one-dimensional.'' There are advantages 
to some other cultures' approaches such as giving anonymously or in 
communal enterprises, he said. ``Philanthropy should be a lifetime 
endeavor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, noting that the baby boomers stand to inherit $12  
trillion as their parents' generation passes on, said just a slight 
increase in the 2 percent that Americans donate to charitable 
organizations each year could produce dramatic results for 
everything from homeless shelters to libraries. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no better gift our generation can give to the future  
than a strengthened philanthropic tradition,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``New communities of donors must be encouraged to participate,''  
she said. ``New avenues of giving must be opened and explored.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
