<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 GOP Presidential Hopefuls Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Gary Bauer attacked Steve Forbes, while Sen.  
John McCain blasted the power of special interests. Alan Keyes 
complained about the ``socialization'' of American government and 
Sen. Orrin Hatch said he was the most competent alternative to 
George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were the persistent themes Friday night as five of the  
seven GOP hopefuls met for their first debate of the 2000 
nomination race. Bush, the Texas governor, stayed away, which put 
the spotlight on those trying to catch him. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, a conservative activist, drew the sharpest line with  
repeated slaps at Steve Forbes, the millionaire publisher who is 
financing his own campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	He disputed Forbes' proposals on taxes, trade and health care.  
``Steve, that sounded real good, but we've got to go beyond 
generalities,'' Bauer said after Forbes complained that Americans 
are losing control over their medical decisions to government and 
to health maintenance organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington is gridlocked by special interests,'' said McCain,  
a champion of campaign finance reform whose legislation the Senate 
defeated this week. The Arizona senator said Democrats are beholden 
to trial lawyers, and Republicans to the health care industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans did differ on trade policy toward China, with  
Bauer and conservative Alan Keyes, a radio talk show host and 
former U.N. ambassador, saying the most-favored-nation treatment 
that Beijing now enjoys -- which is standard for U.S. trading 
partners -- should be revoked. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, Forbes and Hatch, of Utah, criticized administration  
policy toward China, but didn't advocate ending most favored nation 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	More typically, after McCain rebuked Clinton administration  
policy on national defense, Hatch said he agreed with everything 
his fellow senator had said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes was the most talkative and confrontational of the lot,  
denouncing socialism, urging outright abolition of the income tax 
and telling the others to ``stop talking out of both sides of our 
mouths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hourlong forum was sponsored by New Hampshire Public  
Television, The Union Leader of Manchester and New Hampshire Cable 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	C-Span broadcast the debate nationally.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush opted weeks ago to skip the forum and one next week, as his  
lead in campaign funds and in the public opinion polls left no 
incentive for face-to-face encounters with his challengers now. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who campaigned in New Hampshire on Friday, said he had  
committed to a fund-raiser for Vermont Republicans at the same time 
of the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	He also declined to participate in a debate next Wednesday  
because it conflicted with a ceremony honoring his wife, Laura, at 
her alma mater in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said the opening debate would whet the public's appetite.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to want more real debates, not just an hour  
session. They're going to want all the candidates involved and so I 
think it's going to put pressure on Gov. Bush to be more 
participatory in the future,'' the publisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said afterward that he and Forbes are fighting to be the  
conservative alternative to Bush. ``I believe that Steve Forbes has 
peaked just as the foliage in New Hampshire has,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's debate came a day after the latest New Hampshire poll  
found Bush with a commanding lead and McCain solidifying his 
position in second place. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone survey of 600 likely Republican voters, Bush had  
the support of 42 percent, about what he had in August. McCain had 
26 percent -- 10 points better than in August -- with most of his 
gains coming at the expense of other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate also came two days after Elizabeth Dole, the lone  
woman seeking the GOP nomination, quit the race citing difficulty 
raising money. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Bush, conservative commentator Pat Buchanan also skipped  
the debate. He is expected to announce Monday that he is leaving 
the Republican Party to seek the presidency as a Reform Party 
candidate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
