<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jealous Husband Gets Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- A jury found a man guilty of murder for  
shooting his wife to death when he found her with another man, but 
then recommended that he get probation. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jimmy Watkins found his wife, Nancy, with a lover at the  
couple's home last December, he wounded both of them and later 
returned to the house and shot his wife five more times while she 
was calling 911. 
</P>
<P>
	This jury found he acted with ``sudden passion'' and recommended  
Thursday that he get a 10-year probated sentence with no prison 
time at all. Given the jury's action, District Judge Robert Gill 
sentenced Watkins to 120 days in prison as a condition of the 
probation. The most he could have given Watkins was 180 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Watkins bowed his head and wept as the verdict was announced.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure it was a very difficult decision for that jury to  
wrestle with, but we're pleased with their decision,'' said 
attorney Kyle Whitaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors, meanwhile, said they would take Watkins to trial  
again for shooting the other man, Keith Fontenot. Watkins is 
charged with attempted capital murder. If convicted, he could be 
sentenced to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not how we wanted the case to turn out,'' said  
prosecutor James Cook. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors deliberated 21 hours over three days before determining  
that Watkins, 34, had acted out of passion when he found his wife 
with Fontenot at the Watkins' home near Eagle Mountain Lake last 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	According to his confession, Watkins shot his wife once and  
Fontenot twice. Then he chased Fontenot from the house and put a 
gun to the man's head. When the gun failed to fire, Watkins drove 
away, but returned to kill his wife after realizing his gun had 
just jammed and was not empty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw my mom fall down and I saw my dad shoot my mom,'' the  
couple's 11-year-old son testified last week as his father sobbed. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors said Thursday they recommended a probated sentence  
because they didn't think Watkins could be rehabilitated in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel for the family, but Jimmy needs help. The prison  
system just won't give him help,'' juror Alex Davis told the Fort 
Worth Star-Telegram. 
</P>
<P>
	Another juror, James Laurie, e-mailed the newspaper Thursday  
night, saying he hoped Watkins would take advantage of his second 
chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pray Jimmy will use the break that we gave him to turn his  
life back in the right direction,'' Laurie said. ``He has a long 
way to go. I pray for all the family members that were affected.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
