<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens' Billick Ponders QB Switch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWINGS MILLS, Md. (AP) -- It's getting tougher for Brian Billick  
to make a case for Stoney Case. 
</P>
<P>
	As Case struggled in his first three weeks as the Baltimore  
Ravens' starting quarterback, Billick said inexperience and poor 
judgment would soon give way to poise and touchdowns. Billick, who 
has coached several outstanding quarterbacks, insisted that Case 
had the tools for stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday, less than 24 hours after Case's poor performance in  
Baltimore's 35-8 loss to the Kansas City Chiefs, Billick offered no 
ringing vote of confidence. And he didn't discount the possibility 
that Tony Banks would be the starter when the Ravens (2-4) face 
Buffalo Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't tell you now what our quarterback situation is going  
to be,'' Billick said. ``I have to think about what is in the best 
interest of (Case) both now and in the future because I believe he 
does have some potential. As does Tony Banks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Case had one NFL start in four seasons before this year. Despite  
pulling out two preseason games with last-minute throws, he started 
the regular season third on the depth chart. But he replaced an 
ineffective Scott Mitchell in Baltimore's second game, threw for 
the tying touchdown in the waning minutes and took over the top 
spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Case has yet to complete 50 percent of his passes in a game and  
has six interceptions against only three touchdowns. His 
inexperience was on full display for a national TV audience 
Thursday night, when he went 15-for-37 for 103 yards and three 
interceptions, two of which were returned for touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just played terribly,'' Case said. ``I want the opportunity  
to come back, but that's the coach's decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Case was a star in high school and still owns virtually every  
passing record at New Mexico. He went through four years of virtual 
inactivity waiting for his chance to be No. 1. Now, things haven't 
gone as planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a confident young man,'' Billick said. ``I don't think  
he's been through this before. But I think Stoney can bounce back 
from this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Will he get the chance in the Ravens' next game? Hard to say.  
Although Banks was a starter for the St. Louis Rams and was 
8-for-14 in relief against the Chiefs, Billick isn't thrilled about 
the prospect of using a third starter before the season's halfway 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot arbitrarily flip through quarterbacks,'' he said.  
``It's just not good for the organization, it's not good for the 
players, that lack of continuity. By the same token, if you think a 
guy can make a difference, then you make the change. But I'm not 
going to be rash about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In defense of Case, he was operating behind an injury riddled  
offensive line that provided him with little protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's part of football.'' Case said. ``I'm not going to use  
that as an excuse.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
