<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Fines Panthers' Barrow $7,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Mike Barrow's reputation as one of the  
NFL's tireless volunteers in the community didn't stop the league 
from fining him for breaking its rules on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrow, a Carolina Panthers linebacker, was assessed a $7,500  
fine Thursday for his helmet-to-helmet hit on San Francisco 
quarterback Jeff Garcia in Sunday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrow, the team's spokesman for the United Way campaign and a  
player who devotes countless hours to helping disadvantaged 
children, declined to comment on the fine, saying it was a private 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	The fine was a result of league rules that specifically bar  
helmet-to-helmet hits on quarterbacks when they are in the pocket 
and unprotected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Panthers were penalized 15 yards for unnecessary roughness  
on the fourth-quarter play that led to Barrow's fine. Barrow came 
charging up the middle of the pocket and, leading with the crown of 
his helmet, lunged into Garcia's face mask, knocking him on his 
back just after he released the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia's pass to Jerry Rice fell incomplete, but the penalty  
moved the ball to the Carolina 35, and San Francisco scored seven 
plays later to cut its deficit to 31-29 with 1:32 left. The 
Panthers held on to win by the same score. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrow's teammates came to the defense Thursday of a player who  
frequently leads Bible study sessions and has been known to work 
until the wee hours of the morning at schools, churches and soup 
kitchens in both Charlotte and his hometown of Homestead, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those deals where you just have to be with him and  
be around him to see his heart,'' said defensive tackle Sean 
Gilbert, one of Barrow's close friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrow, in his third year with the Panthers after playing his  
first four pro seasons in Houston, frequently takes dozens of young 
students to NFL games as rewards for doing well in school. He also 
finances and coaches several basketball teams for at-risk 
teen-agers and is a member of Charlotte's Community Outreach 
Christian Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's done so much and his heart is so open to service,''  
Gilbert said. ``But we play an aggressive game. I don't think 
anyone's intentions, for the most part, are to go out and try to 
end anyone's career. But it's a game of wills, and you're always 
fighting to dominate the other team's will. That's what makes it so 
competitive.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
