<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Gang Clearing Out ATMs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A sophisticated Russian criminal ring has been  
clearing out bank accounts in several countries -- including the 
United States -- by tampering with ATM machines in Moscow in a scam 
that has mainly targeted foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	The full extent of the fraud is not yet known, but authorities  
believe hundreds of thousands of dollars have been stolen by a 
well-organized criminal group that may have insider connections at 
Russian banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The thieves manipulated ATMs in Moscow and other cities to get  
the PIN codes, and then made false cards which were used to 
withdraw money at automatic teller machines in Western Europe, 
Israel, Russia and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	One victim, American George Sullivan, a production manager at  
the Troika Dialog investment bank in Moscow, said he lost $2,300 
through his MBNA Bank Visa card. 
</P>
<P>
	``Withdrawals took place in Tel Aviv in the beginning of May,''  
said Sullivan, noting that the criminals hit his limit on the card 
before it was frozen. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I told MBNA that there was apparently a rash of these  
cases going on in Russia, they said this was the first they'd heard 
of it,'' Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some foreigners who had money stolen from their bank accounts  
were having problems getting reimbursements from their banks, The 
Moscow Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Many ATM machines were out of service in central Moscow for much  
of Thursday, but bank officials declined to say if the problem was 
linked to the thefts. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's loosely regulated banking system has been subject to  
all sorts of fraud and there is an almost universal distrust of 
banks. Many depositors lost all or part of their money when banks 
collapsed during a financial crisis last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking system remains so primitive that checking accounts  
simply do not exist. Banks in remote parts of the country still use 
abacuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Russians, even middle-class professionals, don't have bank  
accounts because they don't feel their money would be safe. 
</P>
<P>
	However, cash machines are widely available in Moscow and a few  
other big cities, and many people rely on ATMs as their sole means 
of getting cash. The ATMs are particularly popular among foreign 
residents, who also tend not to have bank accounts in Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The thieves might have acquired the personal identification  
numbers with the help of accomplices in the Russian banks, said a 
Moscow police official in charge of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know yet how they were able to learn PIN codes,''  
said the official, who asked to be identified only by his first 
name, Oleg. ``They could have done that both by mechanical action 
and electronic means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said no suspects have been arrested in Russia, but four  
people were arrested in Munich, Germany, earlier this year, and the 
ring is believed to be much larger. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer didn't give the exact number of the fraud victims,  
but said it appeared to be in the hundreds. The amount of money 
stolen is still being determined, but an early estimate puts it in 
the hundreds of thousands dollars, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The theft hit clients of Europay and Visa, the world's leading  
card payment companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Oleg said officials were alerted to the fraud by expatriates who  
withdrew cash from ATMs located in Russia's provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got the first signals from five regions in late 1998,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The thieves quickly moved to Moscow, targeting ATMs in the  
Russian capital in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Warner, head of the fraud and security department at  
Europay in Brussels, Belgium, confirmed the Munich arrests and said 
the company was working with Moscow police and other payment 
systems on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner said the thieves apparently learned the PIN numbers by  
tampering with the machines, rather than by breaking the encryption 
system used to protect clients on automated banking networks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was an encryption problem, it would be a much larger  
problem than the one we currently have,'' Warner said in a 
telephone interview. ``We know that it was in Russia, and know 
which ATMs were involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Europay has sent out a warning to cardholders around the world,  
Warner added. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not talking about thousands of cards, and probably, not  
even hundreds of cards,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it will take time to assess the full damage, he added.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're only at the point of identifying where the problem is,''  
he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
