<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Play Final NBA Game At Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- The marquee announcing coming  
attractions at the Great Western Forum had only one listing Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nov. 6 -- Kings of Comedy.''  
</P>
<P>
	Wrong Kings, but hockey's Los Angeles Kings, along with Los  
Angeles' two NBA teams, are going downtown, moving into the $400 
million Staples Center. 
</P>
<P>
	After 32 years, the Forum's heyday came to an understated end  
Friday night with an NBA exhibition doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	A crowd of 12,510 watched the Lakers bring down the curtain on  
Showtime with a 112-100 loss to the Phoenix Suns in the title game 
of the Great Western Shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours before, the Miami Heat and Golden State Warriors took the  
court for the third-place game in front of about 200 fans at the 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat coach Pat Riley contributed to all six of the NBA  
championship banners hanging in the Forum's rafters, as a player 
(1972), assistant (1980) and head coach (1982, 1985, 1987, 1988). 
</P>
<P>
	``All the good things in my life happened here,'' Riley said of  
coaching the Forum's penultimate game. ``I can only hope to 
duplicate, or even come close to that, somewhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special place,'' Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal  
said. ``We're going to miss it. A lot of legends dominated this 
floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The retired uniforms of seven of them are displayed across from  
the championship banners. Both sets of momentos will stay where 
they are, with replicas to be installed in the Staples Center. 
</P>
<P>
	A typical Lakers crowd displayed little sentimentality about  
bidding the Forum farewell. Some fans held up a banner between the 
third and fourth quarters which read, ``6 Titles, 11 Conference 
Championships, 3,000-plus games with Chick,'' a reference to 
longtime Lakers announcer Chick Hearn. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's strange for the Forum to be closed with exhibitions,  
after as many championships as have been played here,'' said Phil 
Jackson, who won't get to coach the Lakers in the place where his 
Chicago Bulls won the first of their six NBA titles, in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forum will continue as a venue for occasional concerts and  
other special events. 
</P>
<P>
	Its end as a prime-time venue was low-key. The first 10,000 fans  
at Friday night's game received commemorative videotapes and CDs, 
and a montage of highlights flashed on the video board after the 
final -- really final -- whistle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
