<DOCNO> APW19991022.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska-Texas a Hot New Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- In many ways, Nebraska-Texas is the hot new  
rivalry in college football even if only for a little while. 
</P>
<P>
	It has everything: revenge, respect (and disrespect), two ranked  
teams and two victories by underdog Texas in the past three years 
that ended Nebraska streaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think either team thinks this is (just) another  
game,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said as the 18th-ranked Longhorns 
(5-2, 2-1 Big 12) prepared to meet No. 3 Nebraska (6-0, 3-0) 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's huge,'' Longhorns cornerback Ahmad Brooks said. ``It's a  
game for Texas to gain national attention and find itself. This 
game is about more than the Big 12. It's about traditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only problem is the series goes on hold after Saturday.  
Because of the split between the Big 12 North and South divisions, 
the teams aren't scheduled to meet again during the regular season 
until 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	They could play each other in the conference title game during  
the off years and possibly even meet again at the end of this 
season. Both teams are tied for first in their respective 
conference divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems logical that these tradition-rich programs would have  
played each more than just six times. The rivalry didn't spark 
until the Big 8 and Southwest conferences merged. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Texas surprisingly beat Nebraska twice.  
</P>
<P>
	Texas' victory in the 1996 conference title game ended the  
Huskers' run for a third consecutive national title. The Longhorns 
won again at Lincoln last year, breaking Nebraska's 47-game home 
winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas and Florida State (1992-93) are the only teams to beat  
Nebraska twice during the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska coach Frank Solich said his team doesn't think about  
those games anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened last season is well behind us,'' Solich said.  
``We try not to hang on to things. That's not a factor as far as 
our players are concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps Solich misjudged his players.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hate Texas. We want to beat them in the worst way,''  
Nebraska center Dominic Raiola said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are talking some big trash,'' Texas wide receiver Kwame  
Cavil said. ``The pressure is on them. They have expectations of a 
national title and they still haven't beaten us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest pressure will likely come at Texas quarterback Major  
Applewhite, who passed for 269 yards and two touchdowns against 
Nebraska last year. He is averaging 298.7 yards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska has the stingiest defense in the Big 12, giving up  
230.8 total yards and allowing only 9.7 points per game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Longhorns expect Nebraska to mimic Kansas State's blitzing  
game plan that produced a 35-17 Wildcats victory three weeks ago. 
K-State converted six Applewhite turnovers into 26 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Applewhite seems ready to take a pounding Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wish that last year's victory gave me more confidence about  
this week's game,'' he said. ``But we are a different Texas team 
this year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
