<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii Ironman Attracts Large Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KAILUA-KONA, Hawaii (AP) -- Defending men's champion Peter Reid  
of Canada is among seven former winners entered in the largest 
field ever in Saturday's Hawaiian Ironman Triathlon World 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The sport's prestige event consists of a 2.4-mile ocean swim, a  
112-mile bike through the hot and often windy lava fields, and a 
marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,500 professionals and amateurs are registered,  
representing every state and 51 countries. The oldest entrant is 
76. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the entrants, who have a 17-hour time limit,  
will be first-time competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Several top entrants, including 1997 winner Thomas Hellriegel of  
Germany, 1996 winner Luc Van Lierde of Belgium and 1994 winner Greg 
Welch of Australia, also are training for the Olympic triathlon 
distance, a 1.5-kilometer swim, a 40K bike and 10K run. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to work on not sprinting because you can't `hammer'  
the whole day in the Ironman,'' said Hellriegel, the Hawaiian 
course record-holder. ``If you try to do that, the hammer will hit 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The triathlon will make its Olympic debut next year.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult to train for both distances,'' said Lother  
Leder of Germany, who finished third the past two years. ``I have 
very good memories in Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	``But in shorter distances, it only lasts 1 hour, 45 minutes.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Ironman is Reid's specialty distance.  
</P>
<P>
	Last May, he won his third straight Australian Ironman title by  
11 minutes. Two months later, he won the inaugural Austrian Ironman 
and broke the 8-hour barrier (7:51:56) by finishing with a 2:35:21 
marathon, the fastest ever to conclude an Ironman event. 
</P>
<P>
	In Australia, Reid's wife, Lori Bowden, also of Canada, won the  
women's title, the first time a husband-wife team won the same 
Ironman event in the same year. Bowden won by 14 minutes and set a 
marathon course record of 3:08:52. 
</P>
<P>
	Competing in strong winds last year, Reid won in 8:24:20.  
</P>
<P>
	Reigning women's champion Natascha Badmann of Switzerland will  
not defend her title because she's focusing on shorter-distance 
triathlons to train for the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	That means Bowden will be favored to improve upon her  
second-place finishes the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Heather Fuhr of Canada, who has eight career Ironman titles, won  
this year's Ironman Brazil and Ironman Lake Placid, N.Y., and is 
expected to challenge Bowden. 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Smyers, of Lincoln, Mass., winner of the 1995 Hawaii race,  
is returning after a three-year absence from childbirth and 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The professional men and women compete for $250,000 in prize  
money, including $35,000 overall and split bonuses to winners. 
</P>
<P>
	The amateur field includes New Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson;  
``General Hospital'' star Real Andrews; Lyn Brooks, of Baltimore, 
who will attempt to become the race's first 20-time finisher and 
then retire; and triathlon pioneer Scott Tinley of Del Mar, Calif., 
who won this event in 1982 and 1985 and also will retire after 
Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
