<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Push for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Selling President Clinton's ideas on education  
became a family enterprise Friday. While he was making his case in 
a speech at a Washington hotel, his wife was on Capitol Hill, 
making the same points in the company of Senate Democrats she hopes 
to join. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has something to celebrate: House passage Thursday by a  
358-67 vote of a $9.9 billion education bill and rejection of a 
Republican proposal to give federal aid directly to parents for 
private school vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to agree generally on what I think is an adequate  
increase in funding,'' Clinton told the National Board for 
Professional Teaching Standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill aims at boosting the achievement of 10.5 million poor  
and otherwise disadvantaged schoolchildren -- all good news, Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there is no commitment yet for more and better teachers,  
for smaller classes, for increased accountability, for higher 
standards, for giving the tools out there'' that teachers need, 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, at a news conference, Hillary Rodham Clinton and  
Senate Democrats stressed they would oppose, and Clinton would 
veto, any education spending bill that does not provide enough 
money to meet the administration's goal of hiring 100,000 new 
teachers to reduce class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House complains that the Republican version of the  
education spending bill also threatens the jobs of 30,000 federally 
funded teachers hired last year and provides no money to add 8,000 
teachers to their ranks, as Clinton proposed this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republican leadership and the Republicans in Congress have  
consistently voted against what Americans want in education,'' Mrs. 
Clinton said. ``They have denied thousands of children the chance 
to learn in smaller classes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House Committee on  
Education and the Workforce, defended GOP priorities in the ongoing 
talks on the fiscal 2000 education spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton ``needs to go the next step and understand that the  
direction in which he wants to go on the hiring of additional 
teachers is not in the best interest of students across the 
country,'' Goodling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has pushed the idea of smaller class sizes and more  
teachers since he took office. A deadline is implicit in his pitch 
this year; the White House and Congress are now hashing out the 
budget to fund the government during Clinton's last year in office. 
</P>
<P>
	If Clinton is pushing to complete his education to-do list, his  
wife is making the issue central to her all-but-declared Senate 
race. If she wins the 2000 race in New York, Mrs. Clinton will take 
office just as her husband leaves the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president and the administration have been listening to  
the American people, and they presented Congress with a plan to do 
just what the American people want in prioritizing the needs of 
education,'' Mrs. Clinton said at the news conference, called by 
Democrats already serving in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, referred to her as ``Senator Clinton.''  
</P>
<P>
	``She will be the education senator,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy,  
D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope you do decide to run for the Senate,'' said Sen. Patty  
Murray, D-Wash. ``We have been able to put education on the 
national agenda; with you here, it will become the national 
agenda.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
