<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Suicide Rate Worries Insurers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Faced with rising claims because of Japan's surging  
suicide rate, the country's life insurers are making it tougher for 
customers to collect benefits when a policyholder kills himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Major Japanese insurers generally refuse to pay suicide benefits  
on policies under a year old. But some companies are doubling that 
period as a wave of suicides hits Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Life insurers have been accused ... of making it easy for  
people to commit suicide for money,'' said Ken Natori, spokesman 
for Dai-Ichi Mutual Life Insurance Co. ``The change in our policy 
is in answer to that accusation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were 31,755 suicides in Japan in 1998, a 35 percent jump  
from the previous year's level. Experts blamed the trend on the 
country's economic downturn and other social problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The suicide rate of men in their 50s posted the biggest  
increase, and insurance officials say that some men laid off from 
their jobs kill themselves so that their families can live in 
comfort off the insurance money. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has no law that mandates how insurance companies deal with  
suicides of policy holders, said Masaru Tanabe, spokesman for the 
Life Insurance Association of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In France and Italy, the law dictates that insurance payment for  
suicides can be paid out only after two years of belonging to a 
life insurance policy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, the law differs from state to state.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
