<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccine Worries Growing in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lot of today's new parents weren't around  
when polio was so dreaded that children were kept from the movies 
or the beach during the summer because of fears the paralyzing 
virus would sweep through a crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	And if you can remember when measles killed more than 2,000  
American children in a single year -- 1941 -- you're probably too old 
to have kids who now need their measles shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaccinations have protected millions of Americans from diseases  
like polio and measles. But a backlash is starting -- from parents 
who don't remember the heartbreak of some of the world's most 
contagious killers, and question why their babies need the shots 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, doctors are growing more concerned that some parents  
fear possible side effects of vaccines more than the disease. While 
such fears on rare occasions may be real, more often they are 
unproved and alarmist, the doctors say. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a disease wanes, people's attention shifts,'' says Dr.  
Bruce Gellin of Vanderbilt University, who directs a new National 
Immunization Information Network that is researching how to help 
doctors give parents the most scientifically sound vaccine 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaccination is considered the century's biggest public health  
success. Vaccines eradicated smallpox. Polio, one of the most 
feared diseases until an effective vaccine was found in 1955, could 
disappear in a few years. Last year, the nation recorded just 100 
measles cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, let up on vaccination before a disease is eradicated and it  
rapidly bounces back. The United States lapsed with measles 
inoculations in 1989, and 55,000 people got sick and 120 died. When 
diphtheria immunization recently dipped in Russia, 2,000 cases 
occurred -- just waiting for an unvaccinated tourist to carry the 
disease home. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as doctors worry about complacency, reports abound about  
possible vaccine side effects -- from scary media stories to 
Internet sites. Vaccines are not perfect. They sometimes cause 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	One lawmaker complained this summer that 11,000 children were  
reported to have had some reaction after inoculations last year, 
the majority minor but some serious. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Surgeon General David Satcher told Congress, study after  
study proves serious side effects are rare -- tens of millions of 
vaccine doses are given safely every year. 
</P>
<P>
	Public health experts do work to minimize side effects. That's  
why a vaccine against rotavirus, the leading cause of severe 
childhood diarrhea, was pulled off the market last week. Doctors 
monitored the possibility that the year-old vaccine might increase 
infants' risk of a rare but dangerous bowel obstruction, and 
stopped vaccinations when clues emerged that it did. 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, tolerance for vaccine side effects wanes as the  
disease does. Take the oral polio vaccine, a potent live-virus 
vaccine but one that carried a small risk of actually causing 
polio. By the mid-1990s, about 10 of the 4 million American 
children who swallowed the vaccine each year caught polio from it. 
Parents vehemently objected, and now a polio shot that eliminates 
that threat is used instead. 
</P>
<P>
	But what really worries doctors is the spread of alarming and  
unproved allegations, such as claims linking the decades-old 
measles vaccine to autism. Parents in parts of Britain have held 
``measles parties,'' deliberately exposing children to measles so 
they would get the disease very young and consequently avoid 
vaccination. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientific studies find no evidence that the measles vaccine  
causes autism -- but measles itself can be worse than just a rashy 
rite of passage. Among the complications: One in every 1,000 
measles patients gets encephalitis, and one in four of those who do 
will die or suffer neurological damage, Gellin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What people don't understand is they're putting their children  
at a true risk of complications from measles against ... at best a 
hypothetical and totally unproven argument about autism,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gellin's new network is researching how to help doctors address  
such skewed perceptions of risk. In the meantime, its Internet site 
points parents to science-based Web pages they can consult today. 
The information at http://www.idsociety.org/vaccine/resources.htm 
explains research that separates real side effects from debunked 
claims, lists ongoing studies to settle allegations, and explains 
each vaccine's value. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pointing them to the same sources that we as physicians  
look at,'' Gellin said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 11:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Wants U.S. Brokerage Punished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese securities regulators recommended  
punishment for Cresvale International Ltd., the subsidiary of a 
Princeton, N.J. company embroiled in charges of a $1 billion 
securities fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulators said Friday that Cresvale executives gave  
kickbacks to Japanese companies and provided false information 
about investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The usual punishment in such cases is to shut down the offending  
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Cresvale marketed interest-bearing promissory notes to about 100  
Japanese companies, which the company now cannot repay. The 
promissory notes were issued by Princeton Economics International 
Ltd., and the money was invested by its chairman, Martin A. 
Armstrong Jr., a well-known market forecaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Cresvale's operations in Tokyo were suspended for six months in  
September, and Armstrong has been indicted in the United States. He 
pleaded innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest allegations and recommendation were presented Friday  
to Japan's Financial Supervisory Agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
