<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Win Puts Chiefs Near AFC West Top </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Their third road victory in two seasons  
has the Kansas City Chiefs poised for their biggest home game in at 
least that long. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego (4-1) will be in Arrowhead Stadium a week from Sunday  
to face the Chiefs (4-2) with first place in the AFC West possibly 
on the line. First, the Chargers have to play host to Green Bay 
this Sunday. And Seattle (3-2) could make it even more crowded at 
the top by beating Buffalo at home on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs will have the weekend off to savor a 35-8 victory  
over the quarterback-challenged Baltimore Ravens Thursday night, 
their first victory of the season away from Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won on the road,'' were the first words out of first-year  
coach Gunther Cunningham's mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs did more than simply pull off a rare road victory. In  
addition, their aggressive defense returned two interceptions off 
Stoney Case for touchdowns and came within four minutes of their 
first road shutout in 26 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Case, who was replaced in the fourth quarter, was 15-for-37 for  
103 with three interceptions while being constantly harried. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs' Elvis Grbac, frequently booed in Arrowhead Stadium  
during his checkered three years as starter, was almost 
mistake-free in contrast. He threw only 16 passes, but two went for 
touchdowns to Tony Gonzalez, who may be emerging as one of the 
league's top tight ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``The defense played extremely hard,'' Cunningham said. ``We  
took them out of the run game right now. I figured we would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was only 7-0 in the second quarter when 34-year-old  
cornerback James Hasty intercepted Case's pass and cruised 56 yards 
for a touchdown. Hasty also had another interception and totaled 11 
tackles in one of the best games in his 12-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have some serious tendencies on third down and second and  
short,'' said Hasty, who is known for studying every opponent. 
``They run the receiver 6 (yards) and have him break out. I watched 
that on film and anticipated the play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The interceptions gave Hasty an AFC-leading four for the season  
and 38 for his career, tying for eighth among active players with 
teammate Cris Dishman. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham was so pleased with the rousing road victory that he  
didn't even get mad at Donnie Edwards for lateralling the ball to 
Reggie Tongue after intercepting one of Case's poorly thrown 
passes. Of course, Tongue went for a touchdown that made it 28-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a big lateral guy,'' Cunningham said. ``But Donnie  
Edwards did the right thing. Reggie Tongue had a couple of tough 
games in the sense he has to make plays. In practice on Friday, he 
intercepted four passes. And I knew his time was going to come.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
