<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial of Ex-Teamster Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Teamsters' former political director has  
gone on trial, accused by federal prosecutors of funneling union 
money to the re-election campaign of former President Ron Carey 
three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	William Hamilton has been charged with conspiracy, embezzlement,  
mail fraud, wire fraud, lying to an election officer and perjury. 
His trial began Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Robert Gage, said the $885,000 in contributions to  
political organizations were legitimate as a part of a new effort 
by the once-powerful union to gain clout with an increasingly 
hostile White House and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Gage said his client was an innocent victim of false charges  
brought by prosecutors relying on lies by convicted felons trying 
to reduce potential prison sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Hamilton's not guilty of anything he's been charged  
with,'' Gage said Thursday. He said all contributions were ``to 
accomplish important political goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Rice said Hamilton conspired with  
others to make the contributions solely as rewards for donations to 
Carey's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``They betrayed the union and its members and broke the law,''  
Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carey narrowly defeated James P. Hoffa in the 1996 election,  
which was overturned after investigators found that Carey's 
campaign had improperly benefited from donations the union made to 
the organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa was elected president of the 1.4-million union in another  
election while Carey and Hamilton were barred for life from joining 
or working for the union by an Independent Review Board in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice said money was paid out to four third-party political  
organizations with the understanding that money would then be 
contributed to the effort to re-elect Carey. The union is not 
permitted to use its money to fund elections for union members. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor said the contributions to organizations,  
including one for senior citizens and another which encouraged 
people to vote, were staggering in their size and unprecedented, 
especially since the union was nearly broke. 
</P>
<P>
	``The money poured out of the Teamsters like water from an open  
faucet,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jere Nash, Carey's campaign manager, political consultant Martin  
Davis and telemarketer Michael Ansara all pleaded guilty to the 
scheme in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice said Nash and Ansara will testify at the trial, and  
evidence will include many documents such as contribution requests, 
checks from wealthy contributors and other parts of a long paper 
trail. 
</P>
<P>
	He said witnesses would include members of the Clinton-Gore  
re-election committee who were approached by representatives of the 
union seeking donors to Carey's campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
