<HEADLINE> JobBenet Case May Be Reexamined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The task force reexamining the JonBenet Ramsey  
case met again Friday and Gov. Bill Owens said he may decide next 
week whether to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate the 
murder of the 6-year-old beauty queen. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens and members of the task force he called met four times  
this week to consider the case after a grand jury failed to issue 
any indictments following a 13-month investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when a decision on a special prosecutor would be made,  
Owens said, ``Hopefully next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the grand jury's results were announced Oct. 13, police  
said that JonBenet's parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, remain under 
an ``umbrella of suspicion'' in the slaying of JonBenet at their 
Boulder home. Boulder County prosecutor Alex Hunter said they have 
not been eliminated from the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ramseys have insisted they are innocent.  
</P>
<P>
	Early on Dec. 26, 1996, Patsy Ramsey told police she found a  
ransom note demanding $118,000 for her daughter's safe return. 
Eight hours later, JonBenet's father said he found his daughter's 
body in the basement. 
  	   	
</P>
