<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Helps Raise Money in Va. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton offered his political  
coattails Friday to Virginia's Democrats, who are hoping to defend 
themselves against outright Republican control of state government 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton reminded about 700 people at the seventh annual Martin  
Luther King Jr.-Robert F. Kennedy dinner -- which raised $100,000 
for state Democratic candidates -- that both unemployment and crime 
have fallen to historic lows during his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The policies that the Democrats have followed have given us  
the longest peacetime (economic) expansion in history,'' Clinton 
said. ``All those little things they say about us are demolished by 
those statistics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also asked the party members to rally behind Sen.  
Charles Robb, D-Va., who Clinton said was trailing in early polls 
for his November 2000 re-election bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton blamed Robb's trouble, in part, on a vote to raise taxes  
in 1993 and approve of the administration's fiscal plan, and he 
noted, ``We Democrats have a difficult time in Virginia.'' Clinton, 
who easily won re-election in 1996, didn't carry the state. 
</P>
<P>
	This November's elections pose a tough test for Old Dominion's  
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Although they dominated state government for most of the  
century, Republicans now occupy the top jobs of governor, 
lieutenant governor and attorney general and lead the state Senate. 
The GOP needs to pick up only two seats to seize control of the 
state House. 
</P>
<P>
	Much is at stake: The dominant party after this election will  
decide how the state's legislative and congressional districts are 
drawn after the 2000 census. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire future of Virginia will be decided in these  
elections,'' Gov. Jim Gilmore said Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
