<DOCNO> APW19991022.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:42:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parachutist Dies in Protest Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- A 60-year-old veteran  
parachutist plunged to her death when her chute failed to open 
while jumping off the top of 3,200-foot El Capitan on Friday to 
protest park rules banning the extreme sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan Davis was one of five jumpers who planned to leap off the  
sheer granite cliff, a protest organized in response to the June 9 
death of a jumper who successfully parachuted off El Capitan only 
to drown in the river below while trying to flee park rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was the fourth jumper, the first three were beautiful. And  
then she jumped. Everybody thought it was OK, and then people said 
'Open up! Open up!' Then ... the whole place turned quiet,'' said 
Paul Sakuma, an Associated Press photographer. 
</P>
<P>
	The protest was meant to demonstrate that the jumps can be made  
safely. 
</P>
<P>
	The first jumper took about four minutes to float down into  
Yosemite Valley in a brilliant blue sky. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis fell for more than 20 seconds before she hit amid a piles  
of rock at the base of El Capitan. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangers quickly cordoned off the area after the 2 p.m. accident,  
and the fifth parachutist hiked down, said Scott Gediman, a 
spokesman for the park. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a veteran with more than 70 jumps in the past 16 years,  
was using a borrowed parachute and gear that had a cord on the leg, 
unlike her usual gear where the cord was on her back, her husband, 
Tom Sanders, told friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``If only she had used her own gear; if she had only had her own  
gear,'' Sanders said repeatedly, according to friends. She used 
borrowed gear because she didn't want hers to be confiscated by 
rangers waiting to arrest her on the valley floor, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, of Santa Barbara, Calif., was the first woman to jump  
from Angel Falls in Venezuela, the highest waterfall in the world, 
and worked closely with her husband, who has done skydiving 
sequences for James Bond movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who was among the spectators, slumped onto his camera  
after she fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The extreme sport of jumping from fixed objects like cliffs or  
buildings is so dangerous that the National Park Service has banned 
such stunts. Nationwide, an estimated 21 people have died during 
so-called BASE jumps -- the acronym for buildings, antennae, spans 
and earth -- in the last 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	BASE jumping was legal in the park for a trial period in 1980,  
but restrictions on when people could jump and the number of jumps 
per day were routinely violated, so the activity was banned. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the sixth death since 1980 due to BASE jumping in the  
park, and we've had numerous injuries. It's a poor track record,'' 
Gediman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, rangers have arrested anyone they catch jumping off  
El Capitan and other cliffs, seized their equipment and put them in 
the local jail. The fine runs $2,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides have tried to reach an accommodation after rangers  
who staked out a landing area tried to capture Frank Gambalie III 
in June. Gambalie, 28, tried to flee, and drowned in the 
runoff-swollen Merced River. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday, Gambalie's mother joined about 150 people, including the  
five jumpers' families and friends, in what was supposed to be a 
carefully staged demonstration. 
</P>
<P>
	The parachutists, accompanied by rangers at the top of the peak,  
agreed to land in a designated area, be arrested and forfeit their 
equipment, then pursue their opposition to the ban in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis also did not bring a backup parachute because she would  
have had to turn it over to park rangers afterward, said Chris 
Conkright, an employee of Aerial Focus, the Santa-Barbara-based 
aerial cinematography company she and her husband ran. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 14:40:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Examining Philanthropy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The young and the rich of the high-tech realm  
may be better known for punching code late into the night and 
indulging in extreme sports on the weekend. But if participants at 
a White House conference on philanthropy have their way, Silicon 
Valley will become the home of the social entrepreneurs of the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton were hosts  
for the conference highlighting the tradition and possible future 
of philanthropy in America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The face of this tradition is changing,'' President Clinton  
said. ``Philanthropy is like our country now -- more diverse as new 
groups seize and share opportunity in the new economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Participants in the first such conference spoke of a need to  
appeal more directly to baby boomers and Generation X. 
</P>
<P>
	Money isn't the only thing Internet mavens can provide.  
</P>
<P>
	America Online Inc. founder Steve Case highlighted a new  
philanthropic Internet portal, developed by the AOL Foundation, 
American Red Cross, the National Urban League and other groups, to 
offer an easy way to donate to over 620,000 charities. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can take all these tens of millions of people who are  
starting to change their lives because of the Internet and help 
them to change society because of the Internet as well,'' Case 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the talk turned again and again to the deep pockets of the  
cyberlords. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silicon Valley and the whole venture capital, high-tech  
community needs to be at the forefront of what we're doing because 
of the same reason Willie Sutton robbed banks,'' Clinton quipped. 
``That's where the money is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Fong, a general partner in a venture capital fund in  
Ventura, Calif., helped establish a group, the Entrepreneurs' 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fong said he and his associates aim to engage young people in  
Silicon Valley in their own communities. ``Many of these people 
aren't married yet, and all they know about is work,'' Fong said. 
</P>
<P>
	One example of a new approach to philanthropy, Fong said, is for  
a startup company to donate private stock to a local philanthropic 
fund. When a company goes public, the stock can generate millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's program was broadcast via satellite and on public  
television, reaching a potential audience of 10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Other participants included Patty Stonesifer, president of the  
$18 billion Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, actor Paul Newman, 
and 'NSync singer Justin Timberlake, who was announcing creation of 
a foundation to support musical education in public schools. 
Sponsors include the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation, the National 
Endowment for the Humanities, the J. Paul Getty Trust and the Iscol 
Family Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference also took stock of traditional philanthropic  
endeavors in the United States and assessed the importance of 
understanding how different ethnic communities approach the notion 
of supporting each other collectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Emmett Carson of the Minneapolis Fund urged mainstream  
philanthropic organizations to give up any ``noblesse oblige'' view 
of giving as ``narrow and one-dimensional.'' There are advantages 
to some other cultures' approaches such as giving anonymously or in 
communal enterprises, he said. ``Philanthropy should be a lifetime 
endeavor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, noting that the baby boomers stand to inherit $12  
trillion as their parents' generation passes on, said just a slight 
increase in the 2 percent that Americans donate to charitable 
organizations each year could produce dramatic results for 
everything from homeless shelters to libraries. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no better gift our generation can give to the future  
than a strengthened philanthropic tradition,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``New communities of donors must be encouraged to participate,''  
she said. ``New avenues of giving must be opened and explored.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
