<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Rocker Ready for Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- In the winter of 1997, John Rocker was an obscure  
minor-leaguer sent away to harness his considerable skills in 
remote Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	He was still in the infant stage of his career as a reliever,  
but he finally felt comfortable with his place in life. No longer 
did he have to wait four days between starts. No longer did he have 
to conserve his energy for the late innings. 
</P>
<P>
	One night, Rocker was throwing in the bullpen when the call went  
out for a new pitcher in the eighth inning. His eyes quickly 
shifted to the man waiting at the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Rodriguez.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was the first big-name hitter I had ever faced,'' Rocker  
recalled Friday, standing on the field after the Atlanta Braves 
worked out for Game 1 of the World Series against the New York 
Yankees. ``I had nothing to lose if he took me deep. I wanted to go 
out there with a no-holds-barred attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As if to drive that point home, he charged to the mound like a  
mad bull in search of a red cape. After striking out Rodriguez -- or 
so he says; the Texas catcher was unavailable to rebut the story -- 
the furious, 100-yard dash from the bullpen would be the trademark 
of a Rocker appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's a sign of immaturity,'' he said, certain to get no  
argument from New Yorkers. ``But I just have an intense will to 
win. I'm a perfectionist at whatever I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At age 25, nearing the end of his first season as the Braves'  
closer, Rocker has left an indelible impression on the postseason 
with a pattern of conduct totally out of character for his team. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Braves have been criticized for being too businesslike  
about their eight straight playoff appearances, Rocker picked a 
fight with Mets fans prior to the NL Championship Series by calling 
them ``stupid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he came on the field for Game 3 at Shea Stadium, he hardly  
ran away from the spotlight. Instead, Rocker walked slowly toward 
the outfield, soaking in the boos with an sarcastic smile and tip 
of the cap. He even stopped to sign autographs for a couple of kids 
wearing Mets jerseys. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Braves left New York, Rocker described Mets fans as  
``subhuman.'' After totaling his sports car in a wreck the day 
before Game 6 -- escaping without a scratch -- he pitched two 
scoreless innings in the 10-9 victory that sent the Braves to the 
World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker says now that his seemingly rash actions were a  
well-conceived plan to motivate himself and rattle the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something where I just shot my mouth off,'' Rocker  
said. ``It was sort of a motivational tool. It worked out just like 
I thought it would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of his teammates simply shake their heads when discussing  
the 6-foot-4, 210-pound left-hander, who became the closer after 
Kerry Ligtenberg was injured, and wound up with 38 saves -- one away 
from the team record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been here a very long time and, yeah, there's things I've  
wanted to say, but I knew I didn't have the right to say them,'' 
John Smoltz said, squirming a bit against his locker. ``He seems to 
be thriving on that. The guys are just leaving him alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker is clearly in his element in the World Series, where  
every comment is scrutinized, every action is analyzed. Cheer him, 
boo him, it doesn't matter. Just make sure you notice him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd much rather pitch in front of a large crowd,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I pitch with intensity, emotion and aggressiveness,'' said  
Rocker, usually seen around the clubhouse in a T-short bearing the 
name of pro wrestler Bill Goldberg. ``At times this year, I didn't 
have enough emotion or adrenaline. Those were the games where I 
didn't pitch as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A football player in high school, he readily admits he would  
rather be playing with the NFL Falcons than the Braves. But he 
wasn't very fast and his strong left arm made him better suited for 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker's competitiveness is unquestioned. Some of his actions  
could also be interpreted as selfish, however. 
</P>
<P>
	He shot off at his teammates last month when Eddie Perez's  
throwing error after a strikeout cost the Braves a victory -- and 
Rocker a save. In the division series against Houston, Rocker 
escaped a bases-loaded, no-outs situation in the 10th inning of 
Game 3 -- then said afterward that he felt no pressure when he came 
in because the runners wouldn't go on his pitching line. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rocker has been a dominating presence in the postseason,  
carrying the Braves to the World Series for the first time since 
1996. He has one win and three saves, allowing only three hits and 
no earned runs in 10 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	From the Braves point of view, he can keep on talking.  
</P>
<P>
	``Have you seen how big he is?'' Chipper Jones quipped. ``Who's  
going to say anything to him? Not me. He'd pound me in the ground. 
There would probably be a problem if he said things and then didn't 
perform on the field. But he's backing it up. If it's not broke, 
don't fix it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
