<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Courts Vermont Others Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARREN, Vt. (AP) -- As most of his competitors for the Republican  
presidential nomination showed themselves off during a nationally 
televised debate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush was dozens of miles 
away raising campaign cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the GOP front-runner, said he had agreed to attend the  
Vermont fund-raisers before Friday night's debate in New Hampshire 
was scheduled. ``I'm a man who keeps my word,'' he told reporters 
during an earlier appearance in Durham, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was skipping another debate next week because it falls  
on the same evening that his wife Laura is scheduled to receive an 
award from her alma mater. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family is my priority, and if it costs me votes for  
honoring my wife, so be it,'' Bush said, explaining his decision to 
miss the Oct. 28 event in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised to participate in debates with other GOP candidates  
before the start of the primary and caucus season. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush attended two fund-raisers in Vermont on Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The first was a $1,000-per-person private reception at a  
Waitsfield country inn that drew about 100 people. The event was 
expected to add $100,000 to the coffers of a campaign that already 
has raised a record $57 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He also addressed the Vermont Republican Party's annual fall  
dinner, attended by about 1,000 of the party faithful paying $125 
apiece to hear him speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush called on them to help him ``rally armies of compassion.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm running so our conservative minds can match our  
compassionate hearts,'' he said, in a variation on his campaign 
theme of ``compassionate conservatism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also spoke of the need to preserve Social Security while  
allowing beneficiaries to establish personal savings accounts 
within the system, the need for a strong military, to give families 
the right to choose the schools their children attend and to cut 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in Vermont, he told reporters he opposes gay marriage,  
no matter what the Vermont Supreme Court rules on a pending case 
seeking to legalize it. 
</P>
<P>
	``My opinion is we should not have same-gender marriage,'' Bush  
said after landing at the airport in South Burlington. ``I believe 
marriage is between a man and a woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he opposed the effort by New England states to win  
congressional reauthorization of a compact that provides farmers in 
the region with higher prices for milk. He said he preferred a 
``national dairy plan'' because ``that leads to competing compacts, 
states competing with each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also urged President Clinton to sign a bill the Senate  
passed this week to outlaw certain late-term abortions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
