<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Welcomes House Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Picking up his third endorsement from a House  
Democrat, presidential candidate Bill Bradley said elected 
officials shouldn't feel duty-bound to support Al Gore just because 
he is the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can be for Bradley and not vaporize,'' the former New  
Jersey senator said Friday after Rep. Diana DeGette, announced she 
was supporting him. ``I think there will be others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeGette, elected in 1996 to replace Pat Schroeder in a  
Denver-based district, said she liked Bradley's positions on health 
care for the uninsured, gun control and helping average people 
balance jobs and family. 
</P>
<P>
	``These challenges require big ideas and big solutions,''  
DeGette said. ``Senator Bradley is the candidate who offers the 
solutions to unite this country and forcefully address these 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, Bradley told a closed-door meeting of about 20  
liberal members of the House Progressive Caucus that he thought 
personal attacks in the campaign were ineffective and would hurt 
the Democratic Party, participants said afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he believed his poll numbers rose in Iowa this  
month after he declined to fight back when Gore accused him of 
quitting Congress when Democrats needed him most. 
</P>
<P>
	``His numbers rose and he said that there was nothing else to  
explain it,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who also has 
endorsed Bradley. ``He said fighting back's not necessary. He 
didn't think it would be useful for the party to have a 
bloodletting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore met the Progressive Caucus earlier this week. Both  
candidates are chasing endorsements from the Democratic nominating 
convention ``superdelegates,'' who are generally elected or party 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Both candidates discussed issues such as trade, the environment,  
labor and campaign finance reform, lawmakers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we wanted to do is have our issues, issues that affect  
working people and middle-class people, injected into the 
campaign,'' said Rep. Bernie Sanders, an independent from Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said a sharp contrast between the  
two was that Gore criticized Bradley by name over several issues, 
including his Senate voting record. Bradley, on the other hand, 
never mentioned the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of an odd reversal,'' DeFazio said. ``It's usually  
the challenger who goes after the incumbent. Gore acted much more 
like the underdog. Maybe he knows he's got a real race on his 
hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeGette, Nadler and Rep. William Lipinski, D-Ill., are the House  
members publicly supporting Bradley so far. Sens. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan of New York, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Paul Wellstone of 
Minnesota also have endorsed him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
