<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Research: Psychotherapy Predictable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) -- Researchers say they have developed the  
first successful way to predict how long a psychotherapy patient 
will need to recover, a key step in designing proper and successful 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Kopta, the University of Evansville psychology professor  
who led the research, said the predictions can be made with 75 
percent accuracy, depending on a patient's level of mental health. 
</P>
<P>
	The model allows therapists to decide which treatment to try but  
``one that you're more sure will work,'' he said Thursday. ``This 
ultimately can save resources because it can apply psychotherapy to 
people that are most likely to benefit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The research is published in the October issue of the Journal of  
Consulting and Clinical Psychology. 
</P>
<P>
	The team, which started collecting data in 1995, studied 870  
psychotherapy patients in the United States. About 80 percent were 
women. 
</P>
<P>
	By tracking the patients through their psychotherapy sessions,  
researchers developed a model for predicting courses of recovery 
for individual patients. The model also calculates the likelihood 
that the predictions will be correct. 
</P>
<P>
	``For some, we were 25 percent accurate. For others, almost 100  
percent,'' Kopta said. ``It would vary depending on the type of 
patient, the predictability of the estimate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is more difficult to accurately predict the recovery time for  
an individual who is deeply depressed or extremely anxious than for 
someone who is more optimistic about their chances, Kopta said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The value is, we're getting closer to be able to tailor a  
person's treatment needs before they begin therapy,'' he said. 
``Before, when a patient came in for therapy, often money was 
wasted in trial-and-error approaches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By using the model, a psychologist might, for example, decide  
that a patient would benefit more by using medication than by 
undergoing weeks or months of psychotherapy. That can save money 
for patients and their health-insurance carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Madhukar Trivedi, an associate professor of psychiatry at the  
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas, said 
everyone in the field of psychotherapy is interested in this area 
of study. 
</P>
<P>
	If the researchers' findings were accurate, he said, ``that is  
exciting. Nobody's done that yet and that really could give us very 
strong ideas.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
