<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President Signs $8.7B Farm Bailout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today signed into a law a  
record $8.7 billion package of emergency assistance to compensate 
farmers for depressed commodity prices and weather-related crop 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is contained in a $69 billion bill that will fund  
operations of the Agriculture Department and related agencies for 
the 2000 budget year. 
</P>
<P>
	The first assistance checks will be going to farmers in two to  
three weeks, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton agreed to sign the legislation despite his  
administration's reservations that some of the aid will be going to 
large farms and landowners who don't need the money, Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of moderate-size farmers who need these  
payments to survive, there's no question about that,'' Glickman 
said, speaking to reporters after a brief signing ceremony at the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to develop an alternative way to distribute future  
aid that would target the money to ``family-size'' operations, 
Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the money in the measure, about $6 billion, is intended  
to help grain, cotton and soybean farmers cope with a second year 
of low commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also provides $1.4 billion for weather-related crop  
and livestock losses, including $200 million earmarked for Eastern 
livestock producers who were hurt by this summer's drought; $400 
million in crop-insurance discounts; $328 million to compensate 
tobacco producers for falling cigarette sales; and $125 million in 
subsidies for dairy producers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
