<DOCNO> APW19991022.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 03:40:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida St.-Clemson Game Anticipated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEMSON, S.C. (AP) -- The motor homes are three deep. The tickets  
are all gone. About the only one who's apparently not going to the 
Florida State-Clemson game is Seminoles star Peter Warrick. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick was supposed to be polishing his Heisman Trophy  
acceptance speech for No. 1 Florida State (7-0, 5-0) in time for 
coach Bobby Bowden's 300th victory. 
</P>
<P>
	But a plea agreement to get him back on the field was postponed  
in connection with a department store scam that would reduce a 
felony grand theft charge to a misdemeanor. Warrick's lawyer, John 
Kenney, was hoping to get Warrick back this week, but the agreement 
has not been satisfactory to Florida State University President 
Sandy D'Alemberte. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I enter a plea that is acceptable to the court and is  
acceptable to the state attorney's office, but won't help him get 
back on the field, it's not going to make Peter Warrick very 
happy,'' lawyer John Kenny said Thursday. ``So I've got to try to 
work between the state attorney's office and the university. And 
right now, I don't have that set in concrete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About everything else for the historic game is, however. Clemson  
coach Tommy Bowden said an unheard number of fans, 87,000, are 
expected to fill Death Valley to see big-time college football's 
first father-son match. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said there might be as many as 15,000 fans who can't get  
in who'll just listen outside the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to be careful, Tommy and I both, that it does not  
become too much of a distraction,'' Bobby said. 
</P>
<P>
	Campers steadily pulled in behind the Tigers practice field all  
afternoon. Fans were sitting in lawn chairs and dressed in football 
sweat shirts 60 hours before kickoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Knight of St. George Island, Fla., has traveled with the  
Seminoles for more than 35 years and said he and his wife, 
Lorraine, weren't going to miss this one. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Ringle and his wife, JoAnn, of Oxford, Conn., parked next  
to the Knights. ``There are just so many family ties in this one, 
it's hard to keep track,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The town is buzzing, too. Former soccer coach I.M. Ibrahim said  
he sold more than 500 ``Bowden Bowl'' T-shirts from his two stores 
and expected the remaining stock to be gone by today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some dismal years,'' Ibrahim said. ``But coach Bowden's  
arrival has made Clemson paraphernalia a very hot item.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemson sports information director Tim Bourret said 535  
reporters, photographers and others have credentials for the game. 
Normal requests are about 200. State troopers will start traffic 
management at 9 a.m., 10 hours before kickoff, and will designate 
some two-way streets as one ways for the possible record crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby and Tommy shared ESPN appearances and radio shows  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tell Tommy to get out of town,'' Bobby said when the two were  
linked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to know who said Dad could horn in on my show. He  
recruits my state, he steals my players, I want him out now,'' 
Tommy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``See you Friday, Dad,'' Tommy said, signing off.  
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Bowden said his players are feeling as loose as he is.  
He's not worried about Warrick's status, since ``they just replace 
one Parade All-American with another Parade All-American.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His Tigers are big underdogs, so why should they worry, Bowden  
says. ``The problem is going to be our X's tackling their O's,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State quarterback Chris Weinke said he and his teammates  
have done a good job pushing away the overwhelming hype. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't talk about the 300th victory, we don't talk about  
anything except the fact that we need to win this football game and 
we need to find a way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemson defensive coordinator Reggie Herring said he's tried to  
prepare for this like any other game, ``but obviously, who are you 
kidding?'' 
</P>
<P>
	And don't believe Tommy when he says he's just going to enjoy  
his father's potential 300-win milestone, said Herring, Clemson's 
defensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll be jumping out of his skin. He'll be foaming at the  
mouth,'' Herring said. ``I've coached six games with him on the 
sidelines and I think that's wishful thinking on his part.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
