<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Skip GOP Candidates' Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Five Republican presidential candidates  
gathered Friday for their first debate, but the focus was on the 
rival who was not there: front-runner George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor opted to skip the New Hampshire forum weeks  
ago, as his $57 million campaign kitty and sizable lead in public 
opinion polls provided no real incentive for a face-to-face 
encounter with his challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Orrin Hatch, Alan Keyes and John  
McCain agreed to participate in the Friday night forum, sponsored 
by New Hampshire Public Television, The Union Leader of Manchester 
and New England Cable News. C-Span planned to broadcast the session 
live. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry that Governor Bush is continuing to play this delay  
game, hoping to force everybody out of the issue by burying them 
with big dollars,'' Bauer said Thursday as he arrived in the state 
for a local forum with Hatch and Keyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's actually going to make it harder for Governor  
Bush to convince the voters of New Hampshire that he's got a 
governing vision,'' Bauer added. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who had campaign stops in New Hampshire on Friday, said he  
had committed to a fund-raiser for Vermont Republicans at the same 
time of the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	He also declined to participate in an Oct. 28 debate because it  
conflicted with a ceremony honoring his wife, Laura, at her alma 
mater, Southern Methodist University in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's debate came one day after the latest New Hampshire poll  
showed Bush with a commanding lead but McCain strengthening his 
position in second place. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone survey of 600 likely Republican voters, Bush had  
the support of 42 percent, about what he had in August. McCain had 
26 percent -- 10 points better than in August -- with most of his 
gains coming at the expense of other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting also came two days after Elizabeth Dole, the lone  
woman seeking the GOP nomination, announced she was quitting the 
race because of difficulty in raising money. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Bush, one prominent GOP candidate who also skipped the  
forum was conservative commentator Pat Buchanan. He is expected to 
announce Monday that he is leaving the Republican Party to seek the 
nomination of the Reform Party. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
