<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Concerned by Chechnya Attack  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House expressed concern today about  
the ``terrible loss of life'' in Chechnya -- at least 143 killed in 
a missile attack-- and urged Moscow to open a dialogue with leaders 
of the breakaway Russian republic. The administration avoided 
pointing a finger of blame for the attack after a Russian military 
spokesman said it was a special operation and Russian political 
officials denied any responsibility. ``There are conflicting 
reports. ... We don't have a conclusive answer at this point,'' 
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 

</P>
<P>
	Parachutist Dies in Protest Jump  
</P>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- A 60-year-old parachutist  
plunged to her death when her chute failed to open while jumping 
off a 3,200-foot-cliff today during a protest of park rules banning 
such jumps. Jan Davis was one of five jumpers off Yosemite's most 
forbidding peak, a protest organized in response to the June 9 
death of a jumper who successfully parachuted off El Capitan, only 
to drown in the river below while trying to elude rangers. The 
danger of the extreme sport of jumping off cliffs, buildings and 
other stationary objects led the National Park Service to ban such 
jumps. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush-Bashing Book Recalled  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- St. Martin's Press today recalled 70,000 copies  
of ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the Making of an American 
President,'' already in stores. The move comes after the disclosure 
that the biographer, James Howard Hatfield, was convicted in 1988 
for plotting to murder a co-worker. The publisher yesterday 
suspended sales, shipment and promotion of the book. The book 
accused the GOP presidential front-runner of burying a cocaine 
arrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Budget Wrangling Goes on  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders embraced a 1.4  
percent across-the-board cut in federal agency budgets today to 
keep spending bills from eating into Social Security surpluses. The 
proposal, opposed by President Clinton, adds one more point of 
contention to the fight between the White House and Congress as the 
two sides struggle over unfinished spending measures for the new 
fiscal year. GOP leaders said that under their plan, aimed at 
saving $4.5 billion this year, agency heads would be asked to weed 
out waste, fraud and abuse from their budgets. 

</P>
<P>
	Deal Reached on Financial Overhaul Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lengthy political struggle may be coming to  
an end over legislation that would make it easier for banks, stock 
brokerages and insurance companies to combine and sell each other's 
products. Key Republican lawmakers reached agreement early today 
with Democrats and Clinton administration officials on provisions 
in the bill dealing with community lending rules for banks. The 
bill is designed to overhaul Depression-era financial services 
laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic To Allow Montenegro Split  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbian officials said today that  
President Slobodan Milosevic will allow Montenegro to leave the 
Yugoslav federation if the republic decides to do so. The 
government of Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic has demanded 
radical restructuring of the Yugoslav federation, a process that 
would virtually abolish Milosevic's control over the small 
republic. Montenegro plans to hold an independence referendum in 
case Milosevic rejects its proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Allowed To Unmask Klansmen  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a victory for New York City, a federal  
appeals panel ruled today that the city does not have to allow Ku 
Klux Klan members to wear their masks at a planned rally tomorrow. 
Yesterday, a lower court had ordered the city to allow KKK members 
to hold the rally while wearing their hooded white masks. City 
attorney Michael Hess said the KKK leaders had not applied for a 
permit yet. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 172.56 at 10,470.25  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today on the possibility  
that legislation will soon allow banks, stock brokerages and 
insurance companies to combine. The Dow Jones industrial closed up 
172.56 at 10,470.25. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,960-1,062. The Nasdaq composite index was 
up 14.57 at 2,816.52. 

</P>
<P>
	Gaston Interviews for Indians Job  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cito Gaston today interviewed for the Cleveland  
Indians' managing job. Gaston, who led the Toronto Blue Jays to 
Series titles in 1992 and '93, met with Indians general manager 
John Hart and assistant GM Mark Shapiro for more than three hours. 
The Indians fired Mike Hargrove last week following their collapse 
against the Boston Red Sox in the first round of the AL playoffs. 
Hart plans to meet with Braves hitting instructor Don Baylor and 
New York Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss over the weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
