<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii Dockworkers Authorize Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Hawaii's largest group of union dockworkers  
voted Friday to call a strike if shippers don't meet their contract 
demands. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of a strike has triggered panic buying of staples  
like rice, Spam and toilet paper in Hawaii, where 90 percent of 
goods arrive by ship. 
</P>
<P>
	The 507-member International Longshore and Warehouse Union  
canceled a contract extension Monday with the state's four major 
shipping companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Oahu members, the largest contingent with 427 workers,  
authorized a strike on Friday, joining union members on the islands 
of Kauai, Maui and Hawaii who voted earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders can call a strike at any time now, but contract  
talks are scheduled for Saturday. The union wants pay raises 
similar to the three-year, 8 percent wage increase West Coast 
dockworkers received. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll make every effort to settle amicably. We're prepared to  
negotiate around the clock,'' said Local 142 President Eusebio 
Lapenia. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Hawaii Employers Council, which represents  
the shippers, could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Ben Cayetano has offered to mediate. He is so confident  
there will not be a strike that he asked his household staff not to 
raid supermarkets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to go out and stock up on bags of rice and  
soap and toilet paper and all that because I feel good about what's 
happening right now,'' he said. ``I think both sides don't want the 
rest of the state to suffer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, dockworkers staged a work slowdown that created a  
backlog of unloaded cargo ships in Honolulu Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	If dockworkers strike, ships that arrive in Hawaii will sit in  
port without being unloaded. And if the walkout drags on, shipping 
companies will stop sending vessels on the five-day journey from 
the West Coast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
