<HEADLINE> BC Hasn't Beaten Miami Since Flutie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The tapes of Doug Flutie's 48-yard desperation  
touchdown pass are getting grainy with age now. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been 15 years since the ``Hail Flutie'' gave Boston College  
its last win over Miami, and Saturday is as good a time as any for 
the Eagles to reverse their nine-game losing streak against the 
Hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston College (5-1, 2-1 Big East) won its first four games,  
then took a 14-0 lead against Temple two weeks ago before giving up 
24 consecutive points. The Eagles bounced back with a win over 
Pittsburgh last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami (2-3, 0-0) is riding a three-game losing streak, but is  
still ranked No. 23. The Eagles hope to continue the Hurricanes' 
losing streak on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the hard part of the schedule is over now,'' BC coach  
Tom O'Brien said, even though his upcoming schedule includes 
Syracuse, West Virginia, Notre Dame and Virginia Tech. ``To take 
this young football team and go through the expectations that were 
put upon them -- everybody was talking 6-0, 5-1 -- to put that upon 
them was tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we enter a phase where nobody gives them a chance to do  
anything,'' O'Brien said. ``We've got everything to gain and 
nothing to lose. We can relax and play football. Mentally, it will 
be a much better situation for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miami beat Ohio State and Florida A&AMP;M before losing to three  
consecutive ranked teams, including No. 1 Florida State. Last 
week's game was supposed to be a streak-stopper, against Temple, 
but it was postponed until Dec. 4 because of Hurricane Irene. 
</P>
<P>
	``(The players) are getting edgy to play,'' coach Butch Davis  
said. ``It seems like all we've done is practice the last 12 weeks. 
We just need to go play a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes have not won since Labor Day weekend, a span of  
more than six weeks -- their longest midseason winless stretch since 
1970. But they've beaten BC nine consecutive times, and 17 out of 
20 in all. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time they met in Chestnut Hill, in 1997, the Hurricanes  
needed two overtimes to take a 45-44 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``In due time, we're going to get our win,'' wide receiver  
Santana Moss said. ``And I think it will be this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although they've yet to play their first Big East game, Miami  
could catapult itself into the Big East race with a victory. Only 
No. 4 Virginia Tech is left unbeaten in the conference, and the 
teams will play Nov. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like two seasons,'' Davis said. ``We had five  
non-conference games, and those are over with. Now we've got to 
turn our attention to seven consecutive conference games and look 
at this as a fresh start. We're 0-0, and we'll see what happens.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
