<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marathoner Seeks U.S. Citizenship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Khalid Khannouchi is the United States' best hope  
for an Olympic medal in the marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	There's just one problem: He's not an American citizen yet.  
</P>
<P>
	The Moroccan-born runner's request for expedited citizenship was  
rejected in June, leaving on hold his hopes of running in the 
Sydney Olympics as an American. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still working on it and I'm always positive that I'll  
get my citizenship,'' said Khannouchi, the 1997 LaSalle Banks 
Chicago Marathon champion and a favorite to win again Sunday. 
``Hopefully, I'll be able to run in the Olympics as an American. I 
want to give something back to this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without Khannouchi, American prospects are dim. Besides  
Khannouchi, the favorites in Chicago on Sunday are world 
record-holder Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil; defending champion Ondoro 
Osoro of Kenya, and South Africa's Hendrik Ramaala, who is running 
his first marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	The top American in the field, Todd Williams, has a personal  
best of 2:11:17, more than five minutes behind da Costa's 
world-record of 2:06:05. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook isn't much better among the women. Ireland's  
Catherina McKiernan, who has won all three marathons she's entered, 
has a personal best of 2:22:33, while Joyce Chepchumba of Kenya won 
last year's race in 2:23:57. 
</P>
<P>
	The top Americans in Sunday's field, Kristy Johnson and Libbie  
Hickman, have run 2:29:05 and 2:33:06, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always darkest before the dawn,'' Carey Pinkowski, the  
Chicago Marathon's race director, said of the United States' 
long-distance prospects. ``It's got to get better. So I'm not going 
to give up on it. We'll have another Frank Shorter or Alberto 
Salazar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, though, the best hope is Khannouchi. He played soccer  
as a boy, then took up running when his father encouraged him to 
try an individual sport. After only a year of formal training, he 
won the Moroccan cross country championship. He also won junior 
titles at 5,000 and 10,000 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	But Morocco had other elite runners, and Khannouchi didn't get  
the support he wanted from his country's running federation. So in 
1993, he moved to New York without money or a job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got the support from the Americans I didn't get from my own  
country,'' he said. ``They knew I was a great runner, but they 
didn't give me the support. Americans took me in and carried me to 
the top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After winning six road races at shorter distances in 1997,  
Khannouchi made his marathon debut in Chicago and won in 2:07:10, a 
world debut best and the fourth-fastest time ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory made Khannouchi famous. He even got to meet Michael  
Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``This morning, at the airport, I met a guy who shook my hand  
and another man called out my name. I love that,'' Khannouchi said 
Thursday. ``That's the reason I'm training hard. That's the reason 
I want to succeed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Running with a stress fracture in his left heel, Khannouchi  
finished second last year to Osoro, who broke Khannouchi's debut 
record with a time of 2:06:54. 
</P>
<P>
	He's run nine races this year, winning five and finishing second  
in three. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy the way I'm racing,'' he said. ``I'm in good shape,  
but it doesn't matter if I'm in better shape or not. Sometimes you 
can prepare right and just not have your day. But the training went 
according to my plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's something telling me I'm going to have a good race  
...'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
