<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berger Slams 'Isolationist Right' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The United States will not have the authority to  
remain the world's leader if isolationists continue to control 
Congress, national security adviser Sandy Berger told a foreign 
policy group in a scathing criticism of Republican lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Following two major foreign policy defeats in Congress for the  
Clinton administration, Berger called for a national debate on 
foreign policy and said the administration would fight 
``isolationist right'' lawmakers during President Clinton's last 15 
months in office. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new isolationism of 1999 fails to understand precisely  
what the old isolationism of 60 years ago failed to understand -- 
that local conflicts can have global consequences,'' he said. ``In 
effect, they believe in a survivalist foreign policy -- build a 
fortified fence around America and retreat behind it. And if other 
nations complain ... let them, because we are stronger and richer 
than they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas dismissed the speech  
as ``random name-calling by a frustrated administration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armey, in a statement, said ``today's world of peace and  
prosperity was built on the Republican policies of free trade, a 
strong military, a larger NATO and support for Democratic allies 
like Taiwan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush were not  
isolationists ``and neither are we,'' Armey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking Thursday to the Council on Foreign Relations, a private  
group that usually supports an activist U.S. foreign policy, 
Berger's comments also appeared to be an effort to make foreign 
policy a larger campaign issue in 2000. He attacked conservative 
Republicans who blocked a ban on nuclear weapons testing and are 
cutting back overseas programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Inhofe, a foe of the test ban treaty, said the notion  
of lost U.S. leadership was ``absurd,'' adding that the treaty's 
defeat actually would help restore American stature. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will improve our international respect and leadership,  
because we said we are not going to unilaterally disarm anymore,'' 
Inhofe, R-Okla., said in Washington. ``We are going to gain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president is now giving priority to peacemaking in the  
Middle East and in Northern Ireland and to working with Russia on 
missile defenses while also supporting democracy and capitalism 
there, Berger said, adding that the $12.6 billion foreign aid bill 
that Clinton vetoed on Monday could have hampered U.S. efforts to 
promote peace and stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress cut $2 billion from Clinton's proposed budget for  
foreign aid while adding $5 billion to the Pentagon's budget, a 
move that Berger denounced, saying, ``if we underfund our 
diplomacy, we will end up overusing our military.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said most Americans ``understand that we are fortunate to  
be in a position of leadership, and that to maintain it we must 
continue to lead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But congressional isolationists, he said, were consumed with an  
impulse ``to withdraw from the world in a way that would squander 
our advantages, alienate our friends, diminish our credibility, 
betray our values and discredit our example.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Describing congressional conservatives as ``nostalgic for the  
good old days'' when the Soviet Union was a distinct adversary, 
Berger said some have designated China, with its growing economy 
and nuclear program, as the new ``great adversary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said China is a country that has lifted tens of millions  
of its people from poverty and expanded personal freedoms. But it 
also is resisting political reform that is needed for long-term 
growth and stability. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our interest lies in protecting our security while encouraging  
China to make the right choices,'' Berger said. ``We can only do 
that if we continue a policy of principled, purposeful engagement 
with its leaders and people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
