<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canadiens' Hackett Expected Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Montreal Canadiens goaltender Jeff Hackett was  
expected to start Saturday night in Toronto after missing only one 
game with a bruised shoulder and back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Karl Dykhuis, acquired Wednesday from Philadelphia  
for future considerations, was expected to make his Canadiens' 
debut in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	But right wing Dainius Zubrus joined the Canadiens' already  
lengthy injury list with a hip pointer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackett was injured when he was run over by Steve Webb while  
playing the puck alone the sideboards during Montreal's 4-2 loss to 
the New York Islanders last Monday. He sat out a 2-1 loss to the 
Colorado Avalanche on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Zubrus did not make the trip to Toronto, nor did fourth-line  
wing Aaron Asham, who will miss a second game with a sore back. 
</P>
<P>
	With Zubrus out, the Canadiens are expected to promote Martin  
Rucinsky to their top line with center Saku Koivu and wing Brian 
Savage, who has nine goals in as many games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's practice, the second line had Craig Darby centering  
for Scott Thornton and Trevor Linden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadiens returned goaltender Mathieu Garon and defenseman  
Stephane Robidas to Quebec of the AHL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
