<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Not Concerned About 2004 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee is not  
worried about efforts to fund the 2004 Olympics despite the 
cancellation of plans of an online gambling network that was seen 
as a key money maker. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely not concerned,'' Jacques Rogge, head of the  
IOC coordination commission for the Athens games, said Friday 
following three days of meetings with organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	The online gambling program was called off by Premier Costas  
Simitis on Wednesday after it was fiercely criticized by opposition 
parties. Besides being a political embarrassment, it was seen as a 
possible blow to Greece's struggling efforts to pay for the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge also discussed another possible difficulty ahead for  
Athens organizers: keeping to the construction schedule for venues 
and other sites. Some of the projects have been turned over to 
government ministries, which could entangle the process in 
political bickering and Greece's bureaucracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge urged the government for a ``fast resolution'' on any  
outstanding details. Although about 75 percent of the venues 
already exist, some need to be modernized, Rogge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge, IOC director-general Francois Carrard and sports director  
Gilbert Felli met with the secretariat involved in communication 
between the ministries. 
</P>
<P>
	In other points discussed during the visit:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Organizers promised the host broadcast company for the games  
would be set by December. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The IOC requested the creation of a special task force to  
study transportation issues in chronically crowded Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Rogge urged continued attention to anti-terrorist measures.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
