<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons' Bison Dele Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons are thinking about placing  
center Bison Dele on the suspended list rather than the retirement 
list, a spokesman said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-11 Dele has filed retirement papers with the NBA  
office in New York, fulfilling a promise he made last month. 
</P>
<P>
	If he is placed on the suspended list, the Pistons could  
reinstate him if he changes his mind -- or trade him. If Dele goes 
on the retirement list, he will have to sit out the entire season. 
</P>
<P>
	Team spokesman J.J. Carter said Friday that the team hadn't made  
a decision yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the start of the season, he would probably be on the  
suspended list,'' Carter said, although he added, ``he's pretty 
much said he's not coming back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pistons general manager Rick Sund said Thursday that the team  
was not surprised by Dele's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We said from the beginning that his talent helps our club,''  
Sund said. ``If he wanted to come back, we would look at that 
situation very strongly. Or, if he wanted to be traded we could 
look at that if it was something that made sense for our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Lakers and at least one other team have inquired  
about Dele, The Detroit News reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, who averaged 10.5 points and 5.6 rebounds in 49  
regular-season games and 10.6 points and 6.4 rebounds in five 
playoff games last season, will forfeit the $5.67 million he stood 
to earn this season. He has five years and $36.45 million left on 
his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, formerly known as Brian Williams, was the team's  
highest-paid player. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, 30, told the Pistons last month about his possible desire  
to retire. He missed training camp and preseason play. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent two seasons in Detroit after signing as a free agent,  
and his relationship with his teammates was said to be strained. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
