<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 14:30:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Embraces Budget Cut Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders embraced a 1.4  
percent across-the-board cut in federal agency budgets Friday to 
keep spending bills from eating into Social Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, White House officials used budget talks with  
lawmakers to propose a new savings plan of their own: a tax on 
tobacco companies triggered if teen-age smoking rises, said 
participants who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The across-the-board cut, opposed by President Clinton, adds one  
more point of contention to the fight between the White House and 
Congress as the two sides struggle over unfinished spending 
measures for the new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders said that under their plan, aimed at saving $4.5  
billion this year, agency heads would be asked to weed out waste, 
fraud and abuse from their budgets. No programs covered by the 13 
annual spending bills would be exempted, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is going to probably complain we're going to  
hurt all these vulnerable people,'' said House Budget Committee 
Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, one of the plan's proponents. ``But 
this is a great opportunity for us ... to begin to root out the 
duplication and wasteful programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said that under the  
proposal, when Pentagon officials testify before Congress, 
``instead of having two colonels hold your paper, you'll have only 
one major.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not affected would be the salaries of members of Congress. Since  
1981, the money for their pay comes from a part of the federal 
budget not controlled by the spending bills. The rest of Congress' 
budget, such as office expenses, would be subject to the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers voted themselves a 3.4 percent pay raise this year.  
That $4,600 increase will boost their salaries to $141,300 
beginning in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's payroll would be affected, but individual  
federal workers' salaries could not be cut because they are set by 
law. Payroll savings could be achieved by not filling positions of 
civil servants who quit or retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Also not affected would be Social Security, Medicare and other  
benefits paid by the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be up to agency officials to decide where the  
reductions would come from. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Clinton threatened to veto legislation making  
across-the-board reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials and Democrats say the cut would damage  
programs covering education, the environment and other areas while 
not achieving the GOP's goal of leaving Social Security surpluses 
alone. Citing Congressional Budget Office analyses, they say 
Republican spending plans dip into Social Security surpluses by at 
least $13 billion more than the GOP admits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bad idea that is unacceptable,'' said White House  
budget office spokeswoman Linda Ricci. 
</P>
<P>
	Using Social Security surpluses for other spending has been done  
by both parties for decades, and has no effect on the government's 
ability to pay Social Security benefits. Protecting those surpluses 
also does nothing to revamp the program, which many experts say is 
needed to prepare it for baby boomers' approaching retirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, both parties have latched onto the issue as they  
position themselves as guardians of the giant pension program for 
next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, across-the-board reductions have not fared well  
in Congress, where they inevitably end up cutting programs that 
lawmakers like. 
</P>
<P>
	But GOP lawmakers have coalesced around their leaders' calls to  
protect Social Security's surpluses. They believe the strategy has 
made it harder for Clinton to find ways to pay for his spending 
demands, and helped burnish the GOP's image among the program's 
mostly elderly recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	The across-the-board reduction will be attached to a mammoth  
spending measure covering the departments of Education, Labor and 
Health and Human Services that Congress plans to send Clinton next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be the last of the 13 annual spending bills for fiscal  
2000, which began Oct. 1, to be sent to Clinton. He has threatened 
to veto it -- one of six he has vetoed or might veto -- because it 
ignores his demands for $1.4 billion for hiring schoolteachers. 
</P>
<P>
	For further savings, that bill will also contain $1.3 billion in  
savings by delaying some grants to the National Institutes of 
Health and other health agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, White House budget chief Jack Lew told congressional  
budget writers about the administration's new plan for taxing 
tobacco companies. The levy, which he referred to as a penalty, 
would encourage cigarette makers to stop marketing their product to 
teen-agers, he said, according to participants. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew provided no details about the tax.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has conceded his plan to raise cigarette taxes by 55  
cents a pack cannot pass Congress. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
