<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Reaches Union Settlement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After seven months of often tense negotiations,  
Dow Jones &AMP; Co. has settled a dispute over retirement benefits with 
the union representing reporters and editors at The Wall Street 
Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Paul Steiger told employees Friday that he will stay on as  
the Journal's managing editor. CNN had been courting Steiger to 
head up its business news operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute over retirement benefits had left Journal employees  
working without a contract for nearly two months. It also led to 
picketing by staffers and angry speeches by two senior reporters at 
the company's annual shareholders' meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement with the Independent Association of Publishers'  
Employees/CWA Local 1096 calls for wage increases totaling 9.5 
percent over three years and a company contribution of up to 12 
percent of an employee's salary to pension plans. The pact still 
needs the approval of the union's 2,400 members. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest disagreement was over the size of Dow Jones' pension  
contributions, which the company wanted to decrease. Under a 
previous plan, Dow Jones contributed 15 percent of an employee's 
salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones chairman Peter Kann and general counsel Peter Skinner  
sent a note to employees Friday saying: ``While the negotiations 
that led to last night's agreement have been lengthy and sometimes 
difficult, we think that both sides here have achieved their key 
objectives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other protests from Journal reporters over the summer included  
refusing to appear on CNBC, which has an arrangement with Dow 
Jones, and bombarding Dow Jones executives with e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, Paul Steiger, managing editor of The Wall Street  
Journal, told his staffers at a regular morning meeting that he 
would stay at the newspaper, Dow Jones spokesman Richard Tofel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN had been trying to recruit Steiger to head up the network's  
business news operations, a post left vacant by the departure of 
Lou Dobbs in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Tofel declined to discuss details of Steiger's negotiations with  
CNN, and a spokeswoman for CNN also declined to comment. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
