<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morgan Stanley Sues Over Web Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A rose called by any other name might smell as  
sweet, but for a financial services giant, having to come up with 
another Web address because someone else owns the one it wants just 
stinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. is suing the 17-year-old  
creator of the http://www.msdwonline.com site, saying the Web address 
infringes on the company's trademarks and asking a judge to stop 
him from using it. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Wong of Hillsborough, Calif., said his site, ``Mud Sweat's  
Downhill World,'' is named after the store that sold him his 
mountainbike, Mud, Sweat and Gears. The similarity to Morgan 
Stanley's main site, http://www.msdw.com, was just a coincidence, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in its lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,  
Morgan Stanley says the address was targeted specifically in hopes 
of getting the company to pay up to buy the domain name back. 
</P>
<P>
	A company set up by the boy's father, Sau Wong, has registered  
dozens of domain names, many using the names of investment banks, 
including jpmorganonline.com and goldmansachsdirect.com, The New 
York Times reported today. The company, Smart Ideas, registered 
www.msdwonline.com in May, not long before Morgan Stanley decided 
that msdwonline should be the domain name for its new online 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In a motion filed this week, Morgan Stanley said ``the defendant  
in this case has targeted MSDW and the New York investment banking 
community with particular precision and malice.'' Morgan Stanley 
says the boy's bicycle-themed page didn't even appear until after 
the lawsuit was filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley said it had been willing to pay Ivan Wong $10,000  
to buy the name back, with one official describing the offer as ``a 
nice bag of money'' for a teen-age boy. 
</P>
<P>
	But then the company received a demand for $75,000, and when  
Morgan Stanley balked, it got a message from the boy's father, 
saying, ``you are not dealing with a kid,'' the newspaper reported. 
The company withdrew its offer and filed suit Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The company considers the case to be an example of  
``cybersquatting,'' the practice of registering domain names in 
hopes of selling them to companies that have a commercial use for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Pam Samuelson, a professor of law at the University of  
California at Berkeley, told the newspaper a federal law is 
intended to stop cybersquatters from diluting the value of 
established trademarks. But Morgan Stanley doesn't have as strong a 
case, she said, because MSDW is relatively new and not that famous. 
Morgan Stanley merged with Dean Witter in 1997. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
