<DOCNO> APW19991022.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 09:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stunning Retrospective Shows Ensor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Fifty years after his time, a major  
show on James Ensor reveals just how much ahead of his time the 
Belgian painter really was. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of his life, his genius was ignored, even ridiculed by  
critics. As recently as a dozen years ago, Belgium let go of 
Ensor's absolute masterpiece without much ado, with the drone of 
indifference drowning out the few shrieks of outrage. 
</P>
<P>
	Ensor, who died in 1949, gets some of his due back with a  
spectacular retrospective show at the Beaux-Arts Museum in central 
Brussels that runs through Feb. 13. It has received rave reviews 
since the Sept. 24 opening. 
</P>
<P>
	In the biggest show of Ensor work since the 1920s, his breath of  
talent is on full show and will satisfy anyone with a taste for the 
moody seascapes of William Turner, the vivid colors and strokes of 
van Gogh, and Edvard Munch's angst-ridden penchant for the macabre. 
</P>
<P>
	The J. Paul Getty Museum in Malibu, Calif., refused to allow his  
1888 magnum opus ``Christ's Entry Into Brussels'' to travel, but 
the exhibition's organizers could well have dispensed with the 
reproduction that now only distracts from the wealth of his other 
work in the show. 
</P>
<P>
	The show centers on his most creative period, from 1885 to 1895,  
when masks, skulls, daring colors and unconventional vision made 
him one of the greatest precursors of 20th-century art. 
</P>
<P>
	``We discover the greatest artist. It is this painter whom this  
fascinating and exciting retrospective most truly celebrates,'' 
gushed William Packer, art critic of London's Financial Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps we are lucky Ensor rarely heard such glowing comments  
since he thrived on mainstream rejection. When he was made a baron 
in a belated sign of recognition, he had long lost his zest to defy 
society and even much of his inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so in the 1880s, when he turned the attic above his mother's  
curiosity shop on the North Sea coast in Ostend into a cauldron of 
artistic renewal. Alfred H. Barr, the founder of New York's Museum 
of Modern Art, said Ensor was at the time perhaps the most 
progressive artist, bar none, from a list that includes van Gogh, 
Gauguin and Cezanne. 
</P>
<P>
	He experimented with light in such works as the 1887 ``Adam and  
Eve Expelled From Paradise'' and ``Carnival on the Beach'' of the 
same year. He used masks and their power of expression in the 
1883's ``Scandalized Masks,'' and showed his fascination with death 
in the 1885 work, ``Skeleton Watching Curiosities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He got the idea for his masks from those on display in his  
mother's shop and marveled at their symbolic meaning. He painted 
them for every occasion and often highlighted their escapism -- to 
be what one is not without being recognized -- as he condemned their 
inherent falsehood. 
</P>
<P>
	Until his death, he headed the jury of Ostend's Mardi Gras mask  
festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Masks often shared the scene with skulls and bones. Death  
fascinated him. His 1889 ``Self-portrait With Skull,'' in which his 
face is eaten away with decay, exposing the bare bones, shockingly 
contrasts with his youthful ``Self-Portrait With Masks,'' painted a 
decade later. 
</P>
<P>
	His work held the germs of impressionism, expressionism and even  
surrealism all at once. Add to that the thrill to outrage, and even 
Dada is well represented: viewers were thrilled by his ribald humor 
of puking art critics, defecating politicians and flatulent 
magicians. At the same time bourgeois ladies marveled at the 
painterly opulence of the ``Oyster Eater'' and the inner light 
``Somber Lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1893, the conservative bourgeoisie could not care less. When,  
in a fit of depression, Ensor offered to sell his entire works for 
a measly $210, including many of his masterworks, he found no 
taker. He was derisively considered a painter of seashells. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1987, things had changed to the extent that the authorities  
could not hold on to ``Christ's Entry Into Brussels,'' and it was 
whisked away to Malibu for a sum reportedly in excess of $10 
million. Ensor's paintings are now scattered as far as Fort Worth, 
Texas and Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps it is the artist's final irony that he now graces the  
100 franc bill, Belgium's most commonly used bank note, worth $2.50 
in American money. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Norris Gets Wish To Fight Tyson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Mike Tyson's comeback story is becoming  
increasingly familiar. So are the plans of those who enter the ring 
with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlin Norris knows what he has to do to win Saturday night when  
he meets the former heavyweight champion in Tyson's latest comeback 
bid: Follow the game plans of Evander Holyfield and Francois Botha, 
and hope he doesn't get hit with a big punch. 
</P>
<P>
	It worked for Holyfield, and it was working for Botha before a  
right hand that crashed into his face brought a sudden halt to the 
Jan. 16 fight in the fifth round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Botha fought him the right way for the time he fought him,''  
Norris said. ``He did a lot of things right and he didn't stay in 
front of him until that last round. He fought Tyson the way you're 
supposed to fight Tyson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, a former cruiserweight champion with a mediocre record  
in the heavyweight division, gets the chance of his boxing career 
when he meets Tyson in a scheduled 10-round fight at the MGM Grand 
hotel-casino. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a fight Norris sought a decade ago, when Tyson was at his  
prime and Norris saw an opportunity that seemed destined never to 
come. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a fight I've always wanted,'' Norris said. ``We're  
both the same height, one's a puncher and one's a boxer. I've 
always thought it would be a very good fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oddsmakers here don't, however, making Tyson a 12-1 favorite in  
the fight that will be shown on the Showtime cable network 
beginning sometime before midnight EDT, but after the end of the 
first World Series game. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact Tyson is not on pay-per-view is an indication both that  
the intrigue of his fourth comeback has not risen to the level of 
previous comeback bids and that the 34-year-old Norris is not 
considered a serious contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, however, remains an attraction, though it is as much for  
his unpredictability as his boxing skills these days. 
</P>
<P>
	``People love Mike Tyson,'' said Dan Goossen, president of  
promoter America Presents. ``They love to see him win. They love to 
see him lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson weighed in officially Thursday at 223 pounds, which was  
his weight for the Botha fight. Norris weighed 218 pounds, two 
pounds less than when he stopped Pele Reid on June 26 in his only 
fight in 12 1-2 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am planning to bring a lot of pain,'' Tyson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Norris, 50-5 in his lengthy career, will try to avoid that pain  
by fighting Tyson from the outside, and tying him up when the two 
get inside. 
</P>
<P>
	He's not likely to pose a knockout threat himself, with the 27  
stoppages on his record coming mainly with an accumulation of 
punches in late rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson showed he hasn't lost his knockout punch against Botha,  
who was his first opponent since being banned from boxing for 
biting Holyfield's ears. Tyson has been inactive since, having to 
serve 3 1/2 months in a Maryland prison for assaulting two men 
following a minor traffic accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson has not gone the distance in a fight since a decision over  
Razor Ruddock eight years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he is going to hit me. I have to avoid the big bombs,''  
Botha said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson brought back his former lead trainer, Jay Bright, to help  
Tommy Brooks train him for Norris. He looked good in an open 
training session earlier this week, knocking down a sparring 
partner, and Brooks said his 33-year-old reflexes are coming back. 
</P>
<P>
	``The true confidence for Mike is the ability for him to step in  
the ring and hit and not be hit and that's what he's doing,'' 
Brooks said. ``He's landing and he's not taking shots and thus he 
is beginning to believe that he is good enough and that he can get 
it all back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, whose financial problems are well known, is getting  
somewhere between $7 million and $10 million for the fight, while 
Norris will earn $700,000. 
</P>
<P>
	If Tyson wins and looks good enough in doing so, his handlers  
want him to fight once again this year, in December in a 
pay-per-view bout. Though he has lost two of his last three fights 
and was losing badly to Botha when he knocked him out, Tyson still 
figures to be a force in a heavyweight division that pretty much 
begins and ends right now with Holyfield and Lennox Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	In another fight on the card, undefeated Diego Corrales will  
challenge another unbeaten fighter, Roberto Garcia, for Garcia's 
IBF junior lightweight title. Corrales is 28-0 and the No. 1 
challenger to Garcia, who is 32-0. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
