<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiny Beetles Threaten California Oaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT TAMALPAIS, Calif. (AP) -- Thousands of the state's majestic  
oak trees, already weakened by a mysterious disease, now face a 
second threat from bark-burrowing beetles killing the trees from 
the inside out. 
</P>
<P>
	Bewildered tree experts and stunned homeowners have watched as  
trees wither in a matter of weeks. The beetles have claimed 
thousands of live oaks and tan oaks along a 200-mile swath of 
coastline. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one knows what's going on. Not even the state,'' said Mitzi  
Staley, a gardener for the University of California's extension 
service. ``We don't know if it's a cyclical thing or a pollution 
thing because we haven't had anything like this for a long time. 
And once it starts, there's not much you can do about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two types of beetles are being blamed: the Western oak bark  
beetle, which burrows under the bark until it falls off, and the 
oak ambrosia beetle, which tunnels into the wood and deposits a 
fungus that clogs the trees' circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts aren't sure why the trees became sick in the first  
place. 
</P>
<P>
	One theory is that the tan oaks were somehow weakened by  
drought, El Nino or pollution and developed some kind of 
unexplained disease. Beetles then preyed on the weakened tan oaks, 
and eventually spread to the live oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Pavel Svihra, a researcher with the university extension  
service, called the problem an ``entomological blitzkrieg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This epidemic is critical for two reasons,'' he said. ``One,  
it makes the ecosystem unstable. Two, as trees die, each becomes 
fuel for fire. And fires can be extremely explosive in an area like 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few thousand trees out of California's 10 million acres of oak  
woodlands may seem insignificant. But the problem affects urban 
areas, too, disturbing a well-off coastal population whose property 
value has everything to do with trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a lot of well-heeled Marin County residents with  
hundreds of trees dying,'' said Bruce Hagen of the California 
Department of Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Live oaks are almost emblematic of the state. They're durable  
trees that can grow many hundreds of years,'' he said. ``People 
have learned to love their oaks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Moerdyke cut down 200 trees on his 140-acre ranch near  
Santa Cruz, and hand-sprayed several thousand more. 
</P>
<P>
	``The alternative would be losing all my trees,'' he said. ``I'm  
hopefully getting it under control.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
