<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Huang Soon May Be Telling His Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Justice Department official said Thursday  
night that the way soon may be clear for John Huang, a central 
figure in the campaign fund-raising investigation, to testify 
before a congressional committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has been conducting an espionage investigation of Huang.  
</P>
<P>
	While not saying that the espionage investigation is completed,  
the department official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 
the Justice Department no longer will oppose granting limited 
immunity from prosecution to Huang. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Government Reform Committee led by Rep. Dan Burton,  
R-Ind., has been seeking Huang's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	But Huang's lawyer has set a grant of immunity as a condition  
for his client to testify to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	An immunity grant would make it extremely difficult for the  
government to prosecute Huang if it ever uncovered evidence of 
espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, a former Democratic National Committee fund-raiser, has  
pleaded guilty in the probe of campaign finance abuses in the 1996 
presidential election. Huang in August admitted he had conspired to 
violate campaign finance laws and was sentenced to one year of 
probation and a $10,000 fine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
