<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Family Argues Over Finances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The ``scandalous behavior'' of some IOC  
members has ``tarnished the rings'' of the Olympic movement and 
made fund raising more difficult, according to an internal U.S. 
Olympic Committee memo inadvertently released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other confidential memorandums show the Salt Lake Organizing  
Committee arguing over money with the USOC and scrambling to meet 
new and tougher conditions imposed by its bank because of the 
vote-buying scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC President Mitt Romney called the accidental release of the  
memos embarrassing to the USOC and possibly to some Olympic 
sponsors. The letters were disclosed Friday as the USOC prepared 
for a weekend board meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents reveal squabbling in the Olympic family over the  
untangling of octopus-like financial relationships to satisfy a 
Bank of America demand to be repaid first out of Olympic 
sponsorship dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank is financing Salt Lake City's 2002 Winter Games with a  
$130 million line of credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said the memos reflect ``tough, hard'' negotiations  
hidden ``beneath the candy-coated shell'' of the Olympic movement. 
</P>
<P>
	In one memo, USOC lawyer Donis G. Walker attacked the  
unwillingness of the International Olympic Committee to admit fund 
raising was damaged by a scandal implicating one-fifth of its 
103-member body. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker blamed ``the scandalous behavior of some of their board  
members, which has tarnished the rings and made financing the games 
through corporate sponsorships more challenging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He sent the letter to Salt Lake Olympic officials in August.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were surprised by the harsh tone of your introductory  
comments regarding the IOC,'' responded Kelly Flint, senior vice 
president for marketing and legal affairs for the Salt Lake 
committee. ``We are unsure why you addressed them to us. If you 
wish, we can forward your letter to the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC asked for and received promises of ``priority'' access  
to hotel rooms, tickets, transportation and parking for the Salt 
Lake Olympics in exchange for granting the SLOC financial 
concessions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Salt Lake officials flatly turned down the USOC on other  
demands, including veto power over the budget and senior management 
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is not something which found itself into the final  
agreement,'' Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also at issue was Salt Lake's refusal to contribute to a USOC  
image-building campaign by giving it $1 million worth of 
advertising the SLOC had with Time and Sports Illustrated 
magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	And Salt Lake maneuvered to avoid paying lucrative commissions  
to a company hired to salvage fund raising for the Utah Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC finally relented, Romney said, in exchange for more  
than $5.5 million worth of corporate goods and services from USOC 
sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	Those value-in-kind donations were set to expire before the USOC  
could use them. The deal includes goods and services from Xerox, 
Panasonic, General Mills, McDonald's and Time-Warner. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporate benefits should match what the SLOC expects to pay  
in commissions to International Management Group, the outside 
fund-raiser, so the deal ``ends up not costing us anything,'' 
Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC, he said, is wrapping up concessions from the U.S. and  
international Olympic committees that will be worth tens of 
millions of dollars for the Salt Lake City Games. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
