<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 06:00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Can Gophers Finally Beat Buckeyes? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Maybe they're so accustomed to disparaging  
comments that the University of Minnesota football team doesn't 
know a compliment when it hears one. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24th-ranked Gophers are slight favorites over No. 22 Ohio  
State on Saturday, and Buckeyes coach John Cooper calls strong 
safety Tyrone Carter the Big Ten's best. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Gophers (5-1, 2-1 Big Ten) are looking for revenge,  
not respect. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the Buckeyes (4-3, 1-2) routed Minnesota 45-15 in  
Columbus and afterwards didn't even bother to shake hands with the 
Gophers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was disrespectful,'' Gophers running back Thomas Hamner  
said. ``It's something we held in the back of our heads. We aren't 
holding a grudge, but we demand respect and sometimes you've got to 
take it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carter hasn't forgotten the snub, either.  
</P>
<P>
	``They think we're a pushover,'' Carter said. ``They've been  
killing us over the years and we just got to go out there and take 
the game away from them and let them know we are for real this 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper has the utmost respect for Carter.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I've seen a better defensive player in our  
league in a long, long time,'' Cooper said. ``He's just an 
outstanding football player. I've never seen as many tackles as he 
makes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Gophers, who haven't beaten the Buckeyes since 1981,  
returned to the rankings after a 37-7 whipping at Illinois left 
them just one victory shy of their first winning season since 1990. 
A win Saturday and they'd be eligible for their first bowl berth 
since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gophers haven't been 6-1 since 1967, and the Buckeyes  
haven't been 1-3 in the Big Ten since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamner, who is from Hamilton, Ohio, rushed for a career-best 184  
yards and a touchdown at Illinois. The senior is averaging a 
conference-best 148 yards rushing. Quarterback Billy Cockerham 
threw for 95 yards and rushed for 100 more against the Illini. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckeyes quarterback Steve Bellisari also piles up yards on the  
ground, twice leading his team in rushing. But Cooper said that's 
not so much a sign of his mobility as it is an indication of Ohio 
State's struggles. 
</P>
<P>
	``When our quarterback, who we picked up because of his passing  
ability, leads us in rushing, that illustrates some of the problems 
we're having on offense,'' Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gophers coach Glen Mason, who attended and coached at Ohio  
State, sees it another way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think any time you have a mobile quarterback, which he is  
very mobile, that adds another dimension to what you can do. He's 
an awfully good athlete,'' Mason said. ``I know he pulled the ball 
down against Penn State, the best defense there is, and scrambled 
for 44 yards. I think that speaks volumes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes are looking to bounce back offensively after  
mustering just 35 yards rushing in their 23-10 loss to Penn State 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was probably the worst offensive production we've had in  
a long, long, time,'' Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gophers are on a roll just in time for the meat of their  
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to intimidated by any team in the Big Ten,''  
Minnesota center Ben Hamilton said. ``We know we can play with 
them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
