<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Weigh Panama Canal Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conservatives pressed their claim Friday that  
China is moving to gain authority over the Panama Canal. But a top 
U.S. general said environmental damage and terrorism may pose 
bigger threats to the waterway. 
</P>
<P>
	Marine Gen. Charles E. Wilhelm, chief of the Southern Command,  
told a Senate hearing there is no evidence China has designs on the 
canal through Hutchison Whampoa Ltd., a Hong Kong-based shipping 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilhelm told the Senate Armed Services Committee, however, that  
``the canal must always be regarded as a potential target'' given 
its strategic location and importance for world commerce. And he 
said that vulnerability will increase when the United States leaves 
for good Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is expected to represent  
the United States at a Dec. 14 handover ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Panama Canal is not endangered,'' Alberto Aleman Zubieta,  
the canal's Panamanian administrator, told the panel. ``Its 
operation shall not be interrupted for any reason whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee is looking into worries by conservatives including  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that China is becoming an 
increasingly menacing presence at the canal. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is Panama's 1997 award to Hutchison Whampoa of a  
long-term contract to operate terminals for container ships on the 
canal's Atlantic and Pacific entrances. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is a publicly traded multinational corporation with  
major offices in Hong Kong and Featherstone, England. Its major 
shareholder, billionaire Li Ka-shing, has ties with the Chinese 
government, according to critics of the arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	``These Chinese companies do what the government tells them,''  
said Lott, who participated in Friday's hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith, a conservative independent from New Hampshire,  
likened the presence of Hutchison Whampoa at either end of the 
canal to ``having the Chinese army in Williamsburg'' and saying it 
would have no effect on ship movements in nearby Norfolk, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Lino Gutierrez, deputy assistant secretary of state for Western  
Hemispheric affairs, told the panel ``we have found no information 
to substantiate'' allegations that Hutchison Whampoa has ties to 
Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	In any event, the company will have no control or authority over  
passage of ships through the canal, Gutierrez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilhelm said the threat of terrorism remains a major problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to figure out when they might strike, or who they  
might be,'' the Marine general testified. He said Panama needs to 
strengthen its ability to defend the canal and suggested U.S. help 
in that effort. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited ``environmental degradation'' as potentially the  
biggest threat to the canal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deforestation of the canal through clear-cutting, grazing or  
development could threaten the watershed or lead to increased 
silting, ultimately jeopardizing canal operations,'' Wilhelm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Caspar Weinberger, secretary of defense in the Reagan  
administration, told the panel the United States needs to negotiate 
with Panama precise terms under which the U.S. military might 
intervene to open the canal if it were blocked. 
</P>
<P>
	The Panama Canal treaties, ratified by the Senate in 1978, give  
the United States the right to intervene militarily should the 
canal be closed or traffic through it hindered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be catastrophic if there were any attempts to  
interfere with the operation of the canal,'' Weinberger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
