<P>
	Nasdaq After-Hour Quotes Start Monday  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq Stock Market will will extend  
operations of its stock quote ticker beginning Monday to 
accommodate after-hours traders. The ticker provides the stock 
price information that scrolls across the bottom of television 
screens and is distributed to millions of investors via the 
Internet. Yesterday, Nasdaq officials said the extension might be 
delayed for third time to allow stock brokers and dealers more time 
to upgrade computer systems to adjust to changes stemming from 
after-hours trading. Today, Nasdaq said broker-dealers who are 
unable to update their systems in time would be granted waivers 
from some regulations related to the new extended hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Waste Management Has Problems  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Waste Management Inc. acknowledged today that a  
massive audit of its dumps and garbage-collection operations found 
more accounting problems that will hurt its third-quarter and 
annual earnings. But the nation's largest trash hauler said the 
findings also will pave the way for a recovery from its 
multibillion-dollar troubles, and its shares rose modestly on Wall 
Street. Analysts were not surprised by the preliminary audit 
results or by reports that the intensive examination will lead 
Waste Management to take a $1 billion charge against earnings when 
it releases third-quarter results and audit findings on Nov. 9. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Pushes FCC on Digital TV  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is urging federal  
regulators to examine how broadcasters can pay back the public for 
getting valuable digital television channels from the government 
for free. In a letter to Federal Communications Commission Chairman 
Bill Kennard, Gore recommended that the FCC hold a public 
proceeding to consider the obligations of broadcasters in the new 
world of digital television. A presidential commission last year 
suggested that broadcasters, along with cable networks and 
satellite companies, provide five minutes of free air time per day 
in the 30 days leading up to an election. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Canada Earns $84 Billion  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Air Canada said today it earned $84 million in  
the third quarter in contrast to a loss of $41 million a year ago. 
The 1998 figures were affected by a two-week pilots' strike that 
severely hindered service. Earnings amounted to 44 cents a share, 
compared with a loss of 22 cents in the third quarter last year. 
Revenue rose to $1.22 billion in the latest quarter from $1 billion 
a year earlier. Air Canada this week offered to buy back shares in 
order to block an Onex takeover bid, helped by major investments by 
global partners Lufthansa and United Airlines. 

</P>
<P>
	Gillette Earnings Likely To Decline  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Gillette Co. may have the top-selling razor,  
but it's still is getting nicked. A report of listless 
third-quarter earnings and warnings of dim prospects in the final 
months of the year sent Gillette stock sliding today. Things may 
turn around at the diversified shaving giant, but not before it 
tackles a few serious kinks in its operations, analysts said. 
Gillette stock fell as much as 10.6 percent today but then regained 
some of the ground. Gillette shares were at 36, down 1 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Smith &AMP; Wesson Requiring Ethics  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) --The nation's largest handgun  
manufacturer is requiring dealers in its collective advertising 
program to sign a code of ethics designed to prevent the illegal 
sale of guns. More than three-quarters of Smith &AMP; Wesson's 3,500 
registered dealers in the program have signed the agreement since 
the company began mailing it in mid-July, said Paul Pluff, manager 
of retail sales. Among other things, the code requires dealers to 
obey all firearms laws, sell only Smith &AMP; Wesson guns with safety 
locks and to closely monitor buyers to avoid illegal purchases. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Wants U.S. Brokerage Punished  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese securities regulators have recommended  
punishment for Cresvale International Ltd., the subsidiary of a 
Princeton, N.J. company embroiled in charges of a $1 billion 
securities fraud. The regulators said today that Cresvale 
executives gave kickbacks to Japanese companies and provided false 
information about investments. The usual punishment in such cases 
is to shut down the offending company. Cresvale marketed 
interest-bearing promissory notes to about 100 Japanese companies, 
which the company now cannot repay. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stock Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European share prices rose sharply today, lifted  
by technology and oil stocks. The U.S. equity market's morning rise 
supported European gains. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 614 European 
companies rose 5.72 points, or 1.9 percent, to close at 306.75. The 
technology index, the best performer, rose 5.1 percent, followed by 
energy, which rose 3.3 percent. markets have been pretty resilient 
this week,'' said Joe Hall, head of marketing for European equities 
at Deutsche Bank. ``Everybody knows there's going to be a U.S. rate 
increase, and that is being discounted in the market. People are 
expecting a European increase as well, ...he said. The Dow Jones 
Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 310 companies in countries that 
joined the single currency closed up 6.12 points at 323.32. 
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index rose 2.1 percent, Amsterdam's AEX index 
rose 2.2 percent. 

</P>
