<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith &AMP; Wesson Requiring Ethics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- The nation's largest handgun  
manufacturer is requiring its dealers to sign an agreement that 
they will abide by a code of ethics aimed at preventing the illegal 
flow of guns to criminals and youths. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Pluff, manager of retail sales for Smith &AMP; Wesson, said  
more than three-quarters of its 3,500 registered dealers have 
signed the agreement since it was mailed in mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the code requires dealers to obey all  
firearms laws; to only sell Smith &AMP; Wesson guns with safety locks; 
and to closely monitor buyers to avoid illegal purchases, the 
Washington Post reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Springfield-based company also warned that it will stop  
doing business with any dealers that run afoul of the law or have 
failed to sign the agreement within the next 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has been raised in several of the lawsuits that have  
been filed by various cities against the gun industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith &AMP; Wesson officials began meeting privately this fall with  
officials in some of the cities that have gone to court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
