<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan's Advice Comes Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Buchanan is getting some advice that  
sounds remarkably similar to some he gave President Nixon back in 
1971: Don't let the conservatives bolt from the Republican Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, then a White House speechwriter, warned Nixon that  
unless he placated disgruntled conservatives, they would leave and 
weaken the party's chances of holding onto the presidency in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Far Right of our party goes charging off in New  
Hampshire, and is humiliated and routed, a good many people will be 
embittered,'' Buchanan wrote in a memo filed among Nixon papers at 
the National Archives. ``Wounds will have been opened within the 
party which may not have healed in time for November when we need 
everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have the same concern about Buchanan. They worry  
that his bolt to the Reform Party, expected Monday, will fracture 
the GOP and undermine its chances of winning the presidency in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-eight years ago, Buchanan was warning Nixon about John  
Ashbrook, a conservative congressman from Ohio who challenged the 
president in the primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Ashbrook used the occasion for a `let's get aboard speech'  
instead of an announced candidacy, it would truly help us in 
resolving our difficulties with the Right -- and unite the party for 
an election where we are going to have to be united,'' Buchanan 
wrote Dec. 13, 1971, in a memo to Attorney General John Mitchell 
and Nixon's chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buchanan campaign was given copies of several of the memos  
Buchanan wrote about conservatives in the 1970s, but did not return 
repeated telephone calls for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo to Nixon, dated Jan. 6, 1971, Buchanan reported that  
the Republican Party's right wing thought the president's domestic 
policies were too liberal. They complained that the White House had 
no conservative policy-maker. They grumbled that his administration 
had failed to respond adequately to a Soviet arms buildup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a serious political problem developing on the right,''  
Buchanan wrote in a seven-page, single-spaced letter he titled 
``Trouble on the Right.'' ``One of the constant complaints heard is 
that Richard Nixon 'takes the conservatives for granted; he doesn't 
think we have anywhere else to go.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's perceived threat from the right never amounted to  
much in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashbrook and anti-war Rep. Pete McCloskey of California did  
challenge the president in the New Hampshire primaries, but the 
president trounced them and went on to beat Democrat George 
McGovern in the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Is Buchanan's own threat to the Republican Party more daunting?  
He won the New Hampshire primary in 1996 and put a scare into 
then-President Bush in the 1992 primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Bond, former Republican national chairman, said Buchanan is  
right in how he assessed conservatives' discontent with the GOP 
then and now. But he's wrong about the effect, Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he's wrong about again is the consequence of his own  
break-off,'' Bond said. ``He won't be credible enough to stop the 
Republican nominee from winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner for 2000,  
says he wants Buchanan to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to whip him in the primary,'' Bush said. ``I'd like  
to have his ideas out there in Iowa, New Hampshire and South 
Carolina and see whether or not Republicans embrace or don't 
embrace what he stands for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But while campaigning recently in California, Bush said: ``The  
question is: Will some of the people who supported Pat Buchanan, 
who are loyal Republicans, stay with the Republican nominee?'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was Buchanan's concern for Nixon in 1972. ``Right now, we  
could win without these conservatives and their train; but right 
now is not October of 1972,'' Buchanan wrote to Haldeman and 
Mitchell on Dec. 3, 1971. ``A National Conservative Party in the 
general election could be a problem.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
