<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan To Up Investment in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Japanese automaker Nissan Motor Co. will invest an  
additional $332 million at its factory in Sunderland to produce a 
new version of its Primera car. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan's commitment of funds to the plant in northern England  
followed its announcement earlier this week that it would slash 
21,000 jobs worldwide and close three plants in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunderland plant is considered the most productive car  
factory in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sunderland workforce is a winning team. Their commitment  
to quality and determination to be the best in the industry has won 
this investment,'' said John Cushnaghan, managing director of 
Nissan Motor Manufacturing (UK). 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan confirmed Thursday that the next generation of Primera  
would be built at the plant, which employs 5,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade and Industry Secretary Stephen Byers called Nissan's  
decision ``a vote of confidence in the workforce and in the U.K. as 
a place for manufacturing and investment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan has received $8.3 million in government money to help  
finance the project, Byers said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
