<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush-Bashing Biographer Had Secret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The unauthorized biographer of GOP presidential  
front-runner George W. Bush was hoping for a best seller. He may 
end up with a libel lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	His publisher already has recalled the book and suspended  
further sales, shipment and promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	James Howard Hatfield, who accused the Texas governor of burying  
a cocaine arrest, allegedly hid a secret of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Friday that Hatfield was convicted in 1988 for  
plotting to murder a co-worker. And they tell of a second 
conviction in an embezzlement scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	By Friday afternoon, publisher St. Martin's Press had recalled  
all 70,000 copies of the book -- ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and 
the Making of an American President'' -- from stores nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The revelation, first reported in The Dallas Morning News, had  
the Bush campaign's legal staff reviewing the work for possible 
libel implications. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious (the book) was not checked,'' Bush spokeswoman  
Karen Hughes said Friday. Bush had previously denounced the book as 
``science fiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have enough information from our own investigation to make  
the decision that the book must be pulled,'' said Sally Richardson, 
president and publisher of St. Martin's Press trades division. 
</P>
<P>
	``We strongly believe it would be irresponsible to continue to  
keep the book in the marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield was still on parole from a 15-year prison term while  
writing the book, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	He alleged that Bush was arrested in 1972 for cocaine  
possession, but only did community service after his father, former 
President Bush, intervened. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest record was later expunged at the request of the elder  
Bush, the book alleged. Hatfield attributed the story to three 
anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to reach Hatfield through St. Martin's Press were  
unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, due out in January 2000, was released early after the  
manuscript arrived with the cocaine story. 
</P>
<P>
	Although some merchants, such as online bookseller Amazon.com,  
said they would no longer sell the book, the flap wasn't enough to 
dissuade other merchants like Barnes &AMP; Noble, which said it will 
continue peddling the biography. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield, 41, maintains it's a case of mistaken identity.  
</P>
<P>
	But Eddie Cobb, the Arkansas parole officer overseeing the  
convict's parole, said the writer and former prisoner are one and 
the same, according to published reports. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dallas attorney also identified the author as the convicted  
criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyer Norman L. ``Happy'' Nelson Jr., who knew Hatfield for  
about nine years before the 1988 conviction, was stunned to see 
Hatfield's picture in a local newspaper as the Bush biographer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The picture in the paper ... that was him,'' Nelson said. ``I  
quite frankly didn't like him denying that he had a record, when I 
knew he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glen Castlebury, spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal  
Justice, confirmed that a James Howard Hatfield was arrested in 
February 1987 for solicitation of capital murder -- hiring a hit man 
to plant a bomb beneath a co-worker's car. 
</P>
<P>
	After he was found guilty, Hatfield went to prison in April 1988  
and spent the next five years there. Upon his release, Hatfield was 
turned over to federal authorities; he wound up doing a short 
stretch in El Reno, Okla., for embezzling nearly $35,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield was released in December 1994 after doing time in a  
halfway house, said El Reno spokesman Leon Crawford. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield then moved to Arkansas with the approval of Texas  
authorities and remained on parole through April 15, 2003, said 
Castlebury. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 05:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
