<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Houston's Barkley To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Rockets forward Charles Barkley said  
Friday he will announce his retirement Sunday, effective at 
season's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The 36-year-old Barkley has threatened several times in recent  
years to retire, but the 6-foot-6 forward insisted this time he 
means it. He said he will make the announcement at halftime of 
Sunday's exhibition game between the Rockets and Detroit Pistons at 
Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Birmingham is less than a half-hour's drive from his hometown of  
Leeds, Ala., so his family will be on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be Barkley's 16th NBA season.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just time,'' said Barkley, who has been upgraded to  
questionable for Sunday's game after missing the last four 
preseason games with tendinitis in his right elbow. ``It's time. 
That's it. I'm not going to answer any more questions about it. 
It's just time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I'm going to do (after he retires). I might  
just take some time off. But I'm making it official Sunday. I'm 
announcing it there (in Birmingham) because that's my hometown, and 
I'll have a lot of family and friends there. This is my last year, 
period. I don't care how well I'm playing -- this is it. I want to 
get it over with, and that's it. I'm looking forward to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barkley has long been one of the league's top draws, especially  
internationally. He was on the original Dream Team, playing with 
Michael Jordan, Larry Bird and Magic Johnson on the juggernaut that 
won the gold medal at the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Barkley, then with the Phoenix Suns, teamed with  
current Rockets teammate Hakeem Olajuwon on the U.S. team that won 
a gold medal in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Charles has decided that this is his last season, then we  
should all relish one more chance to be entertained by one of the 
most spectacular players in NBA history,'' NBA deputy commissioner 
Russ Granik told the Houston Chronicle. ``Charles is certainly a 
one-of-a-kind personality, but first and foremost, he is a truly 
great talent on the court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rockets owner Leslie Alexander agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's one of the greatest who ever played the game,''  
Alexander said. ``He is a great player, but he also made the game 
fun. People love to be around Charles, and an attitude like that is 
rare in any sport. His routine will be missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barkley averaged less than 10 rebounds only once, when he  
averaged 8.6 as a rookie with the Philadelphia 76ers in 1984-85. 
Entering this season, Barkley has scored 23,468 points (13th on the 
career list) and pulled down 12,337 rebounds, once leading the 
league (14.6 in 1986-87) and hauling in a career-high 33 in his 
first game as a Rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the NBA's second leading rebounder last season with 12.3  
per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, who said he is not surprised by the decision, is  
happy to have Barkley play his last game as a Rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	``Definitely,'' Alexander said. ``It's nice to have a great one  
retire in your uniform. And he's one of the greatest of all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 03:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Repair Companies Settle Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than a dozen ``credit repair'' companies  
and individuals who promised consumers new credit histories and 
phantom Social Security numbers over the Internet must provide full 
refunds as part of a government settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission announced Thursday that sixteen  
firms had agreed to settle federal charges that they sold 
instructions for creating phantom Social Security numbers and using 
``them illegally to build new credit profiles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The firms had been targeted in a FTC crackdown on sales of false  
credit identities called ``Operation New ID-Bad Idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to get the word out to consumers to watch out for  
this sort of thing,'' said Steven Baker, director of the FTC's 
Midwest office and the operation's organizer. ``There isn't any way 
to repair your credit short of paying off your bills and developing 
a good credit history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In settling the cases, the companies did not admit to any crime,  
officials said. Baker refused to say if any criminal investigations 
were still underway. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen of the firms will fully refund their fees, but three  
others said they couldn't afford to repay customers. Cases against 
seven other firms are still ongoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit repair scams are among the top twenty complaints received  
by the FTC, Baker said and ``a lot of these companies do business 
over the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These types of operations lure consumers who have been denied  
loans or credit cards because of poor credit histories, sometimes 
sending letters to people who have filed for bankruptcy. For 
anywhere from $29.95 to $400, the companies promise to instruct 
customers on how to develop a new credit identity through a process 
called ``file segregation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies then sell consumers instructions on how to apply  
to the Internal Revenue Service for an employer or taxpayer 
identification number. Businesses use these numbers to set up a tax 
account for their filing purposes and they shouldn't be used in 
place of a Social Security number. 
</P>
<P>
	But the scam operations tell consumers to do exactly that--using  
the numbers instead of their Social Security number in credit 
reports or loan applications, enabling them to start a fresh, new 
credit record. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem here is not just the money that people spent, but  
the risk that consumers actually followed this advice, got a new 
credit identity and got loans they were not able to repay or they 
filed financial statements and are subject to criminal 
prosecution,'' Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also the risk that someone else's real Social Security  
number could be used, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of turning to illegal methods, consumers should ``sit  
down with a counseling service and review their options,'' said 
Judith Stevens, an education specialist with the Consumer Credit 
Counseling Service, a national nonprofit organization that helps 
consumers manage their debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens advises consumers to get their credit report every year  
and to dispute any inaccuracies, which can often be fixed for free. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit repair firms involved in the settlement varied widely  
in size from less than $100 of business and some more than 
$100,000, said FTC Spokeswoman Claudia Farrell. 
</P>
<P>
	Both she and Baker said they couldn't reveal the number of  
victims involved or the total amount of money the firms had taken 
from consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to repaying the money, the firms must notify their  
customers that using false identification numbers to apply for 
credit is illegal. The settlement also bars the companies from any 
new misleading advertising and from selling their customer lists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
