<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was broadly higher in European  
trading today, rising against the euro and some other major 
currencies but falling against the yen. Gold prices fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0672 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0804 Thursday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0681. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 105.82 Japanese yen, down from 105.98; 1.4977 Swiss 
francs, up from 1.4726; 1.4762 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4854. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6574, down from $1.6756.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 105.77 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6568. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8328 German marks, up from 1.8103; 
6.1465 French francs, up from 6.0726; 2.0650 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0393; 1,814.18 Italian lire, up from 1,791.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $301.60 per troy ounce, up from $302.70  
on Thursday. In Zurich the bid price was $301.00, down from 
$302.90. Gold fell $3.25 in Hong Kong to $303.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.27 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.17. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
