<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Aviation Deaths Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deaths in U.S. military aviation accidents  
fell this year to 43 from 77 the year before, and the Pentagon's 
overall air safety record improved slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	In its annual report on military safety, the Pentagon said  
Thursday that in a year in which hundreds of U.S. aircraft 
participated in the 78-day air campaign over Kosovo, it recorded 
1.58 major aviation accidents for every 100,000 hours of flying 
time. That compares with a rate of 1.64 the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident count covered the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30.  
</P>
<P>
	The military overall recorded 108 on-duty accidental deaths and  
319 off-duty deaths. The accidental death rate was 30 per 100,000 
military members, the same as the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	In other safety categories for the period:  
</P>
<P>
	-- The military lost 55 airplanes in accidents, down from 60 the  
year before. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Privately owned motor vehicle accidents were the leading  
killer for the military, accounting for 280 deaths. The year before 
there were 249 such deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The military recorded $3.3 billion in property losses, about  
$1.9 billion of which was from damage to three satellites. Aviation 
accidents accounted for $1.23 billion of the total property losses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
