<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Seeking Genocide Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *BY PAULINE JELINEK   	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the Rwandan genocide tribunal nears its  
fifth anniversary with little progress, Rwanda is urging the 
world's governments to hand over suspects hiding in their 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Washington press conference, Rwanda's ambassador to the  
United Nations, Joseph Mutaboba, said about 1,000 people believed 
to have helped plan the 1994 massacre of at least 500,000 Rwandans, 
mostly ethnic Tutsis, are still at large. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 20,000 more fugitives include militia, former  
soldiers and others who participated in the widespread killing. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the European countries there are many,'' said Mutaboba.  
``And we have some here as well,'' he said. ``In Washington, even, 
there are some, in New York there are some. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's every single country in the world that should look around  
and sweep the streets of its own cities to find them. They are 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mutaboba noted that Cameroon has detained and sent back nine  
suspects, Kenya 11, and Togo, Benin and others have ``done as much 
as they could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Many more are still at large, and the international community  
(should) live up to its responsibility,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutaboba said the Nov. 8, 1994, United Nations resolution  
setting up the tribunal binds all U.N. member nations to identify, 
arrest, detain and hand over suspects living within their borders. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight of militia and other suspects to neighboring  
countries such as Congo and Burundi, and Rwanda's campaigns to 
flush them out, has contributed to a war in Congo and greatly 
destabilized much of the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``The same way we are worried about those who are across the  
borders, we are worried about those who are hiding, who are living 
the high life here -- and there are many,'' Mutaboba said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no difference as far as we are concerned between the  
one who lives in Burundi, the one who lives in Congo and the one 
who lives in France. They are all the same criminals,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutaboba noted the tribunal set up in Arusha, Tanzania, has been  
plagued by mismanagement, but he said it has been improved since 
the problems were exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal has spent $209 million in disposing of only five  
cases. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
