<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama's Alexander Faces Vols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Despite Shaun Alexander's Heisman aspirations, Tennessee doesn't  
plan to try anything special to slow him down. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to do anything different for Shaun  
Alexander,'' Volunteers linebacker Raynoch Thompson said. ``We'll 
just get after him like we have everybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, neither team is expected to do anything unusual. No.  
10 Alabama (5-1, 4-0 Southeastern Conference) will try to run. No. 
5 Tennessee (4-1, 2-1 SEC) will rely on its defense to try and stop 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do what we've done the last five years and see  
how it unfolds,'' Tennessee defensive coordinator John Chavis said. 
``We've got a good defensive front. We're proud of our defensive 
front. It's a week they'll have to play at their best. We're 
expecting them to win some battles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And no doubt lose a few. The Crimson Tide has run the ball  
successfully against every team they've played. 
</P>
<P>
	In this, the 56th straight year the teams have played -- and the  
first time since 1930 the game is being played in Tuscaloosa 
instead of Birmingham's Legion Field. -- Alabama is promoting 
Alexander for the Heisman Trophy. The tailback has a chance to make 
the case himself Saturday against the Vols, who have one of the top 
rushing defenses in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama's offensive line, led by tackle Chris Samuels, has  
cleared the way to the top of the SEC rushing lead at 191 yards per 
game. Alexander is averaging 155 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samuels is probably the best offensive lineman in the  
country,'' Chavis said. ``He's strong, he's physical and he's 
nasty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander ran for 214 yards and three touchdowns last week  
against a Mississippi defense that went into the game giving up an 
average of 45 yards rushing. He's had at least 100 yards in every 
game this year, including 106 against a Florida defense that 
limited Tennessee's rushers to 95 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I describe him as a skater,'' Chavis said. ``He can make quick  
cuts because his feet are always close to the ground. If there's a 
crease, he can accelerate through it. When you see a guy who's in 
the top three or four for the Heisman, he has to be talented and 
getting the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's defense is third in the nation against the run,  
giving up 64.4 yards per game. Wyoming managed 8 yards rushing, 
Florida 123, Memphis 62, Auburn 75 and Georgia 54. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest challenge we've seen this year,'' said  
Tennessee defensive end Will Overstreet, who will be opposite 
Samuels much of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games Saturday, No. 1 Florida State will be at Clemson,  
No. 2 Penn State at No. 16 Purdue, No. 3 Nebraska at No. 18 Texas, 
No. 7 Kansas State at Oklahoma State, Illinois at No. 9 Michigan, 
No. 11 Michigan State at No. 17 Wisconsin, LSU at No. 12 
Mississippi State, No. 13 Texas A&AMP;M at Oklahoma, Kentucky at No. 14 
Georgia, No. 15 Marshall at Buffalo, No. 19 BYU at UNLV, Tulane at 
No. 20 East Carolina, Cincinnati at No. 21 Southern Mississippi, 
No. 22 Ohio State at No. 24 Minnesota, and No. 23 Miami at Boston 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 4 Virginia Tech, No. 6 Florida, No. 8 Georgia Tech and No.  
25 Mississippi are idle. 
</P>
<P>
	The game between Florida State (7-0) and Clemson (3-3) is  
intriguing because Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden will be going for 
career win No. 300, against his son, Clemson coach Tommy. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy says the pressure will be on the Seminoles.  
</P>
<P>
	``If they lose, they lose a national championship,'' he said.  
``If we lose, we're 3-4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State's Peter Warrick, suspended the past two games  
because of legal problems, probably won't play Saturday because his 
court case has been postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State (7-0) will have to contend with Drew Brees of Purdue  
(5-2), who passed for more than 500 yards in last week's upset of 
previously unbeaten Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
	Brees was 39-of-58 for 361 yards against Penn State last year,  
but the Nittany Lions won 31-13, with the help of six sacks and an 
interception. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska (6-0) has a few scores to settle with Texas (5-2).  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Texas ended Nebraska's 47-game home winning streak  
with a 20-16 upset as Major Applewhite threw for 269 yards and two 
TDs and Ricky Williams ran for 150 yards. And in '96, the Longhorns 
upset the Cornhuskers 37-27 in the first Big 12 title game, denying 
Nebraska a chance for a third straight national title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
