<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 09:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Major Daumier Retrospective Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Biting political satires and gripping portrayals of  
human suffering that once sent Honore Daumier to jail have gone on 
display at the Grand Palais in a major retrospective of works by 
the 19th-century artist. 
</P>
<P>
	With more than 300 lithographs, paintings and sculptures, the  
show is the most comprehensive overview of Daumier's work since 
1878, a year before he died. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-sponsored by Canada's National Museum of Fine Arts in Ottawa,  
the show runs in Paris through Jan. 3. It then travels to the 
Philipps Collection in Washington, D.C., also a co-organizer along 
with the French National Museum Authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Daumier is best-known as a political satirist with the fine,  
steady hand of a draftsman. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a keen and unrelenting observer of the times whose  
satirical lithographs captured the political climate of corruption 
and social injustice of France in the 1800s. 
</P>
<P>
	Daumier's portraits and mini-sculptures of doctors, lawyers and  
judges, peasants, thieves and actors run the gamut of the human 
condition: ambition, desperation, hypocrisy and arrogance. 
</P>
<P>
	Daumier was inspired by the events of the day and remained an  
anti-royalist and ardent defender of human rights until his death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rue Transnonain'' depicts the midnight massacre by royalist  
troops of an innocent family in their bedroom, bodies slumped 
across the bloodied floor. The father lays on top of his dead 
child, the mother is a crumpled heap nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Orsay Museum director Henri Loyrette says visitors don't have to  
be steeped in French history to appreciate Daumier. 
</P>
<P>
	``Daumier's style is so powerful, the rendition of the events is  
so strong that they become universal,'' he said in an interview. 
``Look at Rue Transnonain! What a tragedy! It could be Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Daumier's audacious drawings got him into trouble. In  
1831, he received a six-month jail term for ``Gargantua,'' a 
portrayal of the French king as Rabelais' fictional, gluttonous 
giant. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence was first suspended, but another provocative  
caricature a few months later caught the attention of authorities 
who imprisoned the artist for ``inciting hatred and disrespect of 
government authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daumier's talent went beyond the hooked noses, double chins and  
exaggerated gestures of his many caricatures, and critics widely 
regard him as a forerunner of Impressionism. 
</P>
<P>
	In his final years, paintings such as ``Third Class Railway  
Carriage,'' ``The Drowning'' and his Don Quixote series feature the 
thickly applied paint, the bold brushstrokes, the denial of 
pictorial accuracy and use of light that would later mature in the 
works of Monet and Renoir. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 09:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
