<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stoneman Frontrunner for Angels GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Bill Stoneman, an executive with the  
Montreal Expos since 1983, appears to be the front-runner to become 
general manager of the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported Stoneman was to have met again  
with Disney officials Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoneman, a 55-year-old former major league pitcher who threw  
two no-hitters, had two previous interviews, as did former New York 
Yankees GM Bob Watson, team spokesman Tim Mead said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who interviewed were New York Mets assistant GM Omar  
Minaya and Houston Astros assistant GM Tim Purpura. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing definitive at this point regarding the  
announcement of our next general manager,'' Mead said Thursday. 
``The interview process will continue today. I'm not at liberty to 
discuss names.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Bavasi resigned as general manager of the Angels three  
weeks ago -- two days before the team finished a 70-92 season and in 
last place in the AL West. Bavasi held the job for nearly six 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels hope to hire a GM before the World Series begins  
Saturday. Baseball mandates that no major announcements be made 
during the Series so they will not detract from the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times, quoting an unidentified source, said Stoneman hadn't  
been offered the job before Thursday, but a multiyear contract 
offer was imminent and an announcement could be made today. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoneman has most recently served as Montreal's vice  
president-baseball operations. Before that, he worked primarily as 
the Expos' chief financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoneman pitched in the majors for eight years with a 54-85  
record and 4.08 ERA. He pitched with the Chicago Cubs for two years 
and the Expos for five before completing his career with the Angels 
in 1974. His no-hitters came with the Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	The first priority for the new general manager would be to hire  
a manager. Terry Collins resigned Sept. 3 and was replaced by bench 
coach Joe Maddon on an interim basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Baylor, hitting instructor of the NL champion Atlanta  
Braves, is believed to be a leading contender for the manager's 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, who played for the Angels from 1977-82 and won AL MVP in  
1979, managed the Colorado Rockies from 1993-98. He was NL manager 
of the year in 1995, leading his team to postseason play in its 
third year. He was fired one day after the 1998 season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
