<HEADLINE> Nasdaq After-Hour Quotes Start Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq Stock Market plans to stick to its  
schedule and will extend operations of its stock quote ticker 
beginning Monday to accommodate after-hours traders, it was 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The ticker provides the stock price information that scrolls  
across the bottom of television screens and is distributed to 
millions of investors via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Nasdaq officials said the extension might be  
delayed for third time to allow stock brokers and dealers more time 
to upgrade computer systems to adjust to changes stemming from 
after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Nasdaq said broker-dealers who are unable to update their  
systems in time would be granted waivers from some regulations 
related to the new extended hours. ``Recognizing the legitimate 
technological constraints of these market participants, a brief 
deferral of trade-reporting requirements between the hours of 5:15 
p.m. and 6:30 p.m. has been sought and obtained from the Securities 
and Exchange Commission,'' Nasdaq said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Confusion arose late Thursday when a news release posted on  
Nasdaq's Web site announced there would be a delay until Nov. 15 to 
allow broker-dealers more time. However, Nasdaq spokesman Scott 
Peterson said the statement was prematurely released and that a 
decision had yet to be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq initially planned to extend its ticker hours on Oct. 4,  
but that was delayed until Oct. 11, while the plan awaited approval 
from the SEC. After the SEC gave the go-ahead, Nasdaq pushed back 
the date until Oct. 25 to give brokers and security dealers time 
for computer system upgrades. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq plans to keep its system open until 6:30 p.m. Eastern  
time from 5:15 p.m. Late quotes also are planned for the system 
that reports trades on shares listed on the New York Stock 
Exchange. Both systems currently stop distributing quotes at 5:15 
p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	An increase in after-hours trading sessions scattered across a  
number of different markets -- primarily on electronic 
communications systems, or ECNs -- has prompted calls for the 
extension of hours of centralized stock information systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq last month offered to extend the hours of its ticker to  
address that need. A week later, the organization that runs the 
NYSE's ticker also agreed to extend its ticker hours because the 
Chicago Stock Exchange, which trades NYSE listed stocks for 
regional customers, will soon keep its market open until 6:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE and Nasdaq are also planning extended sessions, but not  
until next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T, British Telecom Venture OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators gave final clearance Friday  
to a global joint venture between AT&AMP;T and British 
Telecommunications PLC, a deal that would combine the two 
companies' international operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The combine would deal mostly with voice and data service,  
mainly for large commercial users. The venture originally was 
valued at $10 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission found the application for  
the alliance to be in the public interest but imposed some limited 
conditions on the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC approval is the final step in the regulatory process. The  
companies expect to launch the global venture, called Concert, in 
about a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased the regulatory agencies both in Europe and the  
U.S. agree that our global joint venture will benefit customers as 
well as the competitive telecommunications marketplace,'' said 
David Dorman, the venture's chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC conditioned its approval on the companies compliance  
with an agreement reached among them, the Defense Department, the 
Justice Department and the Federal Bureau of Investigation. The 
accord had to do with potential national security and law 
enforcement problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement requires that domestic telecommunications  
facilities owned by the companies will be controlled by their 
subsidies and located within the United States. This will ensure 
that U.S. law enforcement authorities have both the jurisdiction 
and the technical ability to conduct electronic surveillance. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies agreed to take reasonable measures to prevent  
improper use of domestic telecommunications facilities and to adopt 
and maintain policies to ensure electronic surveillance orders and 
other legal authorizations are kept confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the companies will require security clearances for people  
with access to sensitive network facilities and to keep access from 
unauthorized people. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the FCC's other conditions, AT&AMP;T and their subsidiaries  
would be prohibited from getting exclusive operating agreements 
with British Telecom because of the joint venture. The commission 
also required that BT comply with British regulations that the 
company must give its competitors access to local customers for 
long-distance and international calls at the same level of access 
that BT has. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies will use their combined international networks to  
become a ``carrier's carrier'' for long-distance services offered 
by telephone companies operating in numerous markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies, in announcing the deal in July 1998, said the  
venture would operate in three main areas: 
</P>
<P>
	--A worldwide voice and data business offering telephone networks  
to multinational corporations and other big institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	--A global sales and service business that initially will target  
corporate clients in the financial, oil and information technology 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	--An international carrier services business that will develop  
low-cost communications links around the world for both individual 
and business customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined, AT&AMP;T and BT carry about half the calling traffic  
between the United States and Britain but own less than 20 percent 
of the network capacity. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 07:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Visa Introduced in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va. is proposing a new  
immigration visa category for foreign-born technology workers to 
make up for what he says is a shortage of Americans qualified for 
high-tech jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under legislation introduced by Robb, a foreign worker would  
need an advanced degree in mathematics, science, engineering or 
computer science and a job offer paying at least $60,000 a year to 
qualify for the visa. Recipients would be limited to recent 
graduates of U.S. master's or doctoral programs currently in the 
country on student visas. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses would have to pay $1,000 for each visa, which would  
allow a foreign worker to remain in the United States for five 
years. Extensions would cost $500 each. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be used to help pay for grants to improve  
mathematics, science and technology education in U.S. public 
schools, Robb told the Senate Judiciary Committee's immigration 
subcommittee at a hearing Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our economy has grown, the number of quality jobs has  
increased and a new and increasingly more important form of 
commerce has been born,'' he said. ``But as with any burgeoning 
industry, there are likely to be growing pains, and the most 
significant one that we see now is the shortage of skilled workers 
to fill the nearly 350,000 vacant information technology jobs in 
this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	High-tech companies have been lobbying hard for Congress to  
allow more skilled immigrants into the country for jobs they say 
can't be filled adequately by Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Congress raised the limit on ``H-1B'' visas, which  
are reserved for foreigners with specialized job skills for any 
industry, from 65,000 in fiscal 1998 to 115,000 in each of the 
following two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Those visas ``can be granted to anyone from bakers to  
occupational therapists, computer programmers to fashion models,'' 
Robb said. 
</P>
<P>
	High-tech executives say their businesses are growing so fast  
that those visas no longer are enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens when companies like mine can't hire the workers  
we need?'' asked Susan Williams DeFife, chief executive officer of 
womenCONNECT.com, an Internet site for women in business. ``We have 
to delay projects, and in the Internet industry where change occurs 
daily and competitors are springing up all around you, waiting to 
execute a project can be lethal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skeptics say the government should step up efforts to make sure  
that companies aren't simply trying to hire foreign workers at 
lower salaries than they would have to pay Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Robb said supplementing the U.S. work force with more highly  
educated foreign workers is a short-term solution. ``The long-term 
challenge is to find ways to upgrade the skills of our existing 
work force and to improve the quality of our education system so 
that the next generation of Americans has the skills needed to 
maintain our global dominance in the technology area,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bill, introduced by Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas,  
would increase the number of H-1B visas to 200,000 annually over 
the next three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
