<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 14:30:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Impressed With Gaston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cito Gaston took a casual-Friday approach to  
his interview for the Cleveland Indians' managing job, electing not 
to wear a tie with his sport coat and dress slacks. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he made sure he put on one of his two World Series  
championship rings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have them both on,'' he said. ``I think that would  
have been a little much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston, who led the Toronto Blue Jays to Series titles in 1992  
and '93, met with Indians general manager John Hart and assistant 
GM Mark Shapiro for more than three hours to discuss Cleveland's 
managerial opening. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was outstanding,'' Hart said. ``He came just as advertised.  
Cito is a guy who has a presence about him, one that demands 
respect. A quiet strength. He did a good job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston is the third candidate to interview with the Indians, who  
fired Mike Hargrove last week following their collapse against the 
Boston Red Sox in the first round of the AL playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Hart met with former Chicago Cubs manager Jim  
Riggleman and Indians hitting instructor Charlie Manuel, considered 
the frontrunner to replace Hargrove. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with Gaston, Hart left for the World Series in  
Atlanta where he plans to meet with Braves hitting instructor Don 
Baylor and New York Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss during 
the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy with our list,'' Hart told the Associated Press  
before boarding his plane. ``But that doesn't mean that it won't 
grow either. There could be some others we will eventually meet 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said he was especially looking forward to talking with  
Chambliss, who in 1971 was the AL Rookie of the Year with the 
Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy I hope blows me away is Chambliss,'' Hart said. ``He  
has not managed at the major league level yet, but from what people 
have been telling me, he has all the credentials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So does Gaston. And his two World Series rings as Toronto's  
manager give him something none of the other candidates can match. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cito knows what it takes to win,'' Hart said. ``He has brought  
a club home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Home, in Cleveland, means a World Series championship. The  
Indians haven't won it all since 1948, and Hargrove's inability to 
get his team to the ``next level'' -- as Hart put it -- cost him his 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston already has proved he can take a veteran club like the  
Indians to a title. His '93 team in Toronto, which featured Rickey 
Henderson, Devon White, Roberto Alomar and Joe Carter, was similar 
to the one in Cleveland now. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been winning here for a long time,'' Gaston said.  
``They've probably had more success than we had in Toronto except 
for winning the World Series. They're right there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said the Indians had not put a timetable on completing  
their managerial search, and that any finalists would be brought 
back for a second interview and meeting with team owner Dick 
Jacobs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
