<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Papon Captured in Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Maurice Papon, the former Vichy  
official who fled France rather than face jail for his role in 
sending Jews to Nazi death camps, has been arrested at a luxury 
hotel in a Swiss mountain resort. 
</P>
<P>
	Papon, 89, was hospitalized after apparently becoming ill soon  
after he was taken into custody Thursday night. Bernhard Kummer, 
spokesman for University Hospital, Bern, said Papon was being cared 
for in a ``special place'' at the hospital but would not give 
details on his health. 
</P>
<P>
	French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin was in contact with Swiss  
President Ruth Dreifuss to ask her to ensure Papon's quick 
repatriation, French officials said. How or when he might be 
extradited, however, was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Papon, a former high-ranking police official in France's  
pro-Nazi Vichy regime, was arrested Thursday night at the Hotel 
Roessli in Gstaad, about 60 miles south of the capital, Bern, Lars 
Widmer, the son of the hotel manager, told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father thought he wasn't very distinctive,'' Widmer said.  
``He saw Papon's picture in the paper and said to me, 'He looks 
almost like the man in room 115.''' 
</P>
<P>
	An arrest warrant for Papon had been issued Thursday in  
Bordeaux, France, after he failed to appear in court. The Court of 
Cassation, France's highest court, ruled Thursday that Papon lost 
his right of appeal by failing to report to prison as required. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement Wednesday, Papon said he had chosen exile to  
uphold his honor. 
</P>
<P>
	His flight was made possible by a controversial decision by the  
Bordeaux court at the beginning of his trial in 1997. The court 
accepted medical testimony that Papon was in poor health and freed 
him for the duration of the trial and the appeals period after he 
spent three days in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	His disappearance triggered widespread criticism of the French  
Interior Ministry for letting him slip out of the country. It was 
also an embarrassment for French officials who did not place 
judicial controls on Papon or revoke his passport. 
</P>
<P>
	French President Jacques Chirac said Papon's arrest marked ``the  
return to a respect of the law.'' Lawmakers at the National 
Assembly, the French parliament, broke into applause at the news 
that he was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Papon was convicted in April 1998 and sentenced to 10 years in  
jail for complicity in crimes against humanity for his role in 
deporting 1,590 Jews from Bordeaux. Most deportees later died at 
the Auschwitz death camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Nazi hunter Serge Klarsfeld, the head of the Association of Sons  
and Daughters of Deported Jews of France, told France Info radio 
that Papon's arrest represented ``a triumph of justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect that he will return to France very soon and will be  
incarcerated,'' Klarsfeld said. 
</P>
<P>
	Swiss officials said Thursday that Papon stayed under a false  
name at a hotel in the western Swiss town of Martigny from Oct. 11 
to 16. 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 14, authorities issued an order barring Papon from  
entering Switzerland. Police authorities say they were unaware that 
Papon was already in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Papon is the highest-ranking official of the pro-Nazi Vichy  
regime to be convicted of crimes against humanity committed during 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial opened old wounds about French collaboration with the  
Nazis, and his flight has raised questions about the nation's 
determination to confront its role in the Holocaust. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 05:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TCU's Tomlinson Is Top Rusher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- LaDainian Tomlinson doesn't play on a  
team with national championship hopes, doesn't have a computer 
mousepad with his likeness on it, doesn't have a catchy nickname 
like ``Cool Brees'' and he doesn't sport dreadlocks. 
</P>
<P>
	All the Texas Christian tailback has is numbers.  
</P>
<P>
	Tomlinson, a junior, is the nation's leading rusher at 177 yards  
per game. By reaching 1,060 yards in six games, he set a school 
record for fewest games to compile 1,000 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet ``L.T.,'' as friends and teammates call him, hasn't been  
seen as a serious contender for the Heisman Trophy or the Doak 
Walker Award for the nation's top running back, and he doesn't 
think that's right. 
</P>
<P>
	He also is annoyed by whispers that his stats have been built at  
the expense of weak teams, even though it's true that more than 
half his yards (569) came against Arkansas State and San Jose 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't look at it like that because it's all Division I-A  
football,'' he said. ``You have Tulsa playing Texas A&AMP;M, who has 
good backs, and LSU playing San Jose State. None of those backs got 
the same amount of yards. Every team in Division I-A has some 
talented scholarship players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Tomlinson continues his quest to break the school  
single-season rushing record of 1,611 yards, an interested observer 
is former Buffalo Bills star Kenneth Davis, who has held the mark 
for 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never really thought about the quality of competition as a  
factor,'' said Davis, an All-American tailback in 1984 and 
nine-year NFL veteran. ``That's really interesting to me, but I 
still don't think it should matter. With the type of stats he has 
run for and with the young man getting ready to smash my record, I 
would like to think L.T. should be considered for the Heisman. He's 
definitely a great running back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Waco University High School grad shared time in the  
backfield the last two seasons with Basil Mitchell, who made the 
Green Bay Packers as an undrafted free agent. He rushed for 1,255 
yards during that time and earned second-team All Western Athletic 
Conference honors as a sophomore. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomlinson almost lost his chance to finally carry the load when  
he and former TCU basketball star Lee Nailon were arrested on 
charges of marijuana possession and evading arrest in July. But the 
case was eventually dropped and Tomlinson was cleared of any 
wrong-doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really bothered me how everything went down,'' he said. ``I  
was just in the wrong place at the wrong time. But now I've learned 
from it and I've moved on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that episode firmly behind him, Tomlinson burst onto the  
national scene against then top 25-ranked Arizona with 170 yards 
and a touchdown in a 35-31 TCU loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that he's getting most of the carries, Tomlinson is showing  
what he can do. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of our best offensive weapons,'' TCU coach Dennis  
Franchione said. ``Whoever stands at the tailback position in this 
offense needs to produce. L.T. is certainly going to get his 
opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomlinson has learned the downside of success, too. Such as when  
Fresno State limited him to 49 yards on 20 carries three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys talked trash to me, trying to get me out of my  
game,'' he said. ``They were saying stuff like, `Where's your 
Heisman now?' So I've just had to go out and focus on my game and 
not worry about what they or anybody else is saying about me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even in one of his lesser outings this year, Tomlinson earned  
the respect of Fresno State coach Pat Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the guy has big-time ability,'' Hill said. ``You've  
really got to want to tackle this guy. He's also very good in the 
open field. He's got it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, not everything. He's lacking some sort of novelty or  
uniqueness that would help carve a national identity. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, Tomlinson has four tattoos, but that's old news these  
days. His only two piercings are in each ear. 
</P>
<P>
	How about a signature touchdown dance?  
</P>
<P>
	``You know, that's pretty funny, because a lot of people have  
asked me about that,'' Tomlinson said, laughing. ``Maybe I need to 
see if I can find some dance I can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While TCU offensive coordinator Dan Dodd will try helping  
Tomlinson get to the end zone, he doesn't want to have anything to 
do with what Tomlinson does once he gets there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trust me, there will be no dances,'' Dodd said. ``Well, maybe  
if the offensive line gets up there and shakes it with him. But it 
wouldn't be a pretty sight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 08:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nomura, Nikko Report Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Bouncing back from last year's losses, two top  
Japanese brokerages, Nomura Securities and Nikko Securities, posted 
robust first-half profits generated in part by strong gains on the 
stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura Securities Co. reported Friday a group net profit of  
54.73 billion yen, or $519 million, for the six months through 
September in contrast to a loss of 207.26 billion yen a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Nomura's group earnings were squeezed by massive  
trading losses overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Nikko Securities Co. reported earnings of 54.63  
billion yen, or $518 million, in the first half versus a loss of 
57.72 billion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Both brokerage concerns said their latest results were  
underpinned by surging trading volume on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the exchange's major  
barometer, began the fiscal year at 16,327.56 points but rose as 
high as 18,623.15 at one point during the day in July -- the highest 
intraday level since September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei has since settled back, closing Friday at 17,438.80.  
</P>
<P>
	Nikko's earnings were also helped by the joint venture it set up  
with Citigroup in March, spinning off its wholesale securities 
operations to Nikko Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint venture contribited revenue of 67 billion yen, or $635  
million, out of the group's overall revenue of 234.15 billion yen, 
or $2.2 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colts Add Jones to Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- With the availability of E.G. Green and  
Jerome Pathon still up in the air for Sunday's game with 
Cincinnati, the Indianapolis Colts made a roster move Friday to try 
and shore up their injury-depleted receiving corps. 
</P>
<P>
	The team activated former Purdue standout Isaac Jones from the  
physically unable to perform list for Sunday's home game. To make 
room for Jones, Lake Dawson was placed on injured reserve, meaning 
he will miss the remainder of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jerome didn't do anything (today) and we just kind of rested  
E.G.,'' Colts coach Jim Mora said Friday following a spirited 
indoor workout. 
</P>
<P>
	Green and Pathon are still recovering from minor knee injuries,  
and both are listed as questionable. Marvin Harrison and rookie 
Terrence Wilkins are expected to be the Colts' starting receivers 
against Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	In regards to the roster moves, Mora said something had to be  
done to help provide better depth at a key position. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just felt like we had do that with the way that the  
receiver situation was,'' Mora said. ``That means that we'll have 
to make a decision Sunday probably as to whether Jerome can play or 
not. He's the one least-ready to play. If he can't play, then Ike 
(Jones) would be playing Sunday. I don't know yet though. It could 
be that either one of them (Green and Pathon) will be out. We'll 
just have to wait and see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mora has been impressed with Jones' progress in rehabilitating  
an injured foot. He missed most of training camp as well as the 
first five games with the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Ike,'' Mora said. ``He's worked hard. He's a good-sized  
guy. He catches well, he runs good routes. He has good speed. He's 
been impressive out here for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, running back Keith Elias missed his third day of  
practice Friday with recurring headaches. Elias has been sidelined 
since incurring a mild concession in last week's game at the New 
York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	``No word yet on Keith,'' Mora said. ``We know that he's going  
to the doctor again this afternoon (Friday) and have another 
checkup. I probably won't know anything more on him until later 
today or tomorrow (Saturday).'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Elias cannot play Sunday, running back Darick Holmes is  
expected to be activated. Holmes, who signed with the Colts as a 
free agent in the spring, has been sidelined since mid-August with 
a foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Safeties Tito Wooten (hamstring) and Jason Belser (groin),  
offensive guard Waverly Jackson (ankle), and defensive end Chad 
Bratzke (ankle) are all listed as probable for Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
