<DOCNO> APW19991022.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European share prices rose sharply Friday, lifted  
by technology and oil stocks. The U.S. equity market's morning rise 
supported European gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 614 European companies rose 5.72  
points, or 1.9 percent, to close at 306.75. The technology index, 
the best performer, rose 5.1 percent, followed by energy, which 
rose 3.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson shares climbed 15 percent after the company announced  
it expects a ``strong improvement in performance'' for next year, 
with order intake up 36 percent in the third quarter and 13 percent 
in the nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finnish technology company Nokia rose 6 percent after  
reporting third-quarter results up 36 percent, with mobile phone 
sales up 58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the oil sector, BP Amoco and Shell rose with the front-month  
Brent contract rising 64 cents to $22.75 a barrel on London's 
International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Philips Electronics rose 5.1 percent, adding to Thursday's 2.5  
percent gain, which followed the company reporting a 
better-than-expected third-quarter profit. 
</P>
<P>
	In Frankfurt, shares of SAP rose 5.6 percent, recovering from  
sharp declines that followed the release of downward earnings 
adjustments two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other gainers, utility RWE continued its rise after saying  
Thursday it plans to merge with VEW to form Europe's largest 
privately held utility. RWE shares closed up 2.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The markets have been pretty resilient this week,'' said Joe  
Hall, head of marketing for European equities at Deutsche Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows there's going to be a U.S. rate increase, and  
that is being discounted in the market. People are expecting a 
European increase as well, and the markets are coming to terms with 
that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 310 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 6.12 points at 
323.32. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 86.95 points to 3778.61,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed up 99.81 points at 3749.98. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange  
100-share index rose 119.6 points, or 2 percent, to 6,058.9 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index rose 2.1 percent, the Paris CAC-40  
index rose 1.6 percent, Amsterdam's AEX index rose 2.2 percent, and 
Milan's MIBtel index rose 1.6 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
