<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Women's Soccer Team Touring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- For those who wondered where American women's  
soccer team was going following a World Cup championship that drew 
unparalleled attention to the sport, here's the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	For the next 2 1/2 months, it will go from Pittsburgh to Cleveland  
to Chicago and New York, Raleigh to Anaheim and San Jose and five 
other cities during an exhibition tour similar to those 
post-Olympic swings by figure skaters and gymnasts. 
</P>
<P>
	How about that: a sport that once was a blip on the national  
sports map is going where only Mary Lou Retton and Tara Lipinski 
went before -- into the arenas of America, with major league ticket 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Remember, this is women's soccer, not hockey or the NBA.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is important because we're getting to play in cities and  
venues where we never could have played before,'' Mia Hamm said of 
a tour that starts tonight in Pittsburgh. ``It's exciting, because 
there's still a lot of buzz about what we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tour will help the U.S. national team keep their game legs  
during what usually is a down period before an Olympic year. It 
also will keep the sport before a public that is embracing women's 
athletics like never before. 
</P>
<P>
	It also will raise the kind of cash that, before the U.S. team's  
overtime shootout victory over China in the Rose Bowl, simply was 
not associated with any women's sport but figure skating. 
</P>
<P>
	And, after the Sydney Olympics, it is possible a U.S. pro league  
might be formed in 2001 to rival the men's MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used to play before 3,000 outdoors, now it's 30,000, 40,000  
every place we play, and that's amazing,'' goaltender Briana Scurry 
said. ``It's good because now we don't have to do as much 
promotion, because people are excited about the sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So excited that the tour sponsors are asking, and getting, top  
dollar for tickets. Prices tonight in the Civic Arena range from 
$18 to $35; a nice-sized crowd is expected, though it won't be a 
sellout. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of doors have opened up for us since Pasadena,'' team  
captain Carla Overbeck said. ``It's unbelievable that so many big 
names and big corporations are behind the team, putting up 
sponsorship money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players are as curious as anyone to see how their game  
translates indoors, where women's soccer has seldom ventured 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm going to get killed,'' said Scurry, accustomed to  
playing in wide-open stadiums, not cozy arenas on an artificial 
playing field surrounded by protective glass. ``I'm going to wear 
arm pads, knee pads, all the protective padding I can get. I'll 
probably need a helmet by the end. I just hope I don't break 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most players have minimal indoor experience, derived mostly from  
two charity games played in Milwaukee for Hamm's brother, Garrett, 
who had a rare blood disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	There is nothing at stake in the games against a collection of  
international players, but Hamm suggested that might change after a 
game or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``Soccer players are competitive by nature, but I hope we're not  
out to kill each other,'' she said. ``I had enough stress this 
summer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the top names -- Hamm, Scurry, Brandi Chastain, Michelle  
Akers, Joy Fawcett, Julie Foudy, Kristine Lilly, Tiffeny Milbrett -- 
will play, though only 12 will appear in each city. Some have other 
commitments, such as Tiffany Roberts, who will juggle appearances 
with classwork at North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	That there is a tour at all remains a sense of wonderment to  
players such as Overbeck and Hamm, who spent years on the team when 
it was watched mostly by curious youngsters and soccer moms. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is important because we all want a pro league, and this  
can only help,'' Hamm said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 11:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Gets 4 Months for Killing Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- A man who shot his wife to death after  
finding her with a lover got four months in prison Friday -- about 
as much as the judge could impose after the jury recommended only 
probation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not how we wanted the case to turn out,'' prosecutor  
James Cook said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the jury found Jimmy Watkins guilty of murder  
but decided he acted with ``sudden passion'' when he discovered his 
wife, Nancy, with Keith Fontenot at the couple's home last 
December. The jury recommended 10 years' probation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Judge Robert Gill sentenced Watkins to four months in  
prison in addition to the probation. Because of the jury's 
recommendation, the most the judge could have given Watkins was six 
months behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Watkins admitted killing his wife and wounding her lover. He  
claimed temporary insanity. 
</P>
<P>
	Watkins still faces trial on attempted murder charges in the  
shooting of Fontenot. He could get life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors said they recommended probation because they didn't think  
Watkins could be rehabilitated in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel for the family, but Jimmy needs help. The prison  
system just won't give him help,'' juror Alex Davis told the Fort 
Worth Star-Telegram. 
</P>
<P>
	Another juror, James Laurie, e-mailed the newspaper, saying: ``I  
pray Jimmy will use the break that we gave him to turn his life 
back in the right direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watkins bowed his head and wept as the jury's decision was  
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure it was a very difficult decision for that jury to  
wrestle with, but we're pleased with their decision,'' defense 
attorney Kyle Whitaker said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:48:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cohen Oversees War Games in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL-OMAYED, Egypt (AP) -- Egyptian, British and Dutch troops  
jumped out of inflatable rafts Friday and charged up a 
Mediterranean beach. American warplanes screeched overhead while 
U.S., Italian and Greek troops trudged through whirling sand 
whipped up by helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	The biannual Bright Star war games brought together 11 nations  
in a show of force that has been a tradition since 1981. U.S. 
Defense Secretary William Cohen, who watched the troops storm the 
beach, said Iraq should take notice. 
</P>
<P>
	``One country that is not represented here today should pay very  
close attention to what Bright Star represents,'' Cohen told 
reporters after proclaiming the drill a success. ``(Iraqi 
President) Saddam Hussein remains an outlaw in his own 
neighborhood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a clear reference to Saddam, Cohen said the nations taking  
part in the maneuvers are ``building prosperity for their people 
and not palaces for their cronies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The amphibious assault exercises are intended to improve the  
ability of troops from the United States, Europe and the Middle 
East to work together in times of war. The maneuvers, which will 
finish Nov. 2, began 18 years ago as an U.S.-Egyptian training 
exercise and have grown to include nearly 70,000 troops, including 
18,000 Americans from all branches of the military. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, France and Germany  
have joined this year's drills, the largest coalition since the 
1991 Gulf War against Iraq . 
</P>
<P>
	At El-Omayed, 50 miles west of the port city of Alexandria,  
British hovercrafts glided ashore. Egyptian soldiers jumped out on 
the sand, raced up the beach and shouted ``Allahu Akbar!'' -- ``God 
is Great!'' -- at an invisible enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen watched the landing from stands on the beach along with  
his Egyptian counterpart, Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi, British 
Defense Minister Geoffrey Hoon and the man in charge of U.S. forces 
in the Gulf, Gen. Anthony Zinni. 
</P>
<P>
	The deputy commander of the U.S. Central Command, Lt. Gen.  
Michael Dodson, said he was pleased with the maneuvers given their 
complexity and language barriers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly gives everyone confidence,'' Dodson said. ``We  
don't all have to have the exact same equipment, but we have to 
know what each other's procedures are so that we can work 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said the United States was not only keeping an eye on Iraq  
but also on Iran. U.S.-Iranian relations have improved slightly in 
recent years, but Cohen said the United States would continue to 
watch Iran closely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will cooperate and work with all of our partners and allies  
in the region to make sure that no country would seek to undermine 
the peace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, Cohen held talks with Egyptian President Hosni  
Mubarak on the Middle East peace process and regional defense 
issues such as cooperation in the face of attacks with biological 
or chemical weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, who is touring nine Middle East countries, was expected  
to leave Egypt Saturday for Kuwait and then make stops in Oman, 
Jordan and Israel. He has already visited Bahrain, Qatar, Saudi 
Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USOC To Vote on Drug Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- Seeking to quell criticism of its  
drug-testing program, the U.S. Olympic Committee is expected to 
approve an independent agency to control everything from test 
samples to sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	The new agency would take domestic drug testing entirely out of  
the USOC's hands and remove the USOC and its governing bodies from 
the hearing process. 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC board of directors, meeting Saturday and Sunday, will  
vote on whether to approve funding of up to $24 million for four 
years for the new agency, double the amount the USOC now spends on 
drug testing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, one of the byproducts of this would be to take us  
out of the glare of the kind of criticism that we get, particularly 
from European countries, that we do our own drug testing, therefore 
we're the fox guarding the henhouse,'' USOC spokesman Mike Moran 
said. ``This group would have a board of directors and employees 
that would be chosen by itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency, which would still use IOC-accredited labs in  
Indianapolis and Los Angeles, would be responsible for the 
collection of test samples, handling, processing, transportation, 
lab results, notification, sanctions and the appeals process. 
</P>
<P>
	If the new agency is approved, a bid process will be held to  
select the company that would run the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of independence is similar to one faced by the  
International Olympic Committee, which wants to have its World 
Anti-Doping Agency operating by early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. drug adviser Barry McCaffrey, who has criticized the IOC's  
drug-testing efforts, met Wednesday in Washington with IOC vice 
president Dick Pound at a Senate Commerce Comittee hearing on drugs 
in the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the IOC's third appearance of the year on Capitol Hill.  
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch is to appear before a House 
committee in December to discuss IOC reform. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharpest criticism of the IOC at the hearing came from  
Doriane Coleman, a Duke law professor who helped set up 
out-of-competition testing in the United States in the 1980s. She 
called WADA ``a false start'' because it lacks independence and 
accountability. 
</P>
<P>
	WADA initially plans to conduct 5,000 out-of-competition tests a  
year and defer testing in some sports to existing federations. 
</P>
<P>
	``So long as testing continues to be conducted by the IOC or  
member entities ... then nothing's being done,'' Coleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound countered that since the IOC has only one-eighth  
representation on WADA's board, the IOC cannot control the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman praised the USOC's plan to remove drug testing from its  
control, but said it still wouldn't be completely independent since 
the board of the agency will be composed of USOC members or those 
selected by the USOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran defended the agency's independence. He said non-USOC  
members would be picked by ``public-sector members of the USOC who 
have no affiliation with USOC organizations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other items on the USOC board's agenda this weekend are the  
selection of the U.S. bid city for the 2007 Pan American Games -- 
either the Raleigh-Durham area in North Carolina or San Antonio -- 
and a report on restructuring the USOC. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by McKinsey and Co., which has been making a  
management review of the USOC for nearly six months, will recommend 
structural changes. Among those will be a redefinition of the 
duties of the president and executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations will require a change in the USOC  
constitution, which could not take place before the next board 
meeting in February. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:48:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cohen Oversees War Games in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
