<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pizza Hut Airs Clinton-Parody Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new Pizza Hut television commercial  
lampooning Hillary Rodham Clinton as a carpetbagger because of her 
undeclared Senate aspirations has some Democrats crying ``strike 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the board of Tricon Foods -- the parent company of Texas-based  
Pizza Hut -- is Kenneth Langone, a billionaire backer of Rudolph 
Giuliani, New York City's Republican mayor and Mrs. Clinton's 
likely rival in next year's Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani also hasn't formally entered the race, but he and Mrs.  
Clinton are raising money to run for the Senate seat being vacated 
by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Tricon's political action committee has donated $2,500 to  
Giuliani's exploratory committee while Langone and his wife each 
have given $1,000, according to Federal Election Commission 
records. Langone once was Giuliani's campaign finance chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite a set of coincidences,'' Mrs. Clinton's campaign  
spokesman Howard Wolfson said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Langone vigorously denied any impropriety.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had no idea about this ad until right now,'' he said  
Thursday. ``For anyone to imply anything different is wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats weren't convinced.  
</P>
<P>
	Jim Jordan, political director for the Democratic Senatorial  
Campaign Committee, said a tape had been delivered to his office, 
which he said implied a political agenda at work. 
</P>
<P>
	``This demands an investigation into whether this was an illegal  
contribution to the mayor's campaign,'' said Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	In the commercial -- set to debut during Saturday's World Series  
opener -- a blonde woman sporting a business suit and a heavy 
Southern accent extolls the virtues of Pizza Hut's ``Big New 
Yorker'' pizza. She eats a slice on a bunting-decked platform with 
skyscrapers behind her. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do I know so much about New York pizza?'' she drawls.  
``'Cause New York, I want to be your next senator!'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the commercial, a police officer with a New York  
City accent chimes in ``$9.99! What do they think this is, 
Arkansas?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pizza Hut spokesman Jay Allison described the commercial as  
``just tongue-in-cheek fun'' which was all part of the Big New 
Yorker pizza ad campaign that began in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've used some quintessential New Yorkers to give it New York  
flavor and authenticity,'' Allison said, noting that Donald Trump 
and Spike Lee were in earlier ads. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there were no plans for a parody of Giuliani.  
</P>
<P>
	Tricon spokesman Jonathan Blum said the commercial was ``about  
pizza not politics'' and that the board had not approved it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giuliani camp did not return a telephone call Thursday  
seeking comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
