<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Duque Takes Place of Wells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joe Torre likes to say that he could pick his  
No. 1 starter out of a hat. It just so happens the same name always 
comes out first. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando Hernandez got the nod to start Game 1 of the World  
Series against Atlanta and Torre dropped Roger Clemens to fourth, 
giving the five-time Cy Young Award winner just one possible start 
in the best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone realized with the year `El Duque' had that he earned  
the right to make the start,'' Torre said Thursday. ``Maybe it will 
be someone else next year. But they all recognize that he has 
earned it this year and he's done nothing in the first two rounds 
to make me change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All he's done is go 2-0 with a 1.17 ERA in three starts against  
Texas and Boston and was the MVP of the AL Championship Series. In 
five career playoff starts, El Duque is 4-0 with an 0.97 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	This sure wasn't the way the Yankees thought their rotation  
would turn out when they traded David Wells for Clemens at the 
beginning of spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	But after an inconsistent season and a two-inning outing for  
Clemens in the ALCS against Boston, it's the way Torre went. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care how you draw it up,'' Clemens said. ``Everybody's  
got to win a game. Obviously, I want to fare better than I did in 
Boston.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, who will pitch Saturday against Tom Glavine in  
Atlanta, will be followed by David Cone, Andy Pettitte and Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens said he wasn't disappointed about being relegated to the  
No. 4 spot and was looking forward to pitch a World Series game in 
Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's a No. 1 starter here,'' Clemens said. ``I'm happy  
for the other guys to get the opportunity. Especially El Duque. He 
hasn't really had that opportunity until this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez earned it by winning the Yankees' biggest game in the  
1998 playoffs. With New York trailing Cleveland 2-1 in the ALCS, 
Hernandez allowed three hits in seven scoreless innings to beat the 
Indians and the Yankees didn't lose again in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always had the personality of a No. 1 starter,'' Cone said.  
``From the day he got here he had a presence. He had supreme 
confidence and we have supreme confidence in him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez followed it up this season, leading New York with 17  
wins and 214 1-3 innings. Hernandez uses a high leg kick, a variety 
of arm angles, and a deep arsenal of pitches to fool the 
opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	He is extremely tough on right-handers, using a sharp slider and  
a deceptively explosive fastball to hold them to a .187 average 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hernandez hasn't had success in two starts against Atlanta.  
He is 0-1 with a 9.72 ERA against the Braves, but Torre said that 
did not factor into his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's not hitting his spots and changing speeds, they will  
get him,'' Torre said. ``But I've seen clubs beat him up and he 
comes back to beat the same team. He just needs to have command and 
the count on his side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, on the other hand, has been inconsistent all season.  
After winning back-to-back Cy Young Awards in Toronto, the Rocket 
was expected to step in and be the ace that carried the Yankees to 
the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it is the rest of the team that has often been called  
upon to carry Clemens. He went 14-10 with a career-high 4.60 ERA in 
the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a lot of individual success,'' Clemens said. ``I've  
won 20 games a lot before and ERA titles and the triple crown in 
back-to-back years. There's no doubt I'd rather be in this 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, who has publicly backed Clemens through his season-long  
struggles, finally revealed a bit of doubt when he picked Pettitte 
over Clemens to start Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``Andy has pitched well,'' Torre said. ``Almost everybody would  
be available in a seventh game. I still think left-handers have a 
bit of an edge against them because it neutralizes (Ryan) Klesko, 
and he's a big part of their offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes: Torre said Jim Leyritz, not on the roster for the ALCS, will  
be on the team for the World Series. Leyritz, whose homer in Game 4 
of the 1996 Series shifted the momentum, takes the place of Shane 
Spencer. ... The Yankees have not decided on their relievers for 
the Series. Jason Grimsley, who did not make the roster in the 
first two rounds, could be added in place of Hideki Irabu. ... Luis 
Sojo missed the workout to spend time with his ailing father. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
