<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knight Shoots Friend While Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOONER, Wis. (AP) -- Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight  
accidentally shot a friend while hunting and was cited by state 
authorities for violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said his trigger finger slipped before he was ready to  
shoot at a bird, and his friend was hit with pellets in the back 
and shoulder. The man was not seriously injured but required 
medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Natural Resources said Thursday that Knight  
will be cited for failing to report a hunting accident. He also 
will receive citations for hunting without a license in 1999 and 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Under state law, Knight was required to report the accident. The  
fine for each citation is $165. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight, Thomas Mikunda and two other men were hunting Oct. 12  
when they spotted a grouse, said Dave Zeug, law enforcement 
director for the DNR's northern region. 
</P>
<P>
	The 59-year-old coach told investigators that as he turned to  
aim at the bird, his finger slipped off the shotgun's safety. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the investigation, it was determined Knight did  
not have a $43 nonresident small game license and that he also 
hunted without one last year in Wisconsin, as did two of his 
hunting companions. The two companions will receive similar 
citations. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight told investigators he didn't think he needed the license  
to hunt on private property. 
</P>
<P>
	An unsigned statement by Indiana University said: ``This is a  
matter that is outside the scope of coach Knight's university 
duties. The university, however, recognizes that matters relating 
to coach Knight receive significant attention. ... The university 
is confident that coach Knight will respond appropriately to 
resolve this matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight did not immediately return a message from The Associated  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	DNR warden Gerald Carow, who is investigating the shooting, said  
he talked to Knight on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's feeling bad that it happened and feels deeply concerned  
over the victim and is willing to pay any penalty,'' Carow said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mikunda, an insurance agent, was not carrying a gun at the time.  
He was treated and released at Marshfield Clinic-Ladysmith Center 
in Ladysmith. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
