<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cambridge Makes Demand of AT&AMP;T </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The city of Cambridge is demanding that  
AT&AMP;T provide ``open access'' to high-speed Internet connections as 
a condition of a planned cable television franchise transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	The move would require AT&AMP;T to provide access to MediaOne's  
Roadrunner service to rival Internet service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	The city has authority to insist on the access requirement  
because it is being asked to approve the proposed transfer of the 
local cable franchise from MediaOne to AT&AMP;T. AT&AMP;T has a deal to buy 
MediaOne for $58 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Without access to RoadRunner's fast connections, America Online,  
Mindspring GTE and other competitors contend that they cannot 
compete. 
</P>
<P>
	Those companies and some consumer groups want MediaOne to be  
required to make deals allowing its competitors to resell 
RoadRunner access to their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T must respond to the demand by Wednesday, City Manager  
Robert Healy told The Boston Globe on Thursday. He said he expects 
AT&AMP;T and state regulators to oppose the city's open-access demands. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to say whether we are going to sue or take other  
action,'' Rick Jenkinson, spokesman for AT&AMP;T, told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	In federal court, the company is challenging similar demands  
made by officials in Portland, Ore., and Broward County, Fla. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
