<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Refugees Pay 'Travel Loans' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians who fled their war-torn  
homeland for the U.S. must reimburse relief agencies for their 
airfare here, according to their refugee contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The repayment of so-called ``travel loans'' has been official  
U.S. policy for all refugees since at least 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kosovo refugees told The Star-Ledger of Newark in a story  
published today they were shocked by the repayment rule and felt 
they had no choice but to sign the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are refugees. We left our country for war,'' said Ardian  
Pelaj, 22, who was studying to be a civil engineer when Serb police 
expelled him under threat of death. He now lives in a church 
rectory in Elizabeth, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees who have returned to Kosovo do not have to pay airfare  
because the U.S. government promised them free passage. 
</P>
<P>
	The recouped money is only a fraction of the organizations' cost  
of resettling the refugees, relief officials said. It amounts to 
$760 per person for those settling in New Jersey, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't have to pay it right away, and they make small  
installments over time,'' said Lauren Engel, a spokeswoman for the 
International Organization for Migration. ``It helps them build 
credit, and it's not something outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials normally explain the travel loan rules to refugees in  
their native language before they step onto the plane. Relief 
agencies acknowledged that, due to the speedy nature of the Kosovo 
effort, many ethnic Albanians may not have been told until they 
arrived at the refugee center at Fort Dix. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, refugees from around the world have repaid $50  
million in travel loans, which covered the expenses of about 85,000 
migrants. The State Department typically provides the agencies with 
the remainder of their airlift costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Norman Runkles, comptroller of the State Department's Bureau of  
Population, Refugees and Migration, said about half of all refugees 
repay the loans. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Thursday, 2,462 of the 14,129 refugees airlifted to the  
United States had returned to Kosovo, the newspaper reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
