<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Say Farewell to Market Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It was the site of Elvis Presley's farewell  
and Michael Jordan's return. Mike Tyson had his Indianapolis debut 
there, and Hulk Hogan even lost a world wrestling title. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuses, rock concerts, religious crusades and, of course, lots  
of basketball marked the 25-year history of Market Square Arena. On 
Friday night, the Indiana Pacers played their final game there, a 
97-65 exhibition victory over the Utah Jazz. They will move into 
the new Conseco Fieldhouse for the start of the 1999-00 NBA season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it was an exhibition game, we understood the  
significance of it. The guys came out and played really well,'' 
said Reggie Miller, who has played his entire career with the 
Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know how much nostalgia this place had until  
tonight,'' said Sam Perkins, a 15-year NBA veteran but starting 
only his second season with Indiana. ``I can't pick one event from 
all that's happened here, but at the end, you still feel goose 
bumps. It's a sad moment for this place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final game Friday night ended with a video of the arena's  
highlights. Most of the players stayed on the court as the arena 
darkened for the video, followed by a shower of confetti floating 
from the rafters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't hit you until right now. The video at the end made  
it more emotional,'' center Rik Smits said. ``I always enjoy that 
stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 16,000-seat Market Square Arena -- now a relic by NBA  
standards -- was built in 1974 for $24 million, which now seems like 
a bargain compared with the $175 million price tag on the new 
18,500-seat fieldhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pacers owners Mel and Herb Simon, millionaire shopping mall  
developers, began pushing city officials several years ago to build 
the new arena with corporate suites and club seating. They claimed 
the team was losing money without such facilities to attract fans 
and big corporate bucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction of the new fieldhouse, four blocks south of Market  
Square in downtown Indianapolis, began in July 1997. It will be 
inaugurated Nov. 6 with the Pacers' home opener against the Boston 
Celtics, coach Larry Bird's former team and the same club the 
Pacers faced in their NBA debut in 1976, two years after Market 
Square opened. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers' first home, when they still played in and dominated  
the old American Basketball Association, was the Coliseum at the 
State Fairgrounds from 1967-73. Crowds were sparse, but the Pacers' 
success, along with the increasing rivalry between the ABA and NBA, 
eventually led to the move downtown to the then-new Market Square 
Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The arena played to some notable firsts:  
</P>
<P>
	--The Pacers' first game in Market Square, an exhibition against  
the Milwaukee Bucks of the NBA, drew a capacity 16,929, double the 
attendance at their ABA regular-season opener against the San 
Antonio Spurs. Two years later, the Pacers, the Spurs, the New York 
Nets and the Denver Nuggets were absorbed by the older league, and 
Indiana's first NBA game in Market Square was a 129-122 overtime 
loss to the Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
	--Market Square Arena was the home of the Indianapolis Racers of  
the now-defunct World Hockey Association, and a teen-age Wayne 
Gretzky -- now in hockey's Hall of Fame -- made his pro debut as a 
member of the Racers in the arena in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mike Tyson also was a teen-ager when he first fought in  
Indianapolis in 1982 -- 10 years before he was convicted and sent to 
prison in Indiana for raping a Miss Black America pageant 
contestant. 
</P>
<P>
	--Two years later, Andre the Giant defeated Hulk Hogan for the  
World Wrestling Federation heavyweight title at Market Square Arena 
in the sport's first live prime-time network telecast since 1955. 
</P>
<P>
	--Jordan, who quit basketball and played one season of pro  
baseball, ended his retirement and scored 19 points in his comeback 
game against the Pacers at Market Square Arena in 1995. Indiana won 
103-96 in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The arena has seen more than just sports. Elvis' final concert  
was in Market Square Arena in 1977, two months before he died at 
42. And among the final events was an appearance in August by the 
Dalai Lama, who spoke at the start of a 12-day visit to Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, at the dawn of the millennium, the Pacers are headed to  
their new home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
