<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Probes Russian Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank is investigating allegations  
one of its former Washington-based Russian officials passed along 
inside information to a Russian bank that lost its license last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The former official, Leonid Grigoriev, has been placed on  
administrative leave by the Bureau of Economic Analysis in Moscow, 
a Moscow-based policy analysis institute he now heads, the bank 
said Friday. The institute is supported by a World Bank loan and 
the action against him was requested by the Russian government, the 
bank said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegations against Grigoriev, appointed by Russia to its World  
Bank mission from 1992 to 1997, were reported Friday in The Wall 
Street Journal. Bank spokesman Jan Pakulsky said the matter was 
brought to the bank's attention by the Journal when it asked for 
comment on the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal report cited documents indicating that Grigoriev  
provided Moscow-based Inkombank with tips on debt-marketing 
investments and acted as its liaison in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Inkombank, one of Russia's largest banks until it lost its  
license last year, has surfaced in U.S. investigators' examination 
of the Bank of New York, through which the Russian mob is believed 
to have funneled $10 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Russian banking authorities issued an audit linking  
Inkombank to criminal activity and recommending that its business 
be curtailed. The bank folded a year ago, claiming $1.5 billion in 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal reported that Grigoriev acknowledges assisting  
Inkombank while in Washington but denies providing confidential 
information or receiving regular payments. 
</P>
<P>
	While at the World Bank, Grigoriev served as alternative  
executive director for the Russian Federation office and later as 
an adviser to the executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	``In view of the recent chargers brought to the World Bank's  
attention, the bank has launched a full investigation as a matter 
of urgency'' to determine whether any action is warranted, the bank 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the bank had hired a law firm, Venable, Baetjer, Howard  
&AMP; Ciovilette, to help with the inquiry. The Russian office at the 
bank and the Russian government also were cooperating fully, it 
said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
