<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, AARP Talk About Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHUA, N.H. (AP) -- ``Flo,'' a feisty television commercial  
character who doesn't want the government to mess with her health 
plan, is no match for a New Hampshire woman of the same name, Vice 
President Al Gore said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting with members of AARP, the nation's largest lobbying  
group for older Americans, Gore criticized the ad, which features 
an elderly woman worrying about the Clinton administration's plan 
to add prescription drug coverage to Medicare. The advertisements 
are financed mainly by drug companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The facts in those commercials, just like that character, are  
fictional,'' said Gore, who is seeking the Democratic presidential 
nomination. ``Let me tell you about a real Flo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he met 88-year-old Florence Seitz of Raymond at a  
similar New Hampshire forum in June, and that she often takes half 
of her prescribed medication to save money. 
</P>
<P>
	``She makes hard choices about which prescriptions she is going  
to do without and which ones she is going to cut back on,'' Gore 
said. ``She feels she has to choose between her medication and her 
food and her rent. We shouldn't put seniors in that position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also highlighted his plan to make it easier for families to  
care for elderly relatives after hearing Joanne Farley describe the 
difficulties she and her husband have caring for her 82-year-old 
mother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	The Manchester woman said their biggest problem is affording  
respite care to give the couple a break. 
</P>
<P>
	``If my husband and I decide to go somewhere together it would  
cost us more than $1,600 a week to bring someone in,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said that, if elected, he would push for giving families  
tax credits to help pay for long-term care, and starting a national 
support network for families. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a crushing burden that is often invisible to the rest  
of the community because the people who shoulder the burden don't 
get out much,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oscar Serard, of Concord, told Gore about his grandson's  
struggle with diabetes and an intestinal disease. He said insurance 
companies have refused to pay for the most effective drug treatment 
doctors have found for the boy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason was there were other alternatives, but the other  
medications did not work,'' Serard said. He asked Gore how he would 
hold health maintenance organizations and insurance companies more 
accountable. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he supports federal legislation giving patients new  
rights in dealing with HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Tornow, a registered Republican from Merrimack, said he  
was impressed with Gore enough to switch parties and vote for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here today to see how boring you could be, and I'm  
thoroughly disappointed,'' he told Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in Washington, Gore thanked the National Association of  
Police Organizations for the role its members have played in 
helping to reduce crime nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	And, without naming names, he said those who allow criminals to  
have firearms more powerful than the police could be found close to 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm certainly not satisfied with the political culture in  
Washington that puts the interests of the gun lobby ahead of the 
needs of American law enforcement,'' Gore said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
