<HEADLINE> Penn St. Wrestlers Charged in Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Two Penn State wrestlers were charged  
with rape and related offenses and suspended indefinitely from all 
wrestling activities pending the outcome of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel Parker, 20, and Jean Celestin, 20, both of Park Avenue  
in State College, were arraigned Thursday on charges of rape, 
involuntary deviate sexual intercourse, sexual assault and indecent 
assault of an 18-year-old woman in August. Each was released on 
$25,000 bail pending a preliminary hearing Oct. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, the two could face up to 20 years in jail for each  
felony count of rape, up to 10 years for sexual assault, and two 
years for indecent assault. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish to let the legal process run its course before making  
any final judgments, but we will not tolerate this kind of 
conduct,'' said wrestling coach Troy Sunderland. ``Should the 
charges be substantiated, we will dismiss the offending parties 
from the wrestling team and from any association with the 
program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to court documents, Parker and the alleged victim met  
for a date Aug. 20 at the Silver Screen Bar, then went to his 
apartment, where the assaults took place. The victim told police 
about the alleged incident on Oct. 13 after she had several 
arguments with Parker on the telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 15, police wiretapped a conversation between the victim  
and Parker, who allegedly told her that Celestin, his roommate, 
also had sex with her that night, the Centre Daily Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker, a sophomore from Chesapeake, Va., started for the team  
last year after he claimed the 1998 Virginia state championship at 
125 pounds. Celestin, a junior from Miami, was a spot starter at 
149 pounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
