<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arts May Improve Students' Grade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If your teen-agers want to be in the high  
school band or drama club, let them. It may improve their grades. 
</P>
<P>
	High school students who take music lessons and join theater  
groups do better in math, reading, history, geography and 
citizenship, according to a study of Education Department data to 
be published today. 
</P>
<P>
	``If young Americans are to succeed and to contribute to what  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan describes as our 'economy 
of ideas,' they will need an education that develops imaginative, 
flexible and tough-minded thinking,'' Education Secretary Richard 
Riley said in a message accompanying the study. ``The arts 
powerfully nurture the ability to think in this manner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study, which tracked more than 25,000 students for more than  
10 years, found that students who reported consistently high levels 
of involvement with instrumental music scored significantly higher 
on math tests by the 12th grade. 
</P>
<P>
	This observation held true for students regardless of their  
parents' income, occupations and levels of education, said James S. 
Catterall, the lead author and an education professor at the 
University of California, Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	While 38.6 percent of higher-income students who were uninvolved  
in music scored high in math, 48 percent of those highly interested 
in music received the high marks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kids who are more advantaged tend to be more involved in the  
arts. Period. They have more opportunities and you'd expect them to 
do better,'' Catterall said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	But the influence of music was far more pronounced among  
lower-income students. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the lower-income students without music involvement, only  
15.5 percent achieved high math scores. But of the musically 
oriented group, more than twice as many excelled in math. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a matter of economic advantage. It's a matter of  
something happening with the arts for the kids,'' Catterall said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found that as students progress through high  
school they are less likely to be involved in the arts. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a clear trend,'' Catterall said. ``Kids participation  
in the arts declines. It may be that high schools offer fewer 
programs than middle schools or that kids are more concerned with 
academics or admissions to college.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than 3 percent of seniors take out-of-school classes in  
music, art or dance, compared with more than 11 percent of 
sophomores. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the ``high-involvement'' seniors are found in  
top levels on standardized tests, compared with fewer than 43 
percent of the ``low-involvement'' seniors. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also indicated arts study affected students' racial  
attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Students at grade 10 were asked if it was OK to make a racist  
remark,'' the authors wrote. ``About 40 percent 'no-drama' students 
felt that making such a remark would be OK, where only about 12 
percent of high theater students thought the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the 12th graders involved in plays were compared to their  
uninvolved counterparts, 20 percent more of those active in drama 
had excellent reading skills. 
</P>
<P>
	Catterall noted that the work supports strong suggestions, but  
is not definitive. 
</P>
<P>
	This study was one of seven included in ``Champions of Change --  
The Impact of the Arts on Learning,'' by Edward B. Fiske, former 
education editor of The New York Times. The project was sponsored 
by the GE (General Electric) Fund and the John D. and Catherine T. 
MacArthur Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press Writer David Ho contributed to this story.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings' Doleman Hopes for Breakout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Chris Doleman had 15 sacks for the  
San Francisco 49ers last season but hasn't gotten his hands on a 
quarterback since coming out of retirement and joining the 
Minnesota Vikings a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci, whose team will face the  
Vikings at the Metrodome on Sunday, knows better than to dismiss 
Doleman as washed up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of Chris. He and I had a good relationship here.  
I was sorry to see him go and he's still a good football player. 
He's managed to stay healthy for a long career, and that's very 
unusual and that's why he's one of the all-time sack leaders,'' 
Mariucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	``So, we know where he is, along with some of their other  
defensive linemen, which is a good defensive line, with John 
Randle, of course, Jerry Ball and Tony Williams. They're something 
to be reckoned with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vikings defensive line coach Andre Patterson said Doleman, who  
started at right defensive end and played nearly 60 snaps last week 
at Detroit, is getting close to a breakout game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's gotten better every week,'' Patterson said.  
``He's playing the run really well and in the pass rush he's 
starting to get into the groove. The pass rush is like hitting, you 
know, training camp in baseball, the pitchers are always ahead of 
the hitters because you have to get into the groove. And the pass 
rushing's the same way. And you can see that starting to come, you 
can see that groove. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's getting ready to break through.''  
</P>
<P>
	Doleman said it's no surprise he's sackless.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough coming in at midstream when you missed training  
camp,'' he said. ``When I'm out there on the field, everything I 
get each week is always new, so you can't just go out and just cut 
it loose as if you've known this stuff for years. It's a matter of 
time before those things start to come. The other thing is the 
conditioning factor, I feel that's coming along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doleman agreed he's about to turn the corner.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel myself getting closer to the quarterback,'' he said.  
``When you get hits on the quarterback and you get hurries on the 
quarterback, it's just a matter of time before you get him on the 
ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's exactly what I'm talking about,'' Patterson said. ``He  
had two really good rushes on Sunday but they happened to be on 
quick passes. So, he beat the guy at the line but the pass was off 
so fast he couldn't get back there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Doleman and return of Ball, a nose tackle who  
recently rejoined the Vikings in a trade with the Cleveland Browns 
for third-year end Stalin Colinet, has solidified the Vikings' 
defensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good combination to have Jerry and Chris. One guy's  
been in the league 13 years, one 15, plus Joe Phillips is 14 
years,'' Patterson said. ``I went from a real young group to a very 
experienced group with a lot of knowledge and I think that really 
helps us out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not only taken pressure off a suspect secondary and a  
banged up linebacker corps but it's also allowed Randle to move 
from under tackle, where he was effectively double teamed, to 
defensive end, where he can get to the quarterback more easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Doleman said he wasn't particularly eager to face his former  
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to get back on the field. After last week's game,  
I'm looking forward to just trying to get this thing going,'' 
Doleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings are 2-4 and have turned the offense over to Jeff  
George. The 49ers are 3-3 and seeking to avoid their first 
three-game losing streak since 1980. They're led by backup Jeff 
Garcia, with Steve Young out with concussion problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're still a great football team. These guys are  
fighters,'' Doleman said. ``I know the guys on the team, they're 
all fighters, I'm sure they're a little frustrated too, as we 
are.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 09:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hei-Kyung Hong Was Born to Sing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Soprano Hei-Kyung Hong walks past long tables  
holding bolts of fabric, and racks of costumes and shelves holding 
plastic boxes of buttons, gold braid and frog fasteners. 
</P>
<P>
	She's in her workplace, the Metropolitan Opera, on her way to  
costume fittings for her first singing of the Countess in Mozart's 
``The Marriage of Figaro'' on Oct. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	She says hello to the women who sit at sewing machines, and they  
in turn greet her. One seamstress follows her to the dressing room 
and Hong, a size 8, says she thinks her voice might be better if 
she weighed more. The seamstress says she doesn't see how Hong's 
voice could be better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hei-Kyung Hong has one of the loveliest natural lyric soprano  
voices of today, which she uses with great intelligence and 
musicality,'' says tenor Placido Domingo, who sang a duet concert 
with Hong in Seoul, Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	``With her physical beauty and unaffected acting ability she is  
a total performer. I am very happy that she will sing Cleopatra in 
Handel's `Giulio Cesare' for us at the Washington Opera this 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though she never seems flamboyant, Hong is a favorite of  
audiences, colleagues and critics. 
</P>
<P>
	During the summer, she sang Mimi in ``La Boheme'' for an  
estimated 35,000 people in Central Park for the Met. Hong turns 
down many overseas engagements because she likes to sing where she 
can drive herself to and from home. Last summer she negotiated with 
the Rome Opera to arrive later than requested to sing Liu in 
``Turandot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's because family life is very important to the Korean  
soprano, who lives on Long Island in Bay Shore, with her husband, 
two teen-age daughters and 5-year-old son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be one more day away than I have to,'' she  
says. ``When the girls were little, I had to feed them, clothe 
them, drive them places. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need to be home even more now. Every experience is a venture  
into their emotional beings. They're still learning, still 
changing. Mother has to be there to be the pillar, the reliable 
person who is the sounding board for them to come to, to say this 
and that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Hong was growing up in Seoul, her mother encouraged her to  
entertain guests and enter contests. 
</P>
<P>
	``She praised me so, I wanted to do it,'' Hong says. ``In my  
career, that has been the basic fuel, that I was praised from an 
early age. I believe this is very important in raising children; 
they need to be praised about their reading or gardening or setting 
the table or tying shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one golden treasure that I learned from my mother.''  
</P>
<P>
	When she was in junior high school, Hong's mother sent her to Ye  
Won, Seoul's music conservatory. Teachers there said she should go 
to Italy or the Juilliard School in New York City. So she came here 
to audition and was awarded a full scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong was 15, alone and didn't speak English. ``A very loving  
American family took me in, in Westfield, N.J. The first year or 
two were undoubtedly the most difficult time in my life. Just to 
finish homework I would stay up till 2 or 3 in the morning,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm glad I came early. I was able to learn the language  
more quickly and adapt more than if I came after college or once my 
profession started. On Saturdays I went to Juilliard. That was the 
fun time. I got to study voice, sing and play piano.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When she was old enough to attend Juilliard full time, she was  
given light soprano roles in opera productions. 
</P>
<P>
	After graduation, she took the latest in what she calls a  
succession of good advice and entered the 1982 Met Auditions for 
Young Singers. She became one of 11 evenly ranked winners. The 
competition didn't worry her. ``I've done so many competitions. 
Getting to perform on the stage was so much fun. I felt right at 
home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The night before Hong's finalists' performance, she and Kim S.  
Hahn got engaged. ``My husband has a very humorous timing of 
things,'' she says. ``He gave me a ring. I didn't know if I was 
more excited about my ring or the stage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her Met debut was in 1984 in Mozart's ``La Clemenza di Tito''  
and she has sung at the Met every season since, often in Mozart 
operas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember Hei-Kyung when she first came to us, in 1984, in  
`La Clemenza di Tito,''' Jonathan Friend, Metropolitan Opera 
artistic administrator, recalled. ``She had then a really special 
timbre to her voice. What is so wonderful to have witnessed in the 
last 15 years is how the voice has grown and yet maintained the 
purity that it had back then. 
</P>
<P>
	``The audiences always react very positively to her and when she  
sings a role like Mimi or Liu we all feel that she is one of the 
major artists of the day in this repertoire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Met dressing room, Hong tries on one of the Countess'  
silk, bustled skirts. ``This is so gorgeous, I don't need anything 
on top. I'm going to go out like this,'' she declares. Regina, the 
costume fitter, giggles. 
</P>
<P>
	She dons an unfinished blue bodice the Countess will wear in Act  
3. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing Strauss' `Daphne' in Munich,'' Hong says. Regina  
repins a ruffle to the sleeve, to make it comfortable at the 
singer's elbow. ``I think it is fitting my voice quite well. I'm 
excited about that,'' she says. ``I should be doing more Strauss; 
it goes with the color of my voice. It has the beautiful legato I 
love and a high tessitura.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hong and Jennifer Larmore sing the ``Presentation of the Rose''  
duet from ``Der Rosenkavalier'' on ``Beautiful Opera Duets,'' a new 
Teldec CD. Hong has never been asked to sing Sophie on stage. ``I 
think they want a Scandinavian look, blonde with a porcelain 
complexion,'' Hong says. 
</P>
<P>
	She steps out of the dressing room and looks in a tall mirror.  
Two men look up from cutting fabric and give her a thumbs up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Singers love to talk about the voice, how to produce it, how  
to support it, how to breathe,'' she says. ``That bores me. I want 
to talk about the person. What kind of life they had, how many 
children, what they love, what makes them fill with emotions. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``I love to sing. I was born to sing. It's the career I've  
chosen. ... My concern is my family and my singing. I want to do my 
best and be worthy of the people buying tickets and taking the time 
to come. They expect a great performance and hopefully I provide 
that. If I don't do it, I'm not doing my job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991022.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Post Earns $59.7M in 3Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Post Co. reported a 17 percent  
increase in profits Friday, saying earnings were helped by boosted 
advertising revenue at its flagship newspaper and at Newsweek 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings rose to $59.7 million, or $5.90 a share, for the third  
quarter ended Oct. 3, from $50.9 million, or $5.00 a share, for the 
same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The results did not include a one-time charge this year of $8  
million in startup costs for BrassRing, Inc., a job search and 
recruiting service owned by the company. They also omit a one-time 
1998 gain of $30.9 million resulting from the Washington Post's 
sale of 14 small cable business and stock in the Internet commerce 
company Junglee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post's earnings beat the $5.61-a-share  
expectation of analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues increased 6 percent to $539.6 million from $509.3  
million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post credited the increased earnings to higher  
subscriber revenues from its cable television division and a 24 
percent drop in its cost for newsprint and an increase in the 
company's pension credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the company said those gains were tempered by increased  
spending on the paper's Internet operations and decreased revenue 
from advertising in its broadcasting division. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, the Washington Post  
reported a 9 percent increase in net income to $172.8 million, or 
$16.97 per share, from $159.1 million, or $15.67 per share in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Those figures don't include the 1999 charge for BrassRing, or a  
total gain of $194.4 million in 1998, when the Washington Post sold 
shares in Cowles Media company in addition to its interests in 
Junglee and the cable companies. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months, revenue was up 6 percent to $1.62  
billion from $1.52 billion the year before. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
